{"title_page": "Bill de Blasio", "text_new": "{{redirect|de Blasio|others with the name|de Blasio (surname)}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Bill Blasio\n| office = 109th [[Mayor of New York City]]\n| image = Bill de Blasio by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| predecessor = [[Michael Bloomberg]]\n| deputy = [[Anthony Shorris]]<br />[[Dean Fuleihan]]\n| signature = Bill de Blasio Signature.png\n| office2 = Member of the [[New York City Council]]<br>from the 39th district\n| predecessor2 = [[Stephen DiBrienza]]\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| office1 = 3rd [[New York City Public Advocate|Public Advocate of New York City]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Betsy Gotbaum]]\n| successor1 = [[Letitia James]]\n| successor2 = [[Brad Lander]]\n| birth_name = Warren Wilhelm Jr.\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1961|5|8}}\n| birth_place = [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.<!-- As per WP:LINKDIRECT and Template:infobox person, birthplace indicates city, state, then country. No need to spell out \"United States; 'U.S.' is fine. -->\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Chirlane McCray]]|1994}}\n| children = 2\n| residence = [[Gracie Mansion]] (Official)\n| website = {{url|nyc.gov/mayor}} (government)<br>{{url|billdeblasio.com}} (personal)\n| term_start = January 1, 2014\n| term_end = \n| term_start1 = January 1, 2010\n| term_end1 = December 31, 2013\n| term_start2 = January 1, 2002\n| term_end2 = December 31, 2009\n| education = [[New York University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Columbia University]] ([[Master of International Affairs|MIA]])\n}}\n'''Bill Blasio''' ({{IPAc-en|d|\u026a|\u02c8|b|l|\u0251\u02d0|z|i|o\u028a}}; born '''Warren Wilhelm Jr.'''; May 8, 1961) is an American politician who has served as the [[Mayor of New York City|109th mayor]] of [[New York City]] since 2014. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he was New York City's [[New York City Public Advocate|public advocate]] from 2010 to 2013.<!-- The lack of citations is purposeful. Refer to Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Lead section#Citations for more information. Wikipedia allows there to be little to no citations in the lead area if it is cited within the main body. If there is something in the lede not cited in the main part drop a {{not found in body}} citation needed tag and it will be addressed. -->\n\nBorn in [[Manhattan]] and raised in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], de Blasio graduated from [[New York University]] and [[Columbia University]] before a brief stint as a [[campaign manager]] for [[Charles Rangel]] and [[Hillary Clinton]]. He started his career as an elected official on the [[New York City Council]], representing the 39th district in [[Brooklyn]] from 2002 to 2009. After serving one term as public advocate, he was elected [[mayor of New York City]] in [[2013 New York City mayoral election|2013]] and reelected in [[2017 New York City mayoral election|2017]].\n\nDe Blasio's policy initiatives have included new [[de-escalation]] training for officers, reduced prosecutions for [[Legality of cannabis|cannabis possession]], implementation of police [[Body worn video|body cameras]], and ending the post-[[September 11 attacks|9/11]] surveillance program of Muslim residents. In his first term, he implemented free universal [[Pre-kindergarten|Pre-K]] in the city. De Blasio has called attention to what he calls stark economic inequality in New York City, which he described as a \"[[A Tale of Two Cities|tale of two cities]]\" during his first campaign. He has supported [[Social liberalism|socially liberal]] and [[Progressive Era|progressive]] policies in regard to [[Economy of New York City|the city's economy]], urban planning, public education, police relations, and [[privatization]].\n\nDe Blasio [[Bill de Blasio 2020 presidential campaign|ran]] in the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|Democratic primaries]] for the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 presidential election]]. After registering low poll numbers and failing to qualify for the third round of primary debates, he suspended his campaign on September 20, 2019, and endorsed [[Bernie Sanders]] five months later.\n\n== Early life, family, and education ==\n[[File:Sant'Agata de'Goti (Benevento).jpg|thumb|Bill de Blasio's maternal grandfather came from the Italian city of [[Sant'Agata de' Goti]].]]\nBill de Blasio was born on May 8, 1961, in [[Manhattan]]'s [[Doctors Hospital (Manhattan)|Doctors Hospital]].<ref name=\"NY Daily News\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/25-facts-new-nyc-mayor-de-blasio-article-1.1563171|title=25 facts about new NYC Mayor de Blasio|work=NY Daily News|access-date=2018-03-04|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/11/06/nyregion/06deblasio-milestones-timeline.html|title=Milestones: Bill de Blasio|last=Corasaniti|first=Nick|website=nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> He is the third son of Maria Angela ({{nee|de Blasio}}; 1917\u20132007) and Warren Wilhelm (1917\u20131979).<ref name=\"nameref1\">{{cite news|author=Dan Janison|first=|url=https://www.newsday.com/long-island/columnists/dan-janison/a-refresher-on-candidate-bill-de-blasio-1.5910726|title=A refresher on candidate Bill de Blasio|date=August 17, 2013|work=[[Newsday]]|accessdate=September 20, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Born Warren Wilhelm Jr., he changed his name to Warren de Blasio-Wilhelm in 1983 and finally to Bill de Blasio in 2001 to honor his [[Mother|maternal family]].<ref name=\"name\">{{cite news|author=Greg Smith|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/election/de-blasio-names-de-blasio-article-1.1463591|title=Mayoral Hopeful Bill de Blasio Has Had Three Different Legal Names, Court Records Show|date=September 22, 2013|work=[[New York Daily News]]}}</ref><ref name=\"wolper\">{{cite news|url=http://www.prx.org/pieces/81520-bill-de-blasio-and-allan-wolper|title=Conversations with Allan Wolper: Bill de Blasio|author=Allan Wolper|accessdate=January 21, 2012|publisher=[[Public Radio Exchange]]|agency=[[WBGO]]}}</ref> De Blasio has two older brothers, Steven and Donald.<ref name=\"NY Daily News\"/> His mother was of [[Italian American|Italian]] heritage, and his father was of [[German American|German]], English, French, and Scots-Irish ancestry.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=7W4sDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA27&dq=%22of+mixed+German,+English,+French,+and+Scotch-Irish+heritage%22|title=The Pragmatist: Bill de Blasio's Quest to Save the Soul of New York|first=Joseph P.|last=Viteritti|date=May 31, 2019|publisher=Oxford University Press|via=Google Books|isbn=9780190679507}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/johncassidy/2013/08/bill-de-plasios-moment-can-he-handle-it.html|title=Bill de Blasio's Moment: Can He Handle It?|author=John Cassidy|date=August 14, 2013|work=[[The New Yorker]]|accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0DEFD71F3AF93BA15752C0A9619C8B63|title=Paid Notice: Deaths: WILHELM, MARIA (NEE DE BLASIO)|date=January 28, 2007|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref> His paternal grandparents were Donald Wilhelm, of Ohio, and Nina (n\u00e9e Warren), of [[Iowa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/between-wwii-and-his-suicide-de-blasios-father-cold-warrior/|title=Between WWII and His Suicide, de Blasio's Father a Cold Warrior - WNYC - New York Public Radio, Podcasts, Live Streaming Radio, News|website=WNYC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clarindaherald.com/news/local/presidential-candidate-explores-family-ties-in-blanchard/article_a2a31ae2-bd37-11e9-8506-cbae64565e64.html|title=Presidential candidate explores family ties in Blanchard|last=Publisher|first=John Van Nostrand|website=Clarinda Herald-Journal - Clarinda, Iowa|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> His maternal grandfather, Giovanni, was from [[Sant'Agata de' Goti]], [[Province of Benevento|Benevento]], and his grandmother, Anna (n\u00e9e Briganti), was from [[Grassano]], [[Province of Matera|Matera]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ansa.it/web/notizie/regioni/basilicata/2013/11/05/Voto-New-York-Grassano-De-Blasio_9571916.html|title=Voto a New York: Grassano per De Blasio|date=November 5, 2013|publisher=[[Agenzia Nazionale Stampa Associata]]|language=Italian|accessdate=January 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.italymagazine.com/news/santagata-de-goti-gives-new-york-mayor-bill-de-blasio-honorary-citizenship|title=Sant'Agata de' Goti Gives New York Mayor Bill de Blasio Honorary Citizenship|website=ITALY Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> His paternal uncle, Donald George Wilhelm Jr., worked for the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] in Iran and secretly wrote the last Shah of Iran, [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]]'s, memoir.<ref name=\"democracynownewlydeclassifieddocuments\">{{cite news|url=https://www.democracynow.org/2017/7/24/newly_declassified_documents_confirm_us_backed|title=Newly Declassified Documents Confirm U.S. Backed 1953 Coup in Iran Over Oil Contracts|date=July 24, 2017|work=Democracy Now!|accessdate=July 29, 2017|quote=JUAN GONZ\u00c1LEZ: I'm just wondering if, in the documents\u2014we've got about 30 seconds\u2014you can across the name of Donald Wilhelm at all, who was a CIA guy who went to Iran after, after the overthrow of Mosaddegh, and who was actually the mayor's\u2014Mayor Bill de Blasio's uncle? ERVAND ABRAHAMIAN: Yeah, he actually co-ghostwrote the shah's memoirs.}}</ref>\n\nHis mother, Maria de Blasio, attended [[Smith College]], served in the [[Office of War Information]] during [[World War II]] and authored ''The Other Italy: The Italian Resistance in World War II'' (1988).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0DEFD71F3AF93BA15752C0A9619C8B63|title=Paid Notice \u2013 Deaths WILHELM, MARIA (NEE DE BLASIO)|work=The New York Times\"}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/election/ryrtyrt-article-1.1477493|title=De Blasio had the makings of a politician well before he even moved to New York|last=Fermino|first=Jennifer|website=nydailynews.com|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> His father, a [[Yale University]] graduate, worked as a contributing editor at ''[[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine]]'' and also served in World War II. In 1942, he enlisted in the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] and was sent to the [[Pacific War]]. During the 82-day [[Battle of Okinawa]], a grenade detonated below his left foot, and his leg was later amputated below the knee. After receiving a [[Purple Heart]], he married Maria in 1945, and became a budget analyst for the federal government. During the 1950s, at the height of the [[Red Scare]], both Maria and Warren were accused of having a \"sympathetic interest in [[Communism]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Storrs|first=Landon R. Y.|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/archive/bill-de-blasio-not-afraid-red-scare-ghosts/|title=Bill de Blasio Is Not Afraid of Red Scare Ghosts|date=2013-10-30|access-date=2020-02-14|language=en-US|issn=0027-8378}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |last1=Hern\u00e1ndez |first1=Javier C. |title=From His Father's Decline, de Blasio 'Learned What Not to Do' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/14/nyregion/from-his-fathers-decline-de-blasio-learned-what-not-to-do.html?src=twr&pagewanted=all |accessdate=18 November 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966, the family moved to Cambridge, Massachusetts, where de Blasio began kindergarten.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2013/09/29/bill-deblasio-soars-from-cambridge-roots-new-york-city-mayor-race/Hvug4jhc9vLFxhrWbCH0DM/story.html|title=Bill deBlasio soars from Cambridge roots to New York City's mayor's race - The Boston Globe|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/election/article231646338.html|title=Democratic presidential candidate Bill de Blasio ended his campaign. Who is he?|last=|first=|date=June 25, 2019|website=Miami Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Bill and his brother Donald were then raised by Maria and her extended family. Of his early childhood, de Blasio said, \"my mother and father broke up very early on in the time I came along, and I was brought up by my mother's family\u2014that's the bottom line\u2014the de Blasio family.\"<ref name=\"wolper\" /> His father committed suicide while suffering from incurable [[lung cancer]] when Bill was 18.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/exclusive-bill-de-blasio-speaks-wnyc-about-his-fathers-suicide/|title=WNYC News Exclusive: Bill de Blasio Speaks with WNYC About His Father's Suicide|author=Anna Sale|date=September 30, 2013|accessdate=October 1, 2013|publisher=[[New York Public Radio]]}}</ref> In 1979, De Blasio graduated from [[Cambridge Rindge and Latin School]], where he served in student government and was known to peers as \"Senator Provolone\".{{Efn|His nickname came from his \"twin penchants for politics and [[Italian sandwich]]es\". De Blasio recalled it as a \"a well-meaning taunt\" that spoke to his \"overt Italian pride\" and interest in politics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://observer.com/2013/09/senator-provolone-doubles-down-on-pre-k-message/|title='Senator Provolone' Doubles Down on Pre-K Message|date=2013-09-30|work=Observer|access-date=2018-03-04|language=en-US}}</ref>}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2013/09/29/bill-deblasio-soars-from-cambridge-roots-new-york-city-mayor-race/Hvug4jhc9vLFxhrWbCH0DM/story.html|title=NYC mayoral favorite Bill de Blasio has Mass. roots - The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> He received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] from [[New York University]] in metropolitan studies, a program in [[urban studies]], and a [[Master of International Affairs]] from [[Columbia University]]'s [[School of International and Public Affairs]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ny1.com/content/politics/special_report_the_contenders/190506/the-contenders--de-blasio-s-activism-grew-upon-arrival-in-the-city|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140926023840/http://www.ny1.com/content/politics/special_report_the_contenders/190506/the-contenders--de-blasio-s-activism-grew-upon-arrival-in-the-city|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 26, 2014|title=The Contenders: De Blasio's Activism Grew Upon Arrival In The City|date=October 15, 2013|accessdate=September 25, 2014|work=[[NY1]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nyunews.com/opinion/offthird/2019/10/29/bill-de-blasio-king-of-new-york-satire-nyu|title=Off-Third: Happy Alumni Weekend From Bill de Blasio {{!}} Washington Square News|last=Hofstetter|first=Abby|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/bill-de-blasio-nyc-mayor-announces-presidential-bid|title=Bill de Blasio, NYC mayor, announces presidential bid|date=2019-05-16|website=PBS NewsHour|language=en-us|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> He is a 1981 [[Harry S. Truman Scholarship|Harry S. Truman Scholar]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.truman.gov/sites/default/files/Truman%20Annual%20Report%202012.pdf | title=The 2012 Annual Report of the Harry S. Truman Scholarship Foundation | publisher=The Harry S. Truman Scholarship Foundation | accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Early career ==\nIn 1984, de Blasio worked for the Urban Fellows Program at the [[New York City Department of Juvenile Justice]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/new-york-city-public-advocate-bill-de-blasio-article-1.1303401 | title=New York City Public Advocate Bill de Blasio | work=[[New York Daily News]] | date=March 30, 2013 | accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimesleftist\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/23/nyregion/a-mayoral-hopeful-now-de-blasio-was-once-a-young-leftist.html | title=A Mayoral Hopeful Now, de Blasio Was Once a Young Leftist | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=September 22, 2013 | accessdate=September 24, 2013 | author=Javier C. Hern\u00e1ndez}}</ref> In 1987, shortly after completing graduate school at Columbia, de Blasio was hired to work as a political organizer by the [[Quixote Center]] in [[Maryland]]. In 1988, he traveled with the Quixote Center to [[Nicaragua]] for 10 days to help distribute food and medicine during the [[Nicaraguan Revolution]]. De Blasio was an ardent supporter of the ruling [[Socialism|socialist]] government, the [[Sandinista National Liberation Front]], which was opposed by the [[Foreign policy of the Ronald Reagan administration#Nicaragua|Reagan administration]] at the time.<ref name=\"nytimesleftist\" /> After returning from Nicaragua, de Blasio moved to New York City, where he worked for a [[nonprofit organization]] focused on improving health care in Central America.<ref name=\"nytimesleftist\" /> He continued to support the Sandinistas in his spare time and joined a group called the Nicaragua Solidarity Network of Greater New York, which held meetings and fundraisers for the Sandinista political party.<ref name=\"nytimesleftist\" /> De Blasio's introduction to city politics came in 1989, when he worked as a volunteer coordinator for [[David Dinkins]]' [[New York City mayoral elections#1989|mayoral campaign]].<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/12/06/bill-de-blasio-for-nyc-mayor_n_2251023.html | title=Bill de Blasio For NYC Mayor: Can The Public Advocate Go From Master Strategist To Mister Mayor? | work=[[The New York Observer]] | date=December 6, 2012 | accessdate=August 13, 2013 | author=Colin Campbell}}</ref> Following the campaign, de Blasio was an aide in [[New York City Hall|City Hall]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/new-york-news/political-education-bill-de-blasio | title=The Political Education Of Bill de Blasio | work=[[The Jewish Week]] | date=July 17, 2013 | accessdate=August 13, 2013 | author=Adam Dickter | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821204142/http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/new-york-news/political-education-bill-de-blasio | archivedate=August 21, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> In 1990, he described himself as an advocate for [[democratic socialism]] when asked about his goals for society.<ref name=\"nytimesleftist\" />\n\nU.S. Representative [[Charles Rangel]] tapped de Blasio to be his campaign manager for his successful [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1994#New York|1994]] reelection bid.<ref>{{cite news|author=Catalina Camia|title=Charlie Rangel's rival endorsed by 'New York Times'|url=http://onpolitics.usatoday.com/2014/06/19/rangel-endorsement-espaillat-new-york-times/|accessdate=June 20, 2014|work=[[USA Today]]|date=June 19, 2014}}</ref> In 1997, he was appointed to serve as the regional director for the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development]] (HUD) for New York and New Jersey under the administration of President [[Bill Clinton]]. As the tri-state region's highest-ranking HUD official, de Blasio led a small executive staff and took part in outreach to residents of substandard housing.<ref>{{cite news|author=James Warren|title=De Blasio's Early Audition|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/opinion/de-blasio-early-audition-article-1.1496691|accessdate=November 6, 2013|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=October 27, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.citylimits.org/content/articles/viewarticle.cfm?article_id=2174 | title=Dream Off? | work=City Limits | date=April 1, 2001 | author=Matt Pacenzat | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071108050422/http://www.citylimits.org/content/articles/viewarticle.cfm?article_id=2174 | archivedate=November 8, 2007 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 1999, he was elected to be a school board member for Brooklyn School District 15.<ref name=\"pubad\">{{cite web|url=http://archive.advocate.nyc.gov/about-bill-de-blasio|title=About Bill De Blasio|work=Office of the Public Advocate|accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref> The following year, he served as campaign manager for [[Hillary Clinton]]'s successful [[United States Senate election in New York, 2000|United States Senate bid]].<ref name=\"pubad\" />\n\n==New York City Council (2002\u20132009)==\n\n===Elections===\n[[File:CityCouncilChambersAT.jpg|thumb|The [[New York City Council]] chambers, where de Blasio served from 2002 to 2009.]]\nIn 2001, de Blasio ran for the [[New York City Council]]'s 39th district, which includes the [[Brooklyn]] neighborhoods of [[Borough Park, Brooklyn|Borough Park]], [[Carroll Gardens, Brooklyn|Carroll Gardens]], [[Cobble Hill, Brooklyn|Cobble Hill]], [[Gowanus, Brooklyn|Gowanus]], [[Kensington, Brooklyn|Kensington]], [[Park Slope]], and [[Windsor Terrace, Brooklyn|Windsor Terrace]]. He won the crowded primary election with 32% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=555974 | title=NYC Council 39 \u2013 D Primary Race \u2013 September 25, 2001 | publisher=Our Campaigns | accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref> In the general election, he defeated Republican Robert A. Bell, 71% to 17%.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=86146 | title=New York City Council 39 Race \u2013 November 6, 2001 | publisher=Our Campaigns | accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref> He was reelected with 72% of the vote in 2002<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=84491 | title=New York City Council 39 Race \u2013 November 4, 2003 | publisher=Our Campaigns | accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref> and with 83% of the vote in 2005.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=318808 | title=New York City Council 39 Race \u2013 November 8, 2005 | publisher=Our Campaigns | accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nOn the City Council, de Blasio passed legislation to prevent landlord discrimination against tenants who hold federal housing subsidy vouchers, and helped pass the HIV/AIDS Housing Services Law, improving housing services for low-income New Yorkers living with HIV/AIDS.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=446983&GUID=0F78AE65-DC68-4CDC-AD40-1F8CC8B5B0C9 | title=Filing, on behalf of the Council, an amicus brief in support of the plaintiffs in the litigation between individual tenants and landlords captioned Rosario v. Diagonal Realty LLC. (Res 0803-2007) | publisher=New York City Council Legislative Research Center |accessdate=January 21, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=443560&GUID=56C7EA40-5F32-4346-B499-631BBE0D8377 | title=Processing of applications for permanent housing for clients of the HIV and AIDS Services Administration. (Int 0535-2005) | publisher=New York City Council Legislative Research Center | accessdate=January 21, 2013}}</ref> As head of the city council's General Welfare Committee, de Blasio helped pass the Gender-Based Discrimination Protection Law to protect transgender New Yorkers, and passed the Domestic Partnership Recognition Law to ensure that same-sex couples in a legal partnership could enjoy the same legal benefits as heterosexual couples in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=446726&GUID=68E087CC-2147-401A-983B-461A37265048 | title=Domestic Partnerships. (Int 0501-2007) | publisher=New York City Council Legislative Research Center | accessdate=January 20, 2013}}</ref> During his tenure, the General Welfare Committee also passed the Benefits Translation for Immigrants Law, which helped non-English speakers receive free language-assistance services when accessing government programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=437168&GUID=482D9A0F-EB57-4D84-BFEA-B49CF178E778| title=Provision of language assistance services. (Int 0038-2002) | publisher=New York City Council Legislative Research Center | accessdate=January 21, 2013}}</ref> He served on the education, [[environmental protection]], finance, and technology committees and chaired the [[Common good|general welfare]] committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/DepartmentDetail.aspx?ID=6903&GUID=5D939F6A-A26A-456C-BF68-2FE3903139C8&R=b270048d-b10a-40de-9b4a-05cab0cf8ea4 |publisher=[[The New York City Council]]  |title=Committee on Education}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/DepartmentDetail.aspx?ID=6904&GUID=F70A0DA9-3E66-4BE2-A777-8F8BE6F41E5D |publisher=[[The New York City Council]]  |title=Committee on Environmental Protection}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/DepartmentDetail.aspx?ID=6905&GUID=0D8F5FED-57D4-42FA-AA98-0F26D09E7158&R=c81924e4-f514-4ef6-9bda-777433fbefff|publisher=[[The New York City Council]]  |title=Committee on Finance}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/DepartmentDetail.aspx?ID=6906&GUID=3A095E28-DEC4-4B6A-A2A3-E5C95F87200D |publisher=[[The New York City Council]]  |title=Committee on General Welfare}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/DepartmentDetail.aspx?ID=8866&GUID=72EEA817-E6FF-4051-B853-BC1DAD04E8CC&R=0f5cb7f0-ac18-4302-8bb5-319f698d4fca|publisher=[[The New York City Council]]  |title=Committee on Technology}}</ref>\n\n==New York City Public Advocate (2010\u20132013)==\n\n===2009 election===\n{{Main|2009 New York City Public Advocate election}}{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| width = \n| image1 = Bill de Blasio Inauguration.jpg\n| width1 = 220\n| caption1 = De Blasio speaking at his January 2010 inauguration\n| image2 = Bill de Blasio & Avigdor Lieberman.jpg\n| width2 = 220\n| caption2 = Bill de Blasio and Israeli Foreign Minister [[Avigdor Lieberman]] in 2012\n}}In November 2008, de Blasio announced his candidacy for [[New York City Public Advocate]], entering a crowded field of candidates vying for the Democratic nomination that included former Public Advocate [[Mark J. Green]]. ''[[The New York Times]]'' endorsed de Blasio, praising his efforts to improve public schools and \"[help] many less-fortunate New Yorkers with food stamps, housing, and children's health\" as a councilmember. The paper declared de Blasio the best candidate for the job \"because he has shown that he can work well with [[Michael Bloomberg|Mayor Bloomberg]] when it makes sense to do so while vehemently and eloquently opposing him when justified.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/29/opinion/29sat4.html | title=For New York City Public Advocate | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=August 29, 2009 | accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref> His candidacy was endorsed by then Public Advocate [[Betsy Gotbaum]], former [[New York City Mayor|Mayor]] [[Ed Koch]], former [[New York Governor|Governor]] [[Mario Cuomo]], and [[Al Sharpton|Reverend Al Sharpton]].<ref name=\"nyt-sharpton\">{{cite news | url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/07/16/snubbing-green-gently-sharpton-backs-de-blasio/ | title=Snubbing Green (Gently), Sharpton Backs de Blasio | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=July 16, 2009 | accessdate=November 6, 2013 | author=David W. Chen}}</ref>\n\nOn September 15, 2009, de Blasio finished first in the Democratic primary, garnering 33% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/16/nyregion/16advocate.html | title=De Blasio and Green in Runoff for Advocate | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=September 16, 2009 | author=Julie Bosman}}</ref> He won the runoff primary election on September 29, defeating Green, 62% to 38%.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=560827 | title=NYC Public Advocate \u2013 D Runoff Race |date= September 29, 2009 | publisher=Our Campaigns | accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref> In the November 3 general election, de Blasio defeated Republican [[Alex Zablocki]], 78% to 18%.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=542116 | title=New York City Public Advocate Race | date=November 3, 2009 | publisher=Our Campaigns | accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2009/results/index.html | title=2009 Election Results | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=November 9, 2009 | accessdate=August 8, 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091107034641/http://elections.nytimes.com/2009/results/index.html | archivedate=November 7, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> De Blasio was inaugurated as New York City's third [[Public Advocate]] on January 1, 2010. In his inauguration speech he criticized the Bloomberg administration, especially its homelessness and education policies.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/02/nyregion/02deblasio.html | title=Public Advocate Takes a Challenging Tone, and Thoughts of 2013 Are Near | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=January 1, 2010 | accessdate=May 11, 2010 | author=Julie Bosman}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n====Affordable housing====\nIn June 2010, de Blasio opposed a [[New York City Housing Authority]] decision to cut the number of [[Section 8 (housing)|Section 8]] vouchers issued to low-income New Yorkers. The cut was announced after the NYCHA discovered it could not pay for approximately 2,600 vouchers that had already been issued.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/public-advocate-bill-de-blasio-section-8-housing-subsidies-cuts-cost-city-article-1.183500 | title=Public Advocate Bill de Blasio: Section 8 housing Subsidies Cuts Will Cost City | work=New York Daily News | date=June 20, 2010 | accessdate=August 11, 2015 | author=Einhorn, Erin}}</ref> Two months later, he launched an online \"NYC's Worst Landlords Watchlist\" to track landlords who failed to repair dangerous living conditions. The list drew widespread media coverage and highlighted hundreds of landlords across the city. \"We want these landlords to feel like they're being watched,\" de Blasio told the ''[[New York Daily News]]''. \"We need to shine a light on these folks to shame them into action.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/new-website-aims-shine-light-city-worst-slumlords-article-1.206621 | title=New Website Aims to Shine Light on City's Worst Slumlords | work=[[New York Daily News]] | date=August 30, 2010 | accessdate=July 21, 2012 | author1=Ben Chapman |author2=Erin Einhorn}}</ref>\n\n====Campaign finance====\n{{See also|Campaign finance in the United States}}\nDe Blasio has criticized ''[[Citizens United v. Federal Election Commission|Citizens United]]'', the January 2010 U.S. [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] decision that overturned parts of the [[Bipartisan Campaign Reform Act|2002 McCain-Feingold Bipartisan Campaign Reform Act]]. He argued that \"corporations should not be allowed to buy elections\" and launched a national campaign by elected officials to reverse the decision's effects.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2010/09/bill-de-blasio-citizens-united-avenger | title=Bill de Blasio: Citizens United Avengers | work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]] | author=Suzy Khimm | date=September 22, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n====Education====\nAs public advocate, de Blasio repeatedly criticized Bloomberg's education policies. He called for [[Cathie Black]], Bloomberg's nominee for [[New York City Schools Chancellor]], to take part in public forums and criticized her for sending her own children to private schools.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/bill-de-blasio-unimpressed-cathie-black-hedging-public-school-do-over-kids-blog-entry-1.1682072 | title=Bill de Blasio Unimpressed With Cathie Black's Hedging On A Public School Do-Over For Her Kids | work=[[New York Daily News]] | date=December 8, 2010 | accessdate=January 11, 2015 | author=Celeste Katz}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20101115/manhattan/public-advocate-wants-cathie-black-hold-open-meeting-with-parents-administrators | title=Public Advocate Wants Cathie Black to Hold Open Meeting With Parents, Administrators | work=DNAinfo New York | date=November 15, 2010 | accessdate=October 16, 2013 | author=Jill Colvin | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021212015/http://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20101115/manhattan/public-advocate-wants-cathie-black-hold-open-meeting-with-parents-administrators | archivedate=October 21, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> In March 2010, he spoke against an [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|MTA]] proposal to eliminate free MetroCards for students, arguing the measure would take a significant toll on school attendance.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://pubadvocate.nyc.gov/news/2010-02-18/protests-against-mta-continue-effort-save-student-metrocards | title=Protects Against the MTA Continue in Effort to Save Student MetroCards | publisher=Office of the Public Advocate | date=February 18, 2010 | access-date=May 8, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017024431/http://pubadvocate.nyc.gov/news/2010-02-18/protests-against-mta-continue-effort-save-student-metrocards | archive-date=October 17, 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Three months later, he voiced opposition to the mayor's proposed budget containing more than $34 million in cuts to childcare services.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://archive.advocate.nyc.gov/daycare | title=Public Advocate de Blasio & NYC Parents Fight to Protect City's Daycare Centers | publisher=Office of the Public Advocate}}</ref> In June 2011, de Blasio outlined a plan to improve the process of school co-location, by which multiple schools are housed in one building. His study found community input was often ignored by the city's Department of Education, resulting in top-down decisions made without sufficient regard for negative impacts. He outlined eight solutions to improve the process and incorporate community opinion into the decision-making process.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://archive.advocate.nyc.gov/news/2011-07-20/consensus-reform-plan-collaborative-school-co-locations | title=Consensus for Reform: A Plan for Collaborative School Co-Locations | publisher=Office of the Public Advocate | date=July 20, 2011}}</ref> The same month, he also criticized a Bloomberg administration proposal to lay off more than 4,600 teachers to balance the city's budget; de Blasio organized parents and communities against the proposed cuts and staged a last-minute call-a-thon. Bloomberg restored the funding, agreeing to find savings elsewhere in the budget.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://pubadvocate.nyc.gov/news/2011-06-20/11th-hour-push-public-advocate-de-blasio-brings-voice-parents-city-hall | title=In 11th Hour Push, Public Advocate de Blasio Brings Voice of Parents to City Hall | publisher=Office of the NYC Public Advocate | date=June 20, 2011 | accessdate=January 1, 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102200012/http://pubadvocate.nyc.gov/news/2011-06-20/11th-hour-push-public-advocate-de-blasio-brings-voice-parents-city-hall | archive-date=January 2, 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Mayor of New York City (2014\u2013present)==\n\n===2013 election===\n{{Main|2013 New York City mayoral election}}[[File:Bill de Blasio and family.jpg|thumb|250px|Bill de Blasio with his wife, Chirlane (left), and two children at a rally in New York City in 2013]]On January 27, 2013, de Blasio announced his candidacy for mayor of New York City in the [[New York City mayoral election, 2013|fall election]].<ref name=\"announcenyt\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/28/nyregion/bill-de-blasio-kicks-off-campaign-for-mayor.html | title=De Blasio, Announcing Mayoral Bid, Pledges to Help People City Hall Forgot | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=January 27, 2013 | accessdate=July 30, 2013 | author=David W. Chen}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2013/01/27/de-blasio-announces-mayoral-campaign | title=De Blasio Announces Mayoral Campaign | work=[[CBS News]] | date=January 27, 2013 | accessdate=January 27, 2013}}</ref> The Democratic primary race included nine candidates, among them Council Speaker [[Christine Quinn]], former [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Anthony Weiner]], and former [[New York City Comptroller]] and [[New York City mayoral election, 2009|2009 mayoral nominee]] [[Bill Thompson (New York)|Bill Thompson]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nyccfb.info/reports/candidate_13.htm | title=Candidates 2013 Citywide Elections | publisher=New York City Campaign Finance Board | access-date=July 31, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053635/http://www.nyccfb.info/reports/candidate_13.htm | archive-date=September 21, 2013 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/04/14/nyregion/mayoral-candidates.html | title=A Viewer's Guide to the Mayoral Candidates | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=April 13, 2013 | accessdate=July 30, 2013 | author1=Michael Barbaro |author2=Tom Giratikanon }}</ref> After Weiner joined the race in April, early polls showed de Blasio in fourth or fifth among the candidates.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} Despite his poor starting position, de Blasio gained the endorsements of major Democratic clubs, such as the [[Barack Obama Democratic Club of Upper Manhattan]], and New York City's largest [[trade union]], [[Service Employees International Union|SEIU]] [[1199SEIU United Healthcare Workers East|Local 1199]]. Celebrities such as [[Alec Baldwin]] and [[Sarah Jessica Parker]] endorsed him, as did prominent politicians such as former Vermont Governor [[Howard Dean]] and U.S. Congresswoman [[Yvette Clarke]].<ref name=\"nydaily-sarahjessicaparker\">{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/sarah-jessica-parker-backs-de-blasio-mayor-article-1.1325650 | title=Sarah Jessica Parker Backs Bill de Blasio | work=[[New York Daily News]] | date=April 23, 2013 | accessdate=July 31, 2013 | author=Erin Durkin}}</ref><ref name=\"nydaily-alecbaldwin\">{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/alec-baldwin-backs-bill-de-blasio-nyc-mayor-article-1.1215458 | title=Alec Baldwin Names Bill De Blasio as His Pick for Next New York City Mayor, Knocks Christine Quinn as 'Untrustworthy' | work=[[New York Daily News]] | date=December 7, 2012 | accessdate=July 31, 2013 | author=Kristen A. Lee}}</ref> By August, singer [[Harry Belafonte]] and actress [[Susan Sarandon]] had endorsed de Blasio.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2013/08/celebrities-in-bill-de-blasio-new-video-ad.html | title=All the Celebrities in Bill de Blasio's New Ad|work=[[New York Magazine]] | date=August 27, 2013 | accessdate=September 20, 2013 | author=Joe Coscarelli}}</ref>\n\nDe Blasio gained media attention during the campaign when he and a dozen others, including city councillor [[Stephen Levin (councillor)|Stephen Levin]], were arrested while protesting the closing of [[University Hospital of Brooklyn at Long Island College Hospital|Long Island College Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/brooklyn/pols-rally-save-long-island-college-hospital-article-1.1402934 | title=Bill de Blasio, Dan Squadron and Other Brooklyn Pols Storm LICH After SUNY Sends in Closure Plan | work=[[New York Daily News]] | date=July 18, 2013 | accessdate=July 31, 2013 | author=Simone Weichselbaum}}</ref> De Blasio and Levin were released a few hours later with disorderly conduct summonses. Fellow Democratic mayoral hopefuls Weiner and City Comptroller [[John Liu]] were also at the protest but were not arrested.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/11/nyregion/3-rivals-join-a-protest-but-just-one-wants-to-be-arrested-and-is.html | title=De Blasio Arrested, Just as He Wanted | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=July 10, 2013 | accessdate=July 30, 2013 | author=Anemona Hartocollis}}</ref>\n\nDuring his mayoral campaign, de Blasio outlined a plan to raise taxes on residents earning more than $500,000 a year to pay for universal [[pre-kindergarten]] programs and to expand after-school programs at [[middle school]]s.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-10-04/de-blasio-proposes-nyc-tax-surcharge-on-wealthy-for-schools.html | title=De Blasio Proposes NYC Tax Surcharge on Wealthy for Schools | work=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=October 4, 2012 | accessdate=August 14, 2013 | author=Henry Goldman}}</ref><ref name=\"wfuv\">{{cite news | url=http://www.wfuv.org/news/news-politics/130812/close-nycs-mayoral-candidates-bill-de-blasio-d | title=Up Close With NYC's Mayoral Candidates: Bill de Blasio (D) | work=WFUV 90.7 FM Public Radio from Fordham University | date=August 12, 2013 | accessdate=August 14, 2013 | author=Ann Pierret}}</ref> He also pledged to invest $150 million annually into the [[City University of New York]] to lower tuition and improve degree programs.<ref name=\"wfuv\"/> In September 2013, de Blasio voiced his opposition to [[Charter schools in the United States|charter schools]], maintaining that their funding saps resources from classes like art, physical education and after-school programs. He outlined a plan to discontinue the policy of offering rent-free space to the city's 183 charter schools and to place a moratorium on the co-location of charter schools in public school buildings.<ref name=\"nyt-charterschools\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/09/nyregion/charter-schools-fear-having-de-blasio-for-a-landlord.html | title=City's Charter Schools Fear Having de Blasio for a Landlord | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=October 8, 2013 | accessdate=November 6, 2013 | author=Javier C. Hern\u00e1ndez}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, the de Blasio campaign released a television advertisement featuring de Blasio's then-15-year-old son, Dante, talking about his father's plans to \"'really break from the Bloomberg years.'\"<ref name=\"Gray\">{{cite web | url=http://nation.time.com/2013/09/11/the-ad-that-won-the-new-york-mayors-race/ | title= The Ad That Won the New York Mayor's Race| work=Time Magazine | last=Gray | first=Eliza | date=September 11, 2013 | accessdate=January 31, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/election/bill-de-blasio-nimble-campaign-made-mayor-article-1.1507754| title= How Bill de Blasio's nimble 2013 mayoral election campaign got Democratic Party back into Gracie Mansion| work=New York Daily News | last=Karni | first=Annie | date=November 5, 2013 | accessdate=January 31, 2018}}</ref> [[Time (magazine)|TIME]] called it \"The Ad That Won the New York Mayor's Race,\" noting that after it ran, \"de Blasio built a steady lead that he never relinquished.\"<ref name=\"Gray\"/> Quinn was attacked by a number of groups including [[NYCLASS (New Yorkers for Clean, Livable, and Safe Streets)|NYCLASS]] with their \"Anybody But Quinn\" campaign, allowing de Blasio to move up in the polls. By mid-August he emerged as the new leader among the Democrats.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/14/nyregion/new-poll-suggests-that-de-blasio-is-now-first-among-voters.html | title=New Poll Suggests That de Blasio Is Now First Among Voters | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=August 14, 2013 | accessdate=September 20, 2013 | author=David W. Chen}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/pac-pummels-nyc-mayor-wannabe-quinn-article-1.1386683|title=PAC pummels NYC mayor wannabe Quinn|work=NY Daily News|access-date=2017-05-04|language=en}}</ref> He reached 43% in a Quinnipiac poll released a week before the primary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quinnipiac.edu/news-and-events/quinnipiac-university-poll/new-york-city/release-detail?ReleaseID=1948 |title=De Blasio Surges Past 40% In New York City Mayoral Race |publisher=[[Quinnipiac University]] |date=September 3, 2013|accessdate=January 11, 2015}}</ref> Preliminary results of the September 11 primary showed de Blasio with 40.1% of the votes, slightly more than the 40% needed to avoid a runoff.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/race-for-new-york-mayors-office-sees-bill-de-blasio-edging-it-8810245.html | title=Race for New York Mayor's office sees Bill De Blasio edging it | work=[[The Independent]] | date=September 11, 2013 | accessdate=September 11, 2013 | author=Nikhil Kumar}}</ref>\n\nOn September 16, second-place finisher [[Bill Thompson (New York)|Bill Thompson]] conceded, citing the unlikelihood of winning a runoff even if uncounted absentee and military ballots pushed de Blasio below the 40% threshold. Thompson's withdrawal made de Blasio the Democratic nominee against Republican [[Joe Lhota]] in the general election.<ref name=\"nyt-thompsoncedes\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/17/nyregion/thompson-to-concede-to-de-blasio-in-mayoral-primary.html?hp | title=A Display of Democratic Unity as Thompson Cedes to de Blasio | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=September 16, 2013 | accessdate=September 20, 2013 | author=Michael M. Grynbaum}}</ref> Exit polls showed that the issue that most aided de Blasio's primary victory was his unequivocal opposition to \"stop and frisk.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nybooks.com/blogs/nyrblog/2013/sep/23/how-different-de-blasio/|title=How Different is de Blasio?|author=Michael Greenberg|newspaper=[[New York Review of Books]]|date=September 23, 2013}}</ref> After the primary, de Blasio was announced as the nominee of the [[Working Families Party]].<ref name=\"WFP\">{{cite press release | url=http://www.workingfamiliesparty.org/2013/09/working-families-party-leaders-back-bill-de-blasio-for-mayor-of-new-york-city | title=Working Families Party Leaders Back Bill de Blasio for Mayor of New York City | publisher=[[Working Families Party]] | date=September 12, 2013 | accessdate=September 16, 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007052042/http://www.workingfamiliesparty.org/2013/09/working-families-party-leaders-back-bill-de-blasio-for-mayor-of-new-york-city/ | archivedate=October 7, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> In the general election, he defeated Lhota in a landslide with 72.2% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vote.nyc.ny.us/downloads/pdf/results/2013/2013GeneralElection/00001100000Citywide%20Mayor%20Citywide%20Recap.pdf |title=Mayor \u2013 Citywide Recap | publisher= NYC Board of Elections | accessdate=November 5, 2013}}</ref> Voter turnout for the election set a new record low of only 24% of registered voters, which ''[[The New York Times]]'' attributed to the expectation of a landslide in the heavily Democratic city.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/news/election-2013/2013/11/06/new-york-turnout-appears-headed-for-record-low | title=New York: Voter Turnout Appears to Be Record Low | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=November 6, 2013 | author=Sam Roberts}}</ref> The campaign finance activities of the de Blasio 2013 committee reportedly became the subject of a federal corruption investigation led by U.S. Attorney [[Preet Bharara]]. Other government authorities were also involved in investigations, some of which reportedly overlapped, including whether campaign donors received preferential treatment from City Hall.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2016/06/guide-to-mayor-de-blasios-investigations.html | title=A Beginner's Guide to the Many Investigations Involving Mayor Bill de Blasio | work=New York | date=June 9, 2016 | accessdate=November 6, 2016 | author=Caroline Bankoff}}</ref> The investigation ended in March 2017 with no charges.\n\n=== 2017 election ===\n{{Main|2017 New York City mayoral election}}\nIn 2017, de Blasio won reelection to a second term, defeating Republican Assemblywoman [[Nicole Malliotakis]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/new-york-general-elections|title=Election Results: De Blasio Wins Second Term as New York City Mayor|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> 65.2%-27.2%.<ref>https://www.vote.nyc.ny.us/downloads/pdf/election_results/2017/20171107General%20Election/00001100000Citywide%20Mayor%20Citywide%20Recap.pdf</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n[[File:The Prime Minister, Shri Narendra Modi meeting the Mayor of New York, Mr. Bill de Blasio, in New York on September 26, 2014.jpg|thumb|De Blasio and Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] in New York on September 26, 2014]]\nDe Blasio was sworn into office on January 1, 2014, by former President [[Bill Clinton]]. In his inaugural address, he reiterated his campaign pledge to address \"economic and social inequalities\" within the city.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/02/nyregion/bill-de-blasio-inauguration.html | title=Taking Office, de Blasio Vows to Fix Inequity | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=January 1, 2014 | author=Michael M. Grynbaum}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' noted that \"The elevation of an assertive, tax-the-rich liberal to the nation's most prominent municipal office has fanned hopes that hot-button causes like universal prekindergarten and low-wage worker benefits... could be aided by the imprimatur of being proved workable in New York.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/01/nyregion/de-blasio-draws-all-liberal-eyes-to-new-york-city.html | title=De Blasio Draws All Liberal Eyes to New York City | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=December 31, 2013 | author=Michael M. Grynbaum.}}</ref>\n[[File:No NYC Hypocrisy rally & march (33783880945).jpg|thumb|''No NYC Hypocrisy'' rally in April 2017]]\n\nIn the first weeks of de Blasio's mayoralty, New York City was struck by a series of snowstorms.<ref name=\"politicker20140212\">{{cite news | url=http://politicker.com/2014/02/de-blasio-adds-35-million-to-snow-removal-budget/ | title=De Blasio Adds $35 Million to Snow Removal Budget | work=[[Politicker]] | date=February 12, 2014 | accessdate=February 15, 2014 | author=Kelly Weill}}</ref> De Blasio was criticized by [[Upper East Side]] residents who said efforts to clear the snow seemed to be lagging in their neighborhood.<ref name=nydn20140123>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/mayor-de-blasio-dismisses-claim-plows-skipped-ues-article-1.1587823 | title=Mayor de Blasio Admits Mistakes in Snow Removal on New York's Upper East Side | work=[[New York Daily News]] | date=January 23, 2014 | accessdate=February 15, 2014 | author1=Annie Karni |author2=Edgar Sandoval |author3=Corky Siamaszk}}</ref> De Blasio apologized the next day, saying that \"more could have been done to serve the Upper East Side.\"<ref name=nydn20140123/> On February 13, heavy snowstorms hit the East Coast again. Under instructions from De Blasio and School Chancellor [[Carmen Fari\u00f1a]], the city's public schools were kept open. This decision was criticized by teacher unions, parents and the media as up to 9.5 inches of snow fell that day.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/14/us/winter-storm.html | title=Winter Offensive Takes Toll on East Coast | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=February 13, 2014 | accessdate=February 15, 2014 | author=Marc Santora}}</ref> By the middle of February, the city had added $35 million to the [[New York City Department of Sanitation|Sanitation Department]]'s budget for snow removal.<ref name=\"politicker20140212\"/>\n\nIn July 2014, de Blasio signed a bill that created [[City identification card|municipal identification cards]] for all residents regardless of immigration status, helping them secure access to city services.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mayor de Blasio Signs Legislation to Create Municipal ID Card|url=http://www1.nyc.gov/office-of-the-mayor/news/345-14/mayor-de-blasio-signs-legislation-create-municipal-id-card |publisher=City of New York|date=July 20, 2014|accessdate=September 16, 2014}}</ref> Homeless New Yorkers are also eligible to obtain the [[IDNYC]] cards so long as they register a \"care of\" address. The IDNYC card program was launched January 1, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsday.com/news/new-york/nyc-muni-id-details-unveiled-1.9685723 |title=NYC municipal ID card details unveiled |work=[[Newsday]] |date=December 5, 2014 |accessdate=January 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDe Blasio has had mixed approval ratings during his mayoralty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://poll.qu.edu/new-york-city/release-detail?ReleaseID=2475|title=QU Poll Release Detail|publisher=[[Quinnipiac University]]|website=QU Poll|language=en|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20170731/POLITICS/170739990/mayor-bill-de-blasios-popularity-takes-a-dive-amid-subway-crisis-as-quinnipiac-poll-finds-his-approval-at-about-50-percent|title=De Blasio's popularity takes a dive amid subway crisis|last=Bredderman|first=Will|work=Crain's New York Business|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/06/magazine/mayor-bill-de-blasio-2020-campaign.html|title=How Bill de Blasio Went From Progressive Hope to Punching Bag|last=Flegenheimer|first=Matt|date=2019-08-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-09-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n====9/11 attacks====\nIn 2016, de Blasio expressed support for the [[Justice Against Sponsors of Terrorism Act]] that would allow relatives of victims of the [[September 11 attacks]] to sue [[Saudi Arabia]] for its government's [[Alleged Saudi role in September 11 attacks|alleged role in the attacks]].<ref>\"[http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/saudi-government-didn-fund-terrorists-obama-aide-article-1.2605678 Mayor de Blasio joins Democrats in calling on President Obama to go after Saudi Arabia on 9/11 ties]\". ''[[New York Daily News]]''. April 19, 2016.</ref>\n\n==== Affordable housing ====\nA key aim of de Blasio's mayoral tenure has been to build more affordable housing, with a goal of 200,000 units.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.nyc.gov/site/housing/problem/problem.page|title=Problem \u2013 NYC Housing Plan|website=www1.nyc.gov|access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref> His plan passed the City Council,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20161019/EXPERT/161019847/why-mayor-bill-de-blasios-affordable-housing-plan-is-in-trouble-as-opponents-of-rezoning-such-as-council-member-ydanis-rodriguez-and-critics-like-jimmy-van-bremer-mount-opposition|title=Why de Blasio's affordable housing plan is in trouble [in 5 steps]|last=Anuta|first=Joe|work=Crain's New York Business|access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref> but has been controversial. Groups such as the [[New York Communities for Change]] have come out against certain aspects of the plan, arguing that it promotes [[gentrification]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://shakingnews.com/blog/2017/05/03/affordable-for-whom-nyc-affordable-housing/|title=Affordable for Whom?&nbsp;The Tragically&nbsp;Misguided Arguments about Affordable Housing in NYC \u2013 ShakingNews|date=2017-05-03|work=ShakingNews|access-date=2017-05-04|language=en-US}}</ref> Relatedly, in April 2017 the state government renewed the [[421-a tax abatement|421-a tax abatement program]] after unions and developers made a deal on wages in qualifying construction projects.<ref name=\"421-a\">{{cite news|last1=Fink|first1=Zach|title=Tax Abatement for Developers Has Passed in State Budget, But Critics are Not Sold|url=http://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/politics/2017/04/15/421-a-tax-abatement-developers-state-budget-critics-skeptical.html|accessdate=June 5, 2017|publisher=NY 1|date=April 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Atlantic Avenue (New York City)|Atlantic Avenue]], in the [[East New York]] neighborhood of [[Brooklyn]], which has been scarred by decades of poverty and crime, was the first test and focus of de Blasio's strategy on affordable housing, one of the policy initiatives central to his platform of reducing inequality. Since 2012, city planners have been working to bring residents to forums to consult on the process. The plan is to \"invite developers to build up local streets in exchange for more units of affordable housing.\" They will invest in new trees, parks, sidewalks, schools, shops, and restaurants that will lead to better services.<ref name=\"NYT_2015\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/04/nyregion/an-obstacle-to-mayor-de-blasios-affordable-housing-plan-neighborhood-resistance.html?smid=tw-nytimes | title=Some See Risk in de Blasio's Bid to Add Housing | work=New York Times | date=February 3, 2015 | accessdate=February 8, 2015 | location=New York | pages=A1 | first2=Mireya | last2=Navarro | first1=Vivian | last1=Yee}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, de Blasio and Secretary of Housing and Urban Development [[Ben Carson]] reached an agreement to change the operations of the New York City Housing Authority. The agreement created \"specific requirements and milestones to address the serious health and safety hazards at NYCHA properties, including lead-based paint, mold, heat, vermin, among others\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2019/01/31/nycha-hud-ben-carson-bill-de-blasio/|title=NYC, Feds Reach Agreement To Overhaul Struggling NYCHA|first=David Baker|last=says|date=January 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Budget====\nIn 2019, ''City Journal'' reported that during the de Blasio administration, \"New York City\u2019s budget has expanded by some $20 billion, and is expected to total about $93 billion for the coming fiscal year. Expenditures have ballooned three times as fast as the rate of inflation\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.city-journal.org/de-blasio-expanding-city-spending |title=De Blasio has enjoyed a spending spree, expanded NYC's budget every year |publisher=City Journal |date=2019-04-24 |accessdate=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\n====Charter schools====\nDe Blasio's decision to deny the use of public space to several New York City [[charter school]]s provoked controversy among advocates of [[school vouchers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/30/nyregion/carranza-charter-schools-deblasio.html|title=With School Visits, Chancellor Signals a Softer Stance on Charters|newspaper=New York Times|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> The decision overturned a Bloomberg administration arrangement that allowed for \"co-locations\", where charter schools were housed in public school buildings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/03/04/why-is-progressive-hero-bill-de-blasio-throwing-charter-schools-out-of-new-york-city.html|title=Why Is Progressive Hero Bill de Blasio Throwing Charter Schools Out of New York City?|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|author=Conor P. Williams|date=March 3, 2014|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref> De Blasio also revoked $200 million of capital funding earmarked for charter schools.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/education/gov-cuomo-airs-support-charter-schools-article-1.1710958 | title=Gov. Cuomo Boosts Charter Schools, Going Over Mayor de Blasio's Head \u2014 Again | work=[[Daily News (New York)|The New York Daily News]] | date=March 4, 2014 | accessdate=March 30, 2014 | author1=Kenneth Lovett |author2=Glenn Blain}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' emphasized that de Blasio approved 14 charter school co-locations and denied just three, suggesting that he was being unfairly cast as opposed to charter schools.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nytimes.com/2014/03/09/nyregion/de-blasio-and-cuomos-tangled-narratives.html |author=Ginia Bellafante |title=How de Blasio's Narrative Got Hijacked |work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 6, 2014 |accessdate=March 27, 2014}}</ref> Approximately two months after the initial decision, the mayor's office announced that it had found space for the three schools. The city would lease three buildings, which were previously used for Catholic schools, from the [[Archdiocese of New York]], and renovate and maintain them. The three charter schools are run by [[Success Academy Charter Schools]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/27/nyregion/new-york-finds-space-for-3-charter-schools.html?smid=fb-share&_r=0 | title=New York Finds Space for 3 Charter Schools | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=April 26, 2014 | accessdate=April 28, 2014 | author=Daniel E. Slotnik}}</ref>\n\n====Environmental issues====\nDe Blasio supports the [[Green New Deal]]. In April 2019 he announced his support for legislation to ban the construction of glass and steel skyscrapers in New York City, citing environmental concerns and contribution to global warming.<ref>\"[https://www.crainsnewyork.com/politics/de-blasio-insists-his-ban-glass-and-steel-buildings-real De Blasio insists his ban on glass-and-steel buildings is real]\". ''[[Crain's New York]]''. April 29, 2016.</ref> De Blasio also criticized the development at [[Hudson Yards (development)|Hudson Yards]] in Manhattan as an example of \"the wrong way to do things\".<ref>\"[https://ny.curbed.com/2019/4/24/18514203/nyc-bill-de-blasio-glass-skyscraper-ban De Blasio\u2019s \u2018glass skyscraper ban,\u2019 explained]. ''[[Curbed]]''. April 24, 2019.</ref>\n\n====Israel====\n[[File:De Blasio at Celebrate Israel Parade (8927511453).jpg|thumb|De Blasio at the [[Celebrate Israel Parade]] in June 2013]]\nOn February 14, 2019, while addressing a rally in New York City about combatting [[antisemitism]], De Blasio said: \"Maybe some people don\u2019t realize it, but when they support the [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions|BDS]] movement, they are affronting the right of Israel to exist and that is unacceptable.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=New York Mayor Condemns BDS, Calls to Stamp Out anti-Semitism |url=https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/.premium-new-york-mayor-condemns-bds-calls-to-stamp-out-anti-semitism-1.6938298 |work=Haaretz |date=February 15, 2019}}</ref> De Blasio condemned [[Ilhan Omar]]'s remarks about Israel and [[Israel lobby in the United States|pro-Israel lobbyists]] as \"absolutely unacceptable\" and \"illogical\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Ilhan Omar: US House votes amid anti-Semitism row |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-47488272 |publisher=BBC |date=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Marijuana legalization====\nIn December 2018, De Blasio announced his support for marijuana legalization in New York City, calling it a \"once-in-a-generation opportunity to get a historic issue right for future New Yorkers.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2018/12/20/de-blasio-endorses-legalizing-marijuana-in-nyc/ |title=De Blasio: Legalizing Marijuana In NYC Is 'Once-In-A-Generation Opportunity' |date=2018-12-20 |language=en |access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref> He worked with a marijuana task force to produce a report on licensing and regulation, which was released along with a letter of endorsement.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/which-states-legalization-marijuana-2019=-1275736 |title=Experts predict 2019 will be a \"real game-changer\" for marijuana legalization. Here's where it could be legal next |last=Hutzler |first=Alexandra |date=2019-01-01 |website=Newsweek |language=en |access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref>\n\n====Mohel disclosure rule====\nIn 2015, de Blasio repealed a requirement that [[mohel]]s inform parents of the risks of [[Brit milah#Metzitzah B'Peh|metzitzah b'peh]], an oral circumcision ritual that was linked to 17 cases of infant herpes, brain damage, and two deaths since 2000.<ref>{{cite news|title=NYC, Orthodox Jews in Talks Over Ritual After Herpes Cases|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2015/02/21/nyc-orthodox-jews-in-talks-over-ritual-after-herpes-cases/23798751/|author=Associated Press|accessdate=23 August 2016|work=USA Today|agency=Associated Press|date=February 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/13/nyregion/regulation-of-circumcision-method-divides-some-jews-in-new-york.html|title=Denouncing City's Move to Regulate Circumcision|date=September 13, 2012|work=The New York Times|last1=Otterman|first1=Sharon|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref> The rule was passed by the city's Board of Health in 2012, required parents to sign a consent form, and had been called an infringement on religious freedom by ultra-Orthodox Jewish leaders, who sued the city in federal court<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/25/nyregion/de-blasio-set-to-waive-rule-requiring-consent-form-for-circumcision-ritual.html|title=Mayor de Blasio Is Set to Ease Rules on Circumcision Ritual|date=February 25, 2015|work=The New York Times|last1=Grynbaum|first1=Michael M.|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref> and pressed their followers not to comply.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/15/nyregion/mayor-de-blasio-and-rabbis-near-accord-on-new-circumcision-rule.html|title=Mayor de Blasio and Rabbis Near Accord on New Circumcision Rule|date=January 15, 2015|work=The New York Times|last1=Otterman|first1=Sharon|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref> After de Blasio installed allies and donors on New York City's Board of Health,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/10/nyregion/de-blasio-puts-allies-on-panel-hearing-circumcision-plan.html|title=De Blasio Puts Allies on Panel Hearing Circumcision Plan|date=June 10, 2015|work=The New York Times|last1=Grynbaum|first1=Michael M.|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref> a new policy stated that mohels could be banned for life if they tested positive for herpes and the DNA strain matched the infant's, but only after a child has been infected, and not when a mohel tests positive but his DNA strain does not match the infant's.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/de-blasio-administration-scraps-circumcision-ritual-rules-article-1.2128239|title=De Blasio administration scraps consent rules for Jewish circumcision ritual|website=NY Daily News|first=Reuven|last=Blau|date=February 24, 2015}}</ref> It was revealed that the city did not disclose new infections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forward.com/news/321465/new-circumcision-rules-metzitzah-dont-ask-dont-tell/|title=New Controversial Circumcision Rite Rules: Don't Ask, Don't Tell|author=Paul Berger|date=September 25, 2015|work=The Forward|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref> Since the change was made, several children have been infected with the disease after undergoing the ritual.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/manhattan/nyc-barred-men-practicing-jewish-circumcision-article-1.3013127|title=NYC bars two men from practicing Jewish circumcision after infants contract herpes|website=NY Daily News|first=Jillian Jorgensen, Erin|last=Durkin|date=March 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====NYPD relations====\n{{Expand section|date=May 2019}}\n[[File:NYC Mike Brown-Ferguson protest Pace University.JPG|thumb|right|New Yorkers demonstrating against police brutality at [[Pace University]] in November 2014|279x279px]]\nDuring his mayoral tenure, de Blasio's relationship with the New York City Police Department has been described as \"strained\",<ref name=\"time.com\">{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3644168/new-york-police-de-blasio-wenjian-liu-rafael-ramos/|title=Why New York Cops Hate Mayor de Blasio|website=Time}}</ref> \"combative\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/05/nyregion/bill-deblasio-police-crime.html|title=De Blasio Kept Crime Down in First Term. His Next Goal: Nicer Police.|first1=J. David|last1=Goodman|first2=Al|last2=Baker|date=November 5, 2017|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2017/07/07/new-york-city-mayor-de-blasio-slammed-for-trump-protesting-germany-trip-as-city-mourns-officers-death/|title=New York mayor on Germany trip: The world should know that Americans don't align with Trump|website=Washington Post}}</ref> and \"frosty\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/07/11/bill-de-blasio-g-20-backlash-240412|title=De Blasio faces Germany trip backlash|first1=Gloria|last1=Pazmino|first2=Laura|last2=Nahmias|website=POLITICO}}</ref>\n\nOpposition to [[Stop-and-frisk in New York City|the NYPD's \"stop and frisk\" policy]] was a centerpiece of De Blasio's campaign.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://nation.time.com/2014/01/30/stop-and-frisk-bill-de-blasio-michael-bloomberg-appeal-crime |title=New NYC Mayor Drops Stop-and-Frisk Appeal |work=[[Time Magazine]] |date= January 30, 2014 |author=Eliana Dockterman}}</ref> The practice had been challenged by civil rights groups in federal court, where it was [[Floyd v. City of New York|ruled unconstitutional in 2013]]. The federal appeal of this decision filed by the Bloomberg administration was dropped by de Blasio upon taking office. He vowed to settle cases with claimants who had ongoing litigation against the police for stop and frisk arrests. The NYPD union appealed the decision without de Blasio's support, and was rejected.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/01/nyregion/police-unions-cant-intervene-in-stop-and-frisk-cases-appeals-panel-rules.html |title=Unions' Bid for Role in Stop-and-Frisk Suits Is Rejected by Court |author=Benjamin Weiser|work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 31, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDe Blasio selected [[Bill Bratton]] for [[New York City Police Commissioner]], a position he had held under Mayor [[Rudy Giuliani]]. Bratton, who introduced [[Frisking|stop and frisk]] under Giuliani, promised it would be used \"legally, respectfully\" and less frequently.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/bratton-miller-on-stop-and-frisk-and-job-qualifications/ | title=NYPD's Bratton, Miller on stop-and-frisk and job qualifications | work=[[CBS News]] | date=January 9, 2014 | author=Shoshana Davis}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/12/27/new-yorkers-against-bratton_n_4509200.html | title=New Group Launches Fight Against de Blasio's Top Cop | work=[[The Huffington Post]] | date=December 27, 2013 | author=Saki Knafo}}</ref> Some de Blasio supporters were disappointed with Bratton's appointment.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.latinpost.com/articles/4807/20131215/mayor-elect-bill-de-blasio-selects-stop-frisk-innovator-william.htm | title=Bill de Blasio Mayor: NYC Mayor-elect Selects Stop-and-Frisk Innovator William Bratton as Police Commissioner; Latino Candidates Snubbed? | work=Latin Post | date=December 15, 2013 | author=Nicole Akoukou Thompson}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2014, de Blasio came under criticism for calling the police shortly after one of his supporters was detained by police. Pastor Bishop Orlando Findlayter\u2014the founder of the New Hope Christian Fellowship Church, and a friend of de Blasio\u2014was pulled over for failing to signal on a left turn. Findlayter was then detained by police on outstanding warrants and driving with a suspended license.<ref name=Bishop1>{{cite news|url=https://nytimes.com/2014/02/12/nyregion/mayors-call-did-not-prompt-pastors-release-police-say.html |title=Mayor's Call Did Not Prompt Pastor's Release Police Say |work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Joseph Goldstein|date=February 12, 2014 |accessdate=March 30, 2014}}</ref> De Blasio is alleged to have called the police on Findlayter's behalf. Findlayter was released shortly thereafter. In a press conference, de Blasio told reporters that while he had called the police to make an inquiry regarding Findlayter's arrest he did not ask the police to release him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/de-blasio-not-bishop-released-article-1.1613284|title=De Blasio: I Did Not Ask for Bishop to be Released|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=February 13, 2014|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref> A spokesperson for the mayor said that de Blasio's call occurred after the police already had decided to release Findlayter.<ref name=Bishop1/> While both the police and City Hall denied that De Blasio asked for preferential treatment, City Comptroller [[Scott M. Stringer]] said De Blasio's behavior was problematic because \"the mayor shouldn't be involved in any way about somebody's arrest.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nytimes.com/2014/02/13/nyregion/mayors-judgment-debated-after-his-call-to-police-about-a-supporters-arrest.html |title=Mayor judgement debated after his call to police about a supporters arrest |work='The New York Times  |author=Michael M. Grynbaum |date=February 13, 2014 |accessdate=March 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn December 3, 2014, following a [[Grand juries in the United States|grand jury]] decision not to indict NYPD officer Daniel Pantaleo in the [[death of Eric Garner]], de Blasio said in a speech that he and his [[African American]] wife, [[Chirlane McCray]], had had many conversations<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2014/dec/21/mayor-bill-de-blasio-police-two-nypd-officers-shot-dead|title=De Blasio at Centre of Police Storm After Two NYPD Officers Shot Dead|author=Amanda Holpuch|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=December 21, 2014|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref> with their biracial son about taking \"special care in any encounters he has with the police officers who are there to protect him.\"<ref name=Garner>{{cite news|author=Erin Durkin|title=De Blasio Talks of Worries for Son Dante After Grand Jury Declines to Indict Cop in Eric Garner Death|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/nyc-crime/de-blasio-talks-biracial-son-eric-garner-grand-jury-article-1.2032253|newspaper=[[New York Daily News]]|date=December 3, 2014|accessdate=December 15, 2014}}</ref> De Blasio also \"offered qualified support for protesters after the grand jury decision not to charge the officer involved in the chokehold death of Eric Garner in New York City\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-police-idUSKBN0KD06A20150104|title=Hundreds of police turn backs on NYC mayor at slain officer's funeral|last=Malo|first=Sebastien|date=2015-01-04|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-01-02|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfter New York City police officers Wenjian Liu and Rafael Ramos were killed in an ambush in December 2014, \"cops and union leaders publicly rebuked [de Blasio], arguing [that] his earlier remarks had stoked anti-police sentiment.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3644168/new-york-police-de-blasio-wenjian-liu-rafael-ramos/|title=Why New York Cops Hate Mayor de Blasio|last=Altman|first=Alex|date=December 22, 2014|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-01-02}}</ref> When de Blasio eulogized the two fallen officers, hundreds of their fellow police officers turned their backs on him.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFollowing the murder of New York City police officer Miosotis Familia in July 2017, de Blasio received further criticism for not attending Familia's vigil. Many officers again turned their backs on him when he spoke at a service for Familia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L_S3KauQWqk|title=NYPD officers turn their backs on Mayor de Blasio at slain officer's funeral|first=Fox|last=News|publisher=YouTube|date=12 July 2017|accessdate=14 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2017/07/11/de-blasio-greeted-by-turned-backs-at-familia-funeral-113318|title=Protesters turn their backs on de Blasio at officer's funeral|first=Gloria|last=Pazmino|website=Politico PRO}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, de Blasio criticized former mayor Michael Bloomberg's apology for the [[stop and frisk]] policy, tweeting, \"This is LONG overdue and the timing is transparent and cynical. With all due respect to my predecessor, we\u2019ve spent six years undoing the damage he created with this bankrupt policy. We ended stop and frisk AND drove down crime. Actions speak louder than words.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Mayor Bill de BlasioVerified account |url=https://twitter.com/NYCMayor/status/1196130583409283072 |title=Mayor Bill de Blasio on Twitter: \"This is LONG overdue and the timing is transparent and cynical. With all due respect to my predecessor, we\u00e2\u20ac\u2122ve spent six years undoing the damage he created with this bankrupt policy. We ended stop and frisk AND drove down crime. Actions speak louder than words.\u00e2\u20ac\u015a https://t.co/86mLlyJefs\" |publisher=Twitter.com |date= |accessdate=2020-01-22}}</ref> Police Benevolent Association President [[Patrick Lynch (police officer)|Patrick Lynch]] joined the Mayor in criticizing Bloomberg's apology as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pix11.com/2019/11/17/too-little-too-late-pat-lynch-police-union-president-slams-bloomberg-stop-and-frisk-apology|title='Too little, too late': Police union president slams Bloomberg 'stop and frisk' apology|date=November 17, 2019|website=WPIX}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/11/17/police-union-de-blasio-blast-bloomberg-over-stop-and-frisk-apology/|title=Police union, de Blasio blast Bloomberg over stop-and-frisk apology|first1=Carl|last1=Campanile|first2=Craig|last2=McCarthy|first3=Aaron|last3=Feis|date=November 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Technology and innovation====\nWhen de Blasio appointed [[Minerva Tantoco]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20140916/TECHNOLOGY/140919903/new-tech-czar-makes-big-app-decision|title=New tech czar makes big app decision|date=September 16, 2014|website=Crain's New York Business}}</ref> as the city's chief technology officer in fall 2014, he said her goal would be to \"develop and implement a coordinated strategy for technology and innovation, for how this city as a whole is going to approach the role of technology in our everyday lives, in our economy, in our schools, in our civic participation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://subscriber.politicopro.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2016/03/city-tech-approach-gets-mixed-grades-two-years-in-099483|title=City tech approach gets mixed grades two years in|last=Miranda Neubauer|website=Politico PRO|language=en|access-date=2019-03-29}}</ref>\n\nAlong with Governor Cuomo, de Blasio supported moving [[Amazon (company)|Amazon's]] [[headquarters]] to [[Long Island City]] in the [[Amazon HQ2]] search, and worked with Cuomo to develop a benefits package from New York City and State funds totaling $2.988 billion.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |last1=Raskin |first1=Sam |title=Amazon's HQ2 deal with New York, explained |url=https://ny.curbed.com/2018/11/16/18098589/amazon-hq2-nyc-queens-long-island-city-explained |website=Curbed New York |accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref> In November 2018, Long Island City was selected as one of two sites for HQ2, along with [[Crystal City, Arlington, Virginia|Crystal City]] in Virginia, directly outside of [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, D.C]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> Long Island City's selection as a site for Amazon's HQ2 was controversial before and after it happened, and was protested by local residents, community organizations, and politicians. After receiving pushback, Amazon withdrew its plans to open HQ2 in Long Island City on February 14, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hanbury |first1=Mary |title=Mayor Bill de Blasio slams Amazon for scrapping its HQ2 project in New York City |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/mayor-bill-de-blasio-criticizes-amazon-cancel-hq2-2019-2 |website=Business Insider |accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref> De Blasio later criticized Amazon's decision.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/14/nyregion/amazon-hq2-queens.html |title=Amazon Pulls Out of Planned New York City Headquarters |date=February 14, 2019 |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190215000024/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/14/nyregion/amazon-hq2-queens.html |archive-date=February 15, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Transportation====\nIn 2014, de Blasio released a report dedicated to \"better transit for New York City.\" Some of the ideas brought up in the report were to rebuild [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Penn Station]]/[[Madison Square Garden]], create more [[bus rapid transit]] routes,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dnwssx4l7gl7s.cloudfront.net/deblasio/default/page/-/One%20New%20York%2C%20Rising%20Together%20-%20Transit.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150524211041/http://dnwssx4l7gl7s.cloudfront.net/deblasio/default/page/-/One%20New%20York%2C%20Rising%20Together%20-%20Transit.pdf|url-status=dead|title=Better Transit for New York City|archivedate=May 24, 2015}}</ref> and a \"Vision Zero\" initiative to reduce traffic-related deaths in the city.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/19/nyregion/de-blasio-unveils-plans-to-eliminate-traffic-deaths.html|title=De Blasio Outlines Steps to Eliminate Traffic Deaths|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Matt Flegenheimer|date=February 18, 2014|accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe \"Vision Zero\" initiative, inspired by a successful Swedish plan, saw a gradual decrease in pedestrian fatalities, from 299 in 2013 to 200 in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/01/nyregion/traffic-deaths-decrease-nyc.html|title=Traffic Deaths in New York City Drop to 200, a Record Low|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Emma G. Fitzsimmons|date=Jan 1, 2019|accessdate=September 5, 2019}}</ref> However, in 2019 there has been an increase in cyclist deaths, and de Blasio has discussed several proposals to combat cyclist deaths, including a $58.4 million plan<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/25/nyregion/nyc-bike-safety-deaths.html|title=After 17 Cyclists Die, New York City Makes $58.4 Million Plan|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Winnie Hu|date=July 25, 2019|accessdate=September 5, 2019}}</ref> and requiring cyclists to wear helmets and acquire licenses to operate a bicycle.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gothamist.com/news/de-blasio-mulls-mandatory-helmets-citi-bike-riders-licenses-all-cyclists|title=De Blasio Mulls Mandatory Helmets For Citi Bike Riders, Licenses For All Cyclists|newspaper=[[Gothamist]]|author=Christopher Robbins|date=September 4, 2019|accessdate=September 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905152047/https://gothamist.com/news/de-blasio-mulls-mandatory-helmets-citi-bike-riders-licenses-all-cyclists|archive-date=September 5, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWhile the de Blasio administration planned on increasing the rate at which bicycle racks were added in the city, the annual rate has instead fallen by 42 percent compared to the Bloomberg administration, reaching a new average of 1,633 new racks per year.{{When|date=October 2019}} Jon Orcutt, a spokesman for Bike New York, said \"Everybody's talking about [[Citi Bike]]s and scooters but it's the humble bike rack that needs more attention.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amny.com/transit/bike-racks-nyc-1.27886025|title=Competition is fierce as bike rack installations slow|website=am New York}}</ref>\n\n====Universal pre-kindergarten====\nAs mayor, de Blasio's signature initiative was the implementation of [[Universal preschool|Universal Pre-K]], the availability of publicly funded pre-kindergarten for all New York City residents.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/01/nyregion/deblasio-pre-k-program-nyc.html|title=Bright Spot for N.Y.'s Struggling Schools: Pre-K|last=Shapiro|first=Eliza|date=2019-01-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-05-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2014/02/de-blasio-presses-forward-with-pre-k-plan.html|title=Mayor de Blasio Presses Forward With Pre-K Plan -- NYMag|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York Magazine]]|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref> He sought to fund the program by increasing taxes on New York City residents earning $500,000 or more.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2014/01/08/pf/taxes/new-york-tax-de-blasio/|title=De Blasio's plan to tax the rich|author=Jeanne Sahadi|date=January 8, 2014|work=[[CNNMoney]]|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref> De Blasio's initiative has seen an increase in Universal Pre-K enrollment in New York City through 2015, with over 70% of pre-K expansions happening within the ZIP codes of the city's poorest quartile.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Shapiro|first1=Eliza|last2=Cheney|first2=Brendan|title=City Enrolls 68K in Pre-K, With Big Growth in Poorest Neighborhoods|url=http://www.capitalnewyork.com/article/city-hall/2015/12/8585999/city-enrolls-68k-pre-k-big-growth-poorest-neighborhoods|website=Politico}}</ref> In 2017 de Blasio proposed an expansion of the program to \"3-K\", to include three-year-olds. Preschool for three-year-olds would start in poorer neighborhoods, with the goal of covering the entire city, if the state or federal governments provided funding.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://shakingnews.com/blog/2017/04/24/de-blasio-announces-3-k-preschool-three-year-olds/|title=Mayor de Blasio Announces 3\u2013K Preschool for Three-Year Olds \u2013 ShakingNews|date=2017-04-24|work=ShakingNews|access-date=2017-05-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==2020 presidential campaign==\n{{short description|Mayor of New York City}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox U.S. federal election campaign\n|committee = de Blasio 2020\n|campaign = [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 presidential election]] ([[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|Democratic Party primaries]])\n|candidate = '''Bill de Blasio'''<br/>[[Mayor of New York City]] (2014\u2013present)\n|logo=Bill de Blasio 2020 presidential campaign logo.svg\n|status=Launched: May 16, 2019<br /> Suspended: September 20, 2019\n|cand_id =\n|fec_date =9/30/2019\n|affiliation = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]\n|headquarters = [[New York City|New York City, New York]]\n|key_people =\n|receipts =1417609.97<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docquery.fec.gov/cgi-bin/forms/C00706697/1358932/|title=Form 3P for de Blasio 2020|website=Federal Electoral Commission|date=October 15, 2019}}</ref> \n|slogan = Working People First<ref name=\"announcement\"/>\n|chant  =\n|homepage = {{URL|https://billdeblasio.com/}}\n}}\n\nOn May 16, 2019, de Blasio announced that he would seek the Democratic nomination for president after releasing a [[YouTube]] video in which he said, \"I\u2019m Bill de Blasio, and I\u2019m running for president because it\u2019s time we put working people first.\"<ref name=\"announcement\">{{cite news|author1=Julia Marsh|author2=Nolan Hicks|author3=Rich Calder|title=Bill de Blasio officially launches 2020 presidential campaign|url=https://nypost.com/2019/05/16/bill-de-blasio-officially-launches-2020-presidential-campaign/|accessdate=May 16, 2019|work=New York Post|date=May 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190516231227/https://nypost.com/2019/05/16/bill-de-blasio-officially-launches-2020-presidential-campaign/|archive-date=May 16, 2019}}</ref> He was the first incumbent mayor of New York City to run for president since [[John Lindsay]], who ran for the Democratic nomination in [[1972 Democratic Party presidential primaries|1972]].<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/politics/2019/03/28/as-bill-de-blasio-contemplates-2020-presidential-run-there-are-possible-warning-signs-from-john-lindsay-1972-campaign|title = As De Blasio Contemplates a Presidential Run, There are Possible Warning Signs from 1972|last = Cuza|first = Bobby|work = [[NY1]]|date = March 27, 2019|accessdate = July 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring his campaign, de Blasio expressed support for increasing the federal [[minimum wage]] to $15 an hour.<ref name=\"announcement\"/> On June 19, 2019, he said, \"We have to make sure there is a peace settlement in Afghanistan; it obviously has to involve the [[Taliban]]. Until that point, I don\u2019t think it\u2019s sensible to take out our troops.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=The Democratic candidates on foreign policy |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020-election/ |work=[[Foreign Policy]]}}</ref> De Blasio advocated a [[robot tax]] and proposed to make large corporations responsible for five years of income tax from jobs that are automated away.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/460162-de-blasio-proposes-robot-tax-to-counter-automation-job-losses|title=De Blasio proposes 'robot tax' to counter job losses from automation|first=Rachel|last=Frazin|publisher=The Hill|date=2019-09-05|accessdate=2019-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/9/9/20857510/bill-de-blasio-nyc-mayor-democratic-candidate-robot-tax-fawpa-proposal|title=New York City mayor and 2020 candidate Bill de Blasio wants a robot tax|first=Adi|last=Robertson|publisher=The Verge|date=2019-09-09|accessdate=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\nDespite his large margins of victory during his mayoral races, polls found de Blasio to be largely unpopular. ''[[The New York Times]]'' described his candidacy as a \"long shot\"'','' citing his low national poll numbers and inconsistent approval ratings in New York City''.''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/01/nyregion/dante-de-blasio-son-2020.html|title=Why 'Raising a Black Son' Is a de Blasio Campaign Theme|last=Mays|first=Jeffery C.|date=2019-07-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/10/nyregion/de-blasio-poll-donald-trump.html|title=Trump's Competition for Most Unpopular Politician in New York: de Blasio|last=Neuman|first=William|date=2019-06-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> A May 2019 [[Quinnipiac University Polling Institute|Quinnipiac University poll]] of New York City voters found that 76% did not want de Blasio to run for president. An April 2019 poll placed his approval rating at 42% in the city, with 44% of voters disapproving.<ref>{{cite news |title=New York City Mayor, First Lady Get Lukewarm Grades, Quinnipiac University Poll Finds; Voters Say 4-1 De Blasio Should Not Run For President |url=https://poll.qu.edu/new-york-city/release-detail?ReleaseID=2613 |accessdate=September 20, 2019 |publisher=Quinnipiac University |date=April 3, 2019}}</ref> Just before he suspended his campaign, his approval rating had dropped to 33%, with 58% disapproving.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Enten |first1=Harry |title=Voters don't like no shot campaigns. Just ask Bill de Blasio |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/17/politics/de-blasio-approval-rating/index.html |accessdate=September 20, 2019 |publisher=CNN |date=September 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDe Blasio attempted to position himself as a progressive in contrast to the at-the-time front-runner, former [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Joe Biden]]. He was hoping to challenge U.S. Senators [[Bernie Sanders]] of [[Vermont]] and [[Elizabeth Warren]] of [[Massachusetts]], both of whom were seen as leaders of the progressive wing of the Democratic party.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cole |first1=Devan |last2=Merica |first2=Dan |title=De Blasio drops out of 2020 presidential race |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/20/politics/bill-de-blasio-ends-presidential-campaign/index.html |accessdate= September 20, 2019 |publisher=CNN |date=September 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDe Blasio's campaign failed to gain traction. He was unable to qualify for [[2020 Democratic Party presidential debates and forums|Democratic primary debates]] in September and October, which were seen as necessary events for his campaign to maintain viability. He regularly polled at 0% among Democratic primary voters, including in his home state.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bill de Blasio: New York mayor pulls out of US presidential race |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-49766266|last1=Zurcher|first1=Anthony|accessdate=September 20, 2019 |publisher=BBC News |date=September 20, 2019}}</ref> After failing to qualify for the third round of primary debates,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/04/nyregion/de-blasio-2020-president.html|title=Bill de Blasio May End 2020 Presidential Bid Next Month|last=Mays|first=Jeffery C.|date=2019-09-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-09-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> de Blasio announced the suspension of his campaign on September 20, 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cole |first1=Devan |last2=Merica |first2=Dan |title=De Blasio drops out of 2020 presidential race |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/20/politics/bill-de-blasio-ends-presidential-campaign/index.html |accessdate=September 20, 2019 |publisher=CNN |date=September 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/may/16/bill-de-blasio-2020-presidential-campaign|title=Bill de Blasio announces 2020 presidential bid|work=The Guardian|last1=Durkin|first1=Erin|date=May 16, 2019|access-date=2019-05-16|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/09/20/bill-de-blasio-ends-2020-presidential-campaign-1506011|title=Bill de Blasio ends 2020 presidential campaign|website=[[Politico]]|author=Sally Goldenburg, Quint Forgey|date=September 20, 2019|accessdate=September 20, 2019}}</ref> On February 14, 2020, de Blasio endorsed Sanders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/02/14/de-blasio-to-endorse-sanders-115138|title=De Blasio to endorse Bernie Sanders|website=Politico|last1=Goldenburg|first1=Sally|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n\n===Endorsements===\n{{main|Endorsements in the 2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries#Bill de Blasio}}\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{main|Electoral history of Bill de Blasio}}\n\n==Personal life==\nDe Blasio and his wife, activist and poet [[Chirlane McCray]], met while both were working for Mayor Dinkins' administration and married in 1994.<ref name=wsj130101/> The couple honeymooned in Cuba in violation of a U.S. travel ban.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2013/09/24/lhota-de-blasio-needs-to-explain-himself-over-cuba-honeymoon-sandinista-support/|title=Lhota: De Blasio 'Needs To Explain Himself' Over Cuba Honeymoon, Sandinista Support|date=September 24, 2013|publisher=}}</ref> They lived in [[Park Slope|Park Slope, Brooklyn]], before moving into [[Gracie Mansion]],<ref name=mansion>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/de-blasio-finally-settles-down-at-gracie-mansion-1406600111 |title=De Blasio Finally Settles Down at Gracie Mansion |author=Mara Gay  |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=July 28, 2014 |accessdate=January 11, 2015}}</ref> the traditional residence of New York City mayors. They have two children: Dante, a graduate of [[Brooklyn Technical High School]] who graduated from [[Yale University]] in 2019,<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/20/nyregion/de-blasio-prods-graduates-to-challenge-injustice-and-son-to-take-a-joke.html?_r=0 | title=De Blasio Prods Graduates to Challenge Injustice (and Son to Take a Joke) | work=The New York Times | date=June 19, 2015 | accessdate=June 20, 2015 | author=Flegenheimer, Matt}}</ref> and Chiara, a student at [[Santa Clara University]] in California.<ref name=\"announcenyt\" /><ref name=\"wsj130101\">{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323820104578215653710530398 | title=Family in the Spotlight | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | date=January 1, 2013 | author=Michael Howard Saul}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.capitalnewyork.com/article/politics/2013/08/8533045/bill-de-blasio-and-brief-history-public-school-parents-mayor | title=Bill de Blasio and a Brief History of Public-School Parents for Mayor | work=Capital New York | date=August 23, 2013 | accessdate=September 8, 2013 | author=Dana Rubinstein | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130825235646/http://www.capitalnewyork.com/article/politics/2013/08/8533045/bill-de-blasio-and-brief-history-public-school-parents-mayor | archive-date=August 25, 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Chiara addressed her [[substance abuse|drug use]] and [[depression (mood)|depression]] in late December 2013, in a four-minute video the mayor's transition team released.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cnsnews.com/news/article/ny-mayor-elects-daughter-tells-substance-abuse-0 | title=NY Mayor-elect's Daughter Tells Of Substance Abuse | author=Jonathan Lemire | date=December 24, 2013 | accessdate=December 26, 2013 | agency=[[Associated Press]] | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150322194100/http://www.cnsnews.com/news/article/ny-mayor-elects-daughter-tells-substance-abuse-0 | archive-date=March 22, 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAt {{height|ft=6|in=5}}, de Blasio is the tallest mayor in New York City's history.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/02/nyregion/a-mayor-most-everybody-looks-up-to-even-when-he-slouches.html | title=A Mayor Most Everybody Looks Up To, Even When He Slouches | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=February 1, 2014 | accessdate=October 26, 2014 | author= Michael M. Grynbaum}}</ref>\n\nDe Blasio, an [[Italian Americans|Italian American]], regularly conducts interviews, press conferences, and speeches in [[Italian language|Italian]].<ref name=\"25facts\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/25-facts-new-nyc-mayor-de-blasio-article-1.1563171|title=25 Facts About New York City's New Mayor Bill de Blasio|date=January 1, 2014|work=[[New York Daily News]]}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=NYC Mayor's Office|title=Mayor Bill de Blasio Hosts Italian Media Roundtable|date=2014-05-16|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=19DfyGrW7MM|accessdate=2018-01-23}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=askanews|title=Il sindaco di New York Bill de Blasio conquista Capri|date=2014-07-22|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BR23pwU_enA|accessdate=2018-01-23}}</ref>\n\nDespite being mayor of New York, de Blasio is a passionate fan of the [[New York Yankees]]' archrivals, having said he has a \"deep devotion\" to the [[Boston Red Sox]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/cut4/new-yorks-next-mayor-could-be-a-diehard-red-sox-fan-update-he-won/c-57786916|title=New York's next mayor could be a diehard Red Sox fan (UPDATE: he won)|website=MLB.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/redsox/2019/03/02/new-york-city-mayor-bill-blasio-remains-big-red-sox-fan/bysoeBafQjlRUIa5AN3NmN/story.html|title=New York City\u2019s mayor, Bill de Blasio, remains a big Red Sox fan - The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nDe Blasio has described himself as \"[[spiritual but not religious]].\" His mother rejected her Roman Catholic roots and did not attend church in his early life.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bill de Blasio, New York's new 'spiritual but not religious' mayor |url=https://www.ncronline.org/news/parish/bill-de-blasio-new-yorks-new-spiritual-not-religious-mayor |website=National Catholic Reporter |accessdate=8 December 2019 |language=en |date=16 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Grynbaum |first1=Michael M. |title=De Blasio, Inspired by Francis, Describes an Evolving Relationship With Faith |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/23/nyregion/de-blasio-inspired-by-francis-describes-an-evolving-relationship-with-faith.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=8 December 2019 |date=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Net worth===\nAccording to [[Forbes]], De Blasio and his wife had a net worth of $2.5 million as of August 2019.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The Net Worth Of Every 2020 Presidential Candidate |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/danalexander/2019/08/14/heres-the-net-worth-of-every-2020-presidential-candidate/#c6bd69637c58 |accessdate=23 August 2019 |magazine=Forbes |date=14 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of mayors of New York City]]\n* [[List of mayors of the 50 largest cities in the United States]]\n\n== Notes ==\n<references group=\"lower-alpha\" />\n<references group=\"nb\" />\n\n== Citations ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{Cite news |last1=Neuman |first1=William |title=De Blasio Finds Biggest Win in Pre-K, but Also Lasting Consequences |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2017-10-31 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/31/nyregion/de-blasio-universal-pre-k.html |issn=0362-4331 |df=mdy-all }}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Bill de Blasio}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.nyc.gov/mayor nyc.gov/mayor Official mayoral website]\n* [http://www.billdeblasio.com/ Official campaign website]\n* {{C-SPAN|Bill de Blasio}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-civ}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stephen DiBrienza]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[New York City Council]]<br>from the 39th district|years=2002\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Brad Lander]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Betsy Gotbaum]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[New York City Public Advocate|Public Advocate of New York City]]|years=2010\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Letitia James]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael Bloomberg]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mayor of New York City]]|years=2014\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bill Thompson (New York politician)|Bill Thompson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[Mayor of New York City]]|years=[[New York City mayoral election, 2013|2013]], [[New York City mayoral election, 2017|2017]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{United States presidential election, 2020}}\n{{Mayors of New York City}}\n{{New York cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n{{Mayors of the largest cities in the world by GDP}}\n{{Mayors of the 50 largest U.S. cities}}\n{{New York City Public Advocate}}\n{{Democratic NYC mayoral nominees}}\n}}\n{{portal bar|Biography|New York City|Politics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:De Blasio, Bill}}\n[[Category:Bill de Blasio| ]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of French descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Lucanian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of New York City]]\n[[Category:New York City Public Advocates]]\n[[Category:New York City Council members]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:New York University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Park Slope]]\n[[Category:People from Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Cambridge, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:School of International and Public Affairs, Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Truman Scholars]]\n[[Category:United States Department of Housing and Urban Development officials]]\n[[Category:2004 United States presidential electors]]\n[[Category:2012 United States presidential electors]]\n[[Category:2016 United States presidential electors]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2020 United States presidential election]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|de Blasio|others with the name|de Blasio (surname)}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Bill de Blasio\n| office = 109th [[Mayor of New York City]]\n| image = Bill de Blasio by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| predecessor = [[Michael Bloomberg]]\n| deputy = [[Anthony Shorris]]<br />[[Dean Fuleihan]]\n| signature = Bill de Blasio Signature.png\n| office2 = Member of the [[New York City Council]]<br>from the 39th district\n| predecessor2 = [[Stephen DiBrienza]]\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| office1 = 3rd [[New York City Public Advocate|Public Advocate of New York City]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Betsy Gotbaum]]\n| successor1 = [[Letitia James]]\n| successor2 = [[Brad Lander]]\n| birth_name = Warren Wilhelm Jr.\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1961|5|8}}\n| birth_place = [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.<!-- As per WP:LINKDIRECT and Template:infobox person, birthplace indicates city, state, then country. No need to spell out \"United States; 'U.S.' is fine. -->\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Chirlane McCray]]|1994}}\n| children = 2\n| residence = [[Gracie Mansion]] (Official)\n| website = {{url|nyc.gov/mayor}} (government)<br>{{url|billdeblasio.com}} (personal)\n| term_start = January 1, 2014\n| term_end = \n| term_start1 = January 1, 2010\n| term_end1 = December 31, 2013\n| term_start2 = January 1, 2002\n| term_end2 = December 31, 2009\n| education = [[New York University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Columbia University]] ([[Master of International Affairs|MIA]])\n}}\n'''Bill de Blasio''' ({{IPAc-en|d|\u026a|\u02c8|b|l|\u0251\u02d0|z|i|o\u028a}}; born '''Warren Wilhelm Jr.'''; May 8, 1961) is an American politician who has served as the [[Mayor of New York City|109th mayor]] of [[New York City]] since 2014. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he was New York City's [[New York City Public Advocate|public advocate]] from 2010 to 2013.<!-- The lack of citations is purposeful. Refer to Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Lead section#Citations for more information. Wikipedia allows there to be little to no citations in the lead area if it is cited within the main body. If there is something in the lede not cited in the main part drop a {{not found in body}} citation needed tag and it will be addressed. -->\n\nBorn in [[Manhattan]] and raised in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], de Blasio graduated from [[New York University]] and [[Columbia University]] before a brief stint as a [[campaign manager]] for [[Charles Rangel]] and [[Hillary Clinton]]. He started his career as an elected official on the [[New York City Council]], representing the 39th district in [[Brooklyn]] from 2002 to 2009. After serving one term as public advocate, he was elected [[mayor of New York City]] in [[2013 New York City mayoral election|2013]] and reelected in [[2017 New York City mayoral election|2017]].\n\nDe Blasio's policy initiatives have included new [[de-escalation]] training for officers, reduced prosecutions for [[Legality of cannabis|cannabis possession]], implementation of police [[Body worn video|body cameras]], and ending the post-[[September 11 attacks|9/11]] surveillance program of Muslim residents. In his first term, he implemented free universal [[Pre-kindergarten|Pre-K]] in the city. De Blasio has called attention to what he calls stark economic inequality in New York City, which he described as a \"[[A Tale of Two Cities|tale of two cities]]\" during his first campaign. He has supported [[Social liberalism|socially liberal]] and [[Progressive Era|progressive]] policies in regard to [[Economy of New York City|the city's economy]], urban planning, public education, police relations, and [[privatization]].\n\nDe Blasio [[Bill de Blasio 2020 presidential campaign|ran]] in the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|Democratic primaries]] for the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 presidential election]]. After registering low poll numbers and failing to qualify for the third round of primary debates, he suspended his campaign on September 20, 2019, and endorsed [[Bernie Sanders]] five months later.\n\n== Early life, family, and education ==\n[[File:Sant'Agata de'Goti (Benevento).jpg|thumb|Bill de Blasio's maternal grandfather came from the Italian city of [[Sant'Agata de' Goti]].]]\nBill de Blasio was born on May 8, 1961, in [[Manhattan]]'s [[Doctors Hospital (Manhattan)|Doctors Hospital]].<ref name=\"NY Daily News\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/25-facts-new-nyc-mayor-de-blasio-article-1.1563171|title=25 facts about new NYC Mayor de Blasio|work=NY Daily News|access-date=2018-03-04|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/11/06/nyregion/06deblasio-milestones-timeline.html|title=Milestones: Bill de Blasio|last=Corasaniti|first=Nick|website=nytimes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> He is the third son of Maria Angela ({{nee|de Blasio}}; 1917\u20132007) and Warren Wilhelm (1917\u20131979).<ref name=\"nameref1\">{{cite news|author=Dan Janison|first=|url=https://www.newsday.com/long-island/columnists/dan-janison/a-refresher-on-candidate-bill-de-blasio-1.5910726|title=A refresher on candidate Bill de Blasio|date=August 17, 2013|work=[[Newsday]]|accessdate=September 20, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Born Warren Wilhelm Jr., he changed his name to Warren de Blasio-Wilhelm in 1983 and finally to Bill de Blasio in 2001 to honor his [[Mother|maternal family]].<ref name=\"name\">{{cite news|author=Greg Smith|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/election/de-blasio-names-de-blasio-article-1.1463591|title=Mayoral Hopeful Bill de Blasio Has Had Three Different Legal Names, Court Records Show|date=September 22, 2013|work=[[New York Daily News]]}}</ref><ref name=\"wolper\">{{cite news|url=http://www.prx.org/pieces/81520-bill-de-blasio-and-allan-wolper|title=Conversations with Allan Wolper: Bill de Blasio|author=Allan Wolper|accessdate=January 21, 2012|publisher=[[Public Radio Exchange]]|agency=[[WBGO]]}}</ref> De Blasio has two older brothers, Steven and Donald.<ref name=\"NY Daily News\"/> His mother was of [[Italian American|Italian]] heritage, and his father was of [[German American|German]], English, French, and Scots-Irish ancestry.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=7W4sDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA27&dq=%22of+mixed+German,+English,+French,+and+Scotch-Irish+heritage%22|title=The Pragmatist: Bill de Blasio's Quest to Save the Soul of New York|first=Joseph P.|last=Viteritti|date=May 31, 2019|publisher=Oxford University Press|via=Google Books|isbn=9780190679507}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/johncassidy/2013/08/bill-de-plasios-moment-can-he-handle-it.html|title=Bill de Blasio's Moment: Can He Handle It?|author=John Cassidy|date=August 14, 2013|work=[[The New Yorker]]|accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0DEFD71F3AF93BA15752C0A9619C8B63|title=Paid Notice: Deaths: WILHELM, MARIA (NEE DE BLASIO)|date=January 28, 2007|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref> His paternal grandparents were Donald Wilhelm, of Ohio, and Nina (n\u00e9e Warren), of [[Iowa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/between-wwii-and-his-suicide-de-blasios-father-cold-warrior/|title=Between WWII and His Suicide, de Blasio's Father a Cold Warrior - WNYC - New York Public Radio, Podcasts, Live Streaming Radio, News|website=WNYC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clarindaherald.com/news/local/presidential-candidate-explores-family-ties-in-blanchard/article_a2a31ae2-bd37-11e9-8506-cbae64565e64.html|title=Presidential candidate explores family ties in Blanchard|last=Publisher|first=John Van Nostrand|website=Clarinda Herald-Journal - Clarinda, Iowa|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> His maternal grandfather, Giovanni, was from [[Sant'Agata de' Goti]], [[Province of Benevento|Benevento]], and his grandmother, Anna (n\u00e9e Briganti), was from [[Grassano]], [[Province of Matera|Matera]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ansa.it/web/notizie/regioni/basilicata/2013/11/05/Voto-New-York-Grassano-De-Blasio_9571916.html|title=Voto a New York: Grassano per De Blasio|date=November 5, 2013|publisher=[[Agenzia Nazionale Stampa Associata]]|language=Italian|accessdate=January 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.italymagazine.com/news/santagata-de-goti-gives-new-york-mayor-bill-de-blasio-honorary-citizenship|title=Sant'Agata de' Goti Gives New York Mayor Bill de Blasio Honorary Citizenship|website=ITALY Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> His paternal uncle, Donald George Wilhelm Jr., worked for the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] in Iran and secretly wrote the last Shah of Iran, [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]]'s, memoir.<ref name=\"democracynownewlydeclassifieddocuments\">{{cite news|url=https://www.democracynow.org/2017/7/24/newly_declassified_documents_confirm_us_backed|title=Newly Declassified Documents Confirm U.S. Backed 1953 Coup in Iran Over Oil Contracts|date=July 24, 2017|work=Democracy Now!|accessdate=July 29, 2017|quote=JUAN GONZ\u00c1LEZ: I'm just wondering if, in the documents\u2014we've got about 30 seconds\u2014you can across the name of Donald Wilhelm at all, who was a CIA guy who went to Iran after, after the overthrow of Mosaddegh, and who was actually the mayor's\u2014Mayor Bill de Blasio's uncle? ERVAND ABRAHAMIAN: Yeah, he actually co-ghostwrote the shah's memoirs.}}</ref>\n\nHis mother, Maria de Blasio, attended [[Smith College]], served in the [[Office of War Information]] during [[World War II]] and authored ''The Other Italy: The Italian Resistance in World War II'' (1988).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0DEFD71F3AF93BA15752C0A9619C8B63|title=Paid Notice \u2013 Deaths WILHELM, MARIA (NEE DE BLASIO)|work=The New York Times\"}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/election/ryrtyrt-article-1.1477493|title=De Blasio had the makings of a politician well before he even moved to New York|last=Fermino|first=Jennifer|website=nydailynews.com|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> His father, a [[Yale University]] graduate, worked as a contributing editor at ''[[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine]]'' and also served in World War II. In 1942, he enlisted in the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]] and was sent to the [[Pacific War]]. During the 82-day [[Battle of Okinawa]], a grenade detonated below his left foot, and his leg was later amputated below the knee. After receiving a [[Purple Heart]], he married Maria in 1945, and became a budget analyst for the federal government. During the 1950s, at the height of the [[Red Scare]], both Maria and Warren were accused of having a \"sympathetic interest in [[Communism]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Storrs|first=Landon R. Y.|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/archive/bill-de-blasio-not-afraid-red-scare-ghosts/|title=Bill de Blasio Is Not Afraid of Red Scare Ghosts|date=2013-10-30|access-date=2020-02-14|language=en-US|issn=0027-8378}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |last1=Hern\u00e1ndez |first1=Javier C. |title=From His Father's Decline, de Blasio 'Learned What Not to Do' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/14/nyregion/from-his-fathers-decline-de-blasio-learned-what-not-to-do.html?src=twr&pagewanted=all |accessdate=18 November 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966, the family moved to Cambridge, Massachusetts, where de Blasio began kindergarten.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2013/09/29/bill-deblasio-soars-from-cambridge-roots-new-york-city-mayor-race/Hvug4jhc9vLFxhrWbCH0DM/story.html|title=Bill deBlasio soars from Cambridge roots to New York City's mayor's race - The Boston Globe|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/election/article231646338.html|title=Democratic presidential candidate Bill de Blasio ended his campaign. Who is he?|last=|first=|date=June 25, 2019|website=Miami Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Bill and his brother Donald were then raised by Maria and her extended family. Of his early childhood, de Blasio said, \"my mother and father broke up very early on in the time I came along, and I was brought up by my mother's family\u2014that's the bottom line\u2014the de Blasio family.\"<ref name=\"wolper\" /> His father committed suicide while suffering from incurable [[lung cancer]] when Bill was 18.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/exclusive-bill-de-blasio-speaks-wnyc-about-his-fathers-suicide/|title=WNYC News Exclusive: Bill de Blasio Speaks with WNYC About His Father's Suicide|author=Anna Sale|date=September 30, 2013|accessdate=October 1, 2013|publisher=[[New York Public Radio]]}}</ref> In 1979, De Blasio graduated from [[Cambridge Rindge and Latin School]], where he served in student government and was known to peers as \"Senator Provolone\".{{Efn|His nickname came from his \"twin penchants for politics and [[Italian sandwich]]es\". De Blasio recalled it as a \"a well-meaning taunt\" that spoke to his \"overt Italian pride\" and interest in politics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://observer.com/2013/09/senator-provolone-doubles-down-on-pre-k-message/|title='Senator Provolone' Doubles Down on Pre-K Message|date=2013-09-30|work=Observer|access-date=2018-03-04|language=en-US}}</ref>}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2013/09/29/bill-deblasio-soars-from-cambridge-roots-new-york-city-mayor-race/Hvug4jhc9vLFxhrWbCH0DM/story.html|title=NYC mayoral favorite Bill de Blasio has Mass. roots - The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> He received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] from [[New York University]] in metropolitan studies, a program in [[urban studies]], and a [[Master of International Affairs]] from [[Columbia University]]'s [[School of International and Public Affairs]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ny1.com/content/politics/special_report_the_contenders/190506/the-contenders--de-blasio-s-activism-grew-upon-arrival-in-the-city|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140926023840/http://www.ny1.com/content/politics/special_report_the_contenders/190506/the-contenders--de-blasio-s-activism-grew-upon-arrival-in-the-city|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 26, 2014|title=The Contenders: De Blasio's Activism Grew Upon Arrival In The City|date=October 15, 2013|accessdate=September 25, 2014|work=[[NY1]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nyunews.com/opinion/offthird/2019/10/29/bill-de-blasio-king-of-new-york-satire-nyu|title=Off-Third: Happy Alumni Weekend From Bill de Blasio {{!}} Washington Square News|last=Hofstetter|first=Abby|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/bill-de-blasio-nyc-mayor-announces-presidential-bid|title=Bill de Blasio, NYC mayor, announces presidential bid|date=2019-05-16|website=PBS NewsHour|language=en-us|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> He is a 1981 [[Harry S. Truman Scholarship|Harry S. Truman Scholar]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.truman.gov/sites/default/files/Truman%20Annual%20Report%202012.pdf | title=The 2012 Annual Report of the Harry S. Truman Scholarship Foundation | publisher=The Harry S. Truman Scholarship Foundation | accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Early career ==\nIn 1984, de Blasio worked for the Urban Fellows Program at the [[New York City Department of Juvenile Justice]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/new-york-city-public-advocate-bill-de-blasio-article-1.1303401 | title=New York City Public Advocate Bill de Blasio | work=[[New York Daily News]] | date=March 30, 2013 | accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimesleftist\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/23/nyregion/a-mayoral-hopeful-now-de-blasio-was-once-a-young-leftist.html | title=A Mayoral Hopeful Now, de Blasio Was Once a Young Leftist | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=September 22, 2013 | accessdate=September 24, 2013 | author=Javier C. Hern\u00e1ndez}}</ref> In 1987, shortly after completing graduate school at Columbia, de Blasio was hired to work as a political organizer by the [[Quixote Center]] in [[Maryland]]. In 1988, he traveled with the Quixote Center to [[Nicaragua]] for 10 days to help distribute food and medicine during the [[Nicaraguan Revolution]]. De Blasio was an ardent supporter of the ruling [[Socialism|socialist]] government, the [[Sandinista National Liberation Front]], which was opposed by the [[Foreign policy of the Ronald Reagan administration#Nicaragua|Reagan administration]] at the time.<ref name=\"nytimesleftist\" /> After returning from Nicaragua, de Blasio moved to New York City, where he worked for a [[nonprofit organization]] focused on improving health care in Central America.<ref name=\"nytimesleftist\" /> He continued to support the Sandinistas in his spare time and joined a group called the Nicaragua Solidarity Network of Greater New York, which held meetings and fundraisers for the Sandinista political party.<ref name=\"nytimesleftist\" /> De Blasio's introduction to city politics came in 1989, when he worked as a volunteer coordinator for [[David Dinkins]]' [[New York City mayoral elections#1989|mayoral campaign]].<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/12/06/bill-de-blasio-for-nyc-mayor_n_2251023.html | title=Bill de Blasio For NYC Mayor: Can The Public Advocate Go From Master Strategist To Mister Mayor? | work=[[The New York Observer]] | date=December 6, 2012 | accessdate=August 13, 2013 | author=Colin Campbell}}</ref> Following the campaign, de Blasio was an aide in [[New York City Hall|City Hall]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/new-york-news/political-education-bill-de-blasio | title=The Political Education Of Bill de Blasio | work=[[The Jewish Week]] | date=July 17, 2013 | accessdate=August 13, 2013 | author=Adam Dickter | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821204142/http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/new-york-news/political-education-bill-de-blasio | archivedate=August 21, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> In 1990, he described himself as an advocate for [[democratic socialism]] when asked about his goals for society.<ref name=\"nytimesleftist\" />\n\nU.S. Representative [[Charles Rangel]] tapped de Blasio to be his campaign manager for his successful [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1994#New York|1994]] reelection bid.<ref>{{cite news|author=Catalina Camia|title=Charlie Rangel's rival endorsed by 'New York Times'|url=http://onpolitics.usatoday.com/2014/06/19/rangel-endorsement-espaillat-new-york-times/|accessdate=June 20, 2014|work=[[USA Today]]|date=June 19, 2014}}</ref> In 1997, he was appointed to serve as the regional director for the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development]] (HUD) for New York and New Jersey under the administration of President [[Bill Clinton]]. As the tri-state region's highest-ranking HUD official, de Blasio led a small executive staff and took part in outreach to residents of substandard housing.<ref>{{cite news|author=James Warren|title=De Blasio's Early Audition|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/opinion/de-blasio-early-audition-article-1.1496691|accessdate=November 6, 2013|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=October 27, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.citylimits.org/content/articles/viewarticle.cfm?article_id=2174 | title=Dream Off? | work=City Limits | date=April 1, 2001 | author=Matt Pacenzat | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071108050422/http://www.citylimits.org/content/articles/viewarticle.cfm?article_id=2174 | archivedate=November 8, 2007 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 1999, he was elected to be a school board member for Brooklyn School District 15.<ref name=\"pubad\">{{cite web|url=http://archive.advocate.nyc.gov/about-bill-de-blasio|title=About Bill De Blasio|work=Office of the Public Advocate|accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref> The following year, he served as campaign manager for [[Hillary Clinton]]'s successful [[United States Senate election in New York, 2000|United States Senate bid]].<ref name=\"pubad\" />\n\n==New York City Council (2002\u20132009)==\n\n===Elections===\n[[File:CityCouncilChambersAT.jpg|thumb|The [[New York City Council]] chambers, where de Blasio served from 2002 to 2009.]]\nIn 2001, de Blasio ran for the [[New York City Council]]'s 39th district, which includes the [[Brooklyn]] neighborhoods of [[Borough Park, Brooklyn|Borough Park]], [[Carroll Gardens, Brooklyn|Carroll Gardens]], [[Cobble Hill, Brooklyn|Cobble Hill]], [[Gowanus, Brooklyn|Gowanus]], [[Kensington, Brooklyn|Kensington]], [[Park Slope]], and [[Windsor Terrace, Brooklyn|Windsor Terrace]]. He won the crowded primary election with 32% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=555974 | title=NYC Council 39 \u2013 D Primary Race \u2013 September 25, 2001 | publisher=Our Campaigns | accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref> In the general election, he defeated Republican Robert A. Bell, 71% to 17%.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=86146 | title=New York City Council 39 Race \u2013 November 6, 2001 | publisher=Our Campaigns | accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref> He was reelected with 72% of the vote in 2002<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=84491 | title=New York City Council 39 Race \u2013 November 4, 2003 | publisher=Our Campaigns | accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref> and with 83% of the vote in 2005.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=318808 | title=New York City Council 39 Race \u2013 November 8, 2005 | publisher=Our Campaigns | accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nOn the City Council, de Blasio passed legislation to prevent landlord discrimination against tenants who hold federal housing subsidy vouchers, and helped pass the HIV/AIDS Housing Services Law, improving housing services for low-income New Yorkers living with HIV/AIDS.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=446983&GUID=0F78AE65-DC68-4CDC-AD40-1F8CC8B5B0C9 | title=Filing, on behalf of the Council, an amicus brief in support of the plaintiffs in the litigation between individual tenants and landlords captioned Rosario v. Diagonal Realty LLC. (Res 0803-2007) | publisher=New York City Council Legislative Research Center |accessdate=January 21, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=443560&GUID=56C7EA40-5F32-4346-B499-631BBE0D8377 | title=Processing of applications for permanent housing for clients of the HIV and AIDS Services Administration. (Int 0535-2005) | publisher=New York City Council Legislative Research Center | accessdate=January 21, 2013}}</ref> As head of the city council's General Welfare Committee, de Blasio helped pass the Gender-Based Discrimination Protection Law to protect transgender New Yorkers, and passed the Domestic Partnership Recognition Law to ensure that same-sex couples in a legal partnership could enjoy the same legal benefits as heterosexual couples in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=446726&GUID=68E087CC-2147-401A-983B-461A37265048 | title=Domestic Partnerships. (Int 0501-2007) | publisher=New York City Council Legislative Research Center | accessdate=January 20, 2013}}</ref> During his tenure, the General Welfare Committee also passed the Benefits Translation for Immigrants Law, which helped non-English speakers receive free language-assistance services when accessing government programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=437168&GUID=482D9A0F-EB57-4D84-BFEA-B49CF178E778| title=Provision of language assistance services. (Int 0038-2002) | publisher=New York City Council Legislative Research Center | accessdate=January 21, 2013}}</ref> He served on the education, [[environmental protection]], finance, and technology committees and chaired the [[Common good|general welfare]] committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/DepartmentDetail.aspx?ID=6903&GUID=5D939F6A-A26A-456C-BF68-2FE3903139C8&R=b270048d-b10a-40de-9b4a-05cab0cf8ea4 |publisher=[[The New York City Council]]  |title=Committee on Education}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/DepartmentDetail.aspx?ID=6904&GUID=F70A0DA9-3E66-4BE2-A777-8F8BE6F41E5D |publisher=[[The New York City Council]]  |title=Committee on Environmental Protection}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/DepartmentDetail.aspx?ID=6905&GUID=0D8F5FED-57D4-42FA-AA98-0F26D09E7158&R=c81924e4-f514-4ef6-9bda-777433fbefff|publisher=[[The New York City Council]]  |title=Committee on Finance}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/DepartmentDetail.aspx?ID=6906&GUID=3A095E28-DEC4-4B6A-A2A3-E5C95F87200D |publisher=[[The New York City Council]]  |title=Committee on General Welfare}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://legistar.council.nyc.gov/DepartmentDetail.aspx?ID=8866&GUID=72EEA817-E6FF-4051-B853-BC1DAD04E8CC&R=0f5cb7f0-ac18-4302-8bb5-319f698d4fca|publisher=[[The New York City Council]]  |title=Committee on Technology}}</ref>\n\n==New York City Public Advocate (2010\u20132013)==\n\n===2009 election===\n{{Main|2009 New York City Public Advocate election}}{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| width = \n| image1 = Bill de Blasio Inauguration.jpg\n| width1 = 220\n| caption1 = De Blasio speaking at his January 2010 inauguration\n| image2 = Bill de Blasio & Avigdor Lieberman.jpg\n| width2 = 220\n| caption2 = Bill de Blasio and Israeli Foreign Minister [[Avigdor Lieberman]] in 2012\n}}In November 2008, de Blasio announced his candidacy for [[New York City Public Advocate]], entering a crowded field of candidates vying for the Democratic nomination that included former Public Advocate [[Mark J. Green]]. ''[[The New York Times]]'' endorsed de Blasio, praising his efforts to improve public schools and \"[help] many less-fortunate New Yorkers with food stamps, housing, and children's health\" as a councilmember. The paper declared de Blasio the best candidate for the job \"because he has shown that he can work well with [[Michael Bloomberg|Mayor Bloomberg]] when it makes sense to do so while vehemently and eloquently opposing him when justified.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/29/opinion/29sat4.html | title=For New York City Public Advocate | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=August 29, 2009 | accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref> His candidacy was endorsed by then Public Advocate [[Betsy Gotbaum]], former [[New York City Mayor|Mayor]] [[Ed Koch]], former [[New York Governor|Governor]] [[Mario Cuomo]], and [[Al Sharpton|Reverend Al Sharpton]].<ref name=\"nyt-sharpton\">{{cite news | url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/07/16/snubbing-green-gently-sharpton-backs-de-blasio/ | title=Snubbing Green (Gently), Sharpton Backs de Blasio | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=July 16, 2009 | accessdate=November 6, 2013 | author=David W. Chen}}</ref>\n\nOn September 15, 2009, de Blasio finished first in the Democratic primary, garnering 33% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/16/nyregion/16advocate.html | title=De Blasio and Green in Runoff for Advocate | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=September 16, 2009 | author=Julie Bosman}}</ref> He won the runoff primary election on September 29, defeating Green, 62% to 38%.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=560827 | title=NYC Public Advocate \u2013 D Runoff Race |date= September 29, 2009 | publisher=Our Campaigns | accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref> In the November 3 general election, de Blasio defeated Republican [[Alex Zablocki]], 78% to 18%.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=542116 | title=New York City Public Advocate Race | date=November 3, 2009 | publisher=Our Campaigns | accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2009/results/index.html | title=2009 Election Results | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=November 9, 2009 | accessdate=August 8, 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091107034641/http://elections.nytimes.com/2009/results/index.html | archivedate=November 7, 2009 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> De Blasio was inaugurated as New York City's third [[Public Advocate]] on January 1, 2010. In his inauguration speech he criticized the Bloomberg administration, especially its homelessness and education policies.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/02/nyregion/02deblasio.html | title=Public Advocate Takes a Challenging Tone, and Thoughts of 2013 Are Near | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=January 1, 2010 | accessdate=May 11, 2010 | author=Julie Bosman}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n====Affordable housing====\nIn June 2010, de Blasio opposed a [[New York City Housing Authority]] decision to cut the number of [[Section 8 (housing)|Section 8]] vouchers issued to low-income New Yorkers. The cut was announced after the NYCHA discovered it could not pay for approximately 2,600 vouchers that had already been issued.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/public-advocate-bill-de-blasio-section-8-housing-subsidies-cuts-cost-city-article-1.183500 | title=Public Advocate Bill de Blasio: Section 8 housing Subsidies Cuts Will Cost City | work=New York Daily News | date=June 20, 2010 | accessdate=August 11, 2015 | author=Einhorn, Erin}}</ref> Two months later, he launched an online \"NYC's Worst Landlords Watchlist\" to track landlords who failed to repair dangerous living conditions. The list drew widespread media coverage and highlighted hundreds of landlords across the city. \"We want these landlords to feel like they're being watched,\" de Blasio told the ''[[New York Daily News]]''. \"We need to shine a light on these folks to shame them into action.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/new-website-aims-shine-light-city-worst-slumlords-article-1.206621 | title=New Website Aims to Shine Light on City's Worst Slumlords | work=[[New York Daily News]] | date=August 30, 2010 | accessdate=July 21, 2012 | author1=Ben Chapman |author2=Erin Einhorn}}</ref>\n\n====Campaign finance====\n{{See also|Campaign finance in the United States}}\nDe Blasio has criticized ''[[Citizens United v. Federal Election Commission|Citizens United]]'', the January 2010 U.S. [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] decision that overturned parts of the [[Bipartisan Campaign Reform Act|2002 McCain-Feingold Bipartisan Campaign Reform Act]]. He argued that \"corporations should not be allowed to buy elections\" and launched a national campaign by elected officials to reverse the decision's effects.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2010/09/bill-de-blasio-citizens-united-avenger | title=Bill de Blasio: Citizens United Avengers | work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]] | author=Suzy Khimm | date=September 22, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n====Education====\nAs public advocate, de Blasio repeatedly criticized Bloomberg's education policies. He called for [[Cathie Black]], Bloomberg's nominee for [[New York City Schools Chancellor]], to take part in public forums and criticized her for sending her own children to private schools.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/bill-de-blasio-unimpressed-cathie-black-hedging-public-school-do-over-kids-blog-entry-1.1682072 | title=Bill de Blasio Unimpressed With Cathie Black's Hedging On A Public School Do-Over For Her Kids | work=[[New York Daily News]] | date=December 8, 2010 | accessdate=January 11, 2015 | author=Celeste Katz}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20101115/manhattan/public-advocate-wants-cathie-black-hold-open-meeting-with-parents-administrators | title=Public Advocate Wants Cathie Black to Hold Open Meeting With Parents, Administrators | work=DNAinfo New York | date=November 15, 2010 | accessdate=October 16, 2013 | author=Jill Colvin | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021212015/http://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20101115/manhattan/public-advocate-wants-cathie-black-hold-open-meeting-with-parents-administrators | archivedate=October 21, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> In March 2010, he spoke against an [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|MTA]] proposal to eliminate free MetroCards for students, arguing the measure would take a significant toll on school attendance.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://pubadvocate.nyc.gov/news/2010-02-18/protests-against-mta-continue-effort-save-student-metrocards | title=Protects Against the MTA Continue in Effort to Save Student MetroCards | publisher=Office of the Public Advocate | date=February 18, 2010 | access-date=May 8, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017024431/http://pubadvocate.nyc.gov/news/2010-02-18/protests-against-mta-continue-effort-save-student-metrocards | archive-date=October 17, 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Three months later, he voiced opposition to the mayor's proposed budget containing more than $34 million in cuts to childcare services.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://archive.advocate.nyc.gov/daycare | title=Public Advocate de Blasio & NYC Parents Fight to Protect City's Daycare Centers | publisher=Office of the Public Advocate}}</ref> In June 2011, de Blasio outlined a plan to improve the process of school co-location, by which multiple schools are housed in one building. His study found community input was often ignored by the city's Department of Education, resulting in top-down decisions made without sufficient regard for negative impacts. He outlined eight solutions to improve the process and incorporate community opinion into the decision-making process.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://archive.advocate.nyc.gov/news/2011-07-20/consensus-reform-plan-collaborative-school-co-locations | title=Consensus for Reform: A Plan for Collaborative School Co-Locations | publisher=Office of the Public Advocate | date=July 20, 2011}}</ref> The same month, he also criticized a Bloomberg administration proposal to lay off more than 4,600 teachers to balance the city's budget; de Blasio organized parents and communities against the proposed cuts and staged a last-minute call-a-thon. Bloomberg restored the funding, agreeing to find savings elsewhere in the budget.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://pubadvocate.nyc.gov/news/2011-06-20/11th-hour-push-public-advocate-de-blasio-brings-voice-parents-city-hall | title=In 11th Hour Push, Public Advocate de Blasio Brings Voice of Parents to City Hall | publisher=Office of the NYC Public Advocate | date=June 20, 2011 | accessdate=January 1, 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102200012/http://pubadvocate.nyc.gov/news/2011-06-20/11th-hour-push-public-advocate-de-blasio-brings-voice-parents-city-hall | archive-date=January 2, 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Mayor of New York City (2014\u2013present)==\n\n===2013 election===\n{{Main|2013 New York City mayoral election}}[[File:Bill de Blasio and family.jpg|thumb|250px|Bill de Blasio with his wife, Chirlane (left), and two children at a rally in New York City in 2013]]On January 27, 2013, de Blasio announced his candidacy for mayor of New York City in the [[New York City mayoral election, 2013|fall election]].<ref name=\"announcenyt\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/28/nyregion/bill-de-blasio-kicks-off-campaign-for-mayor.html | title=De Blasio, Announcing Mayoral Bid, Pledges to Help People City Hall Forgot | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=January 27, 2013 | accessdate=July 30, 2013 | author=David W. Chen}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2013/01/27/de-blasio-announces-mayoral-campaign | title=De Blasio Announces Mayoral Campaign | work=[[CBS News]] | date=January 27, 2013 | accessdate=January 27, 2013}}</ref> The Democratic primary race included nine candidates, among them Council Speaker [[Christine Quinn]], former [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Anthony Weiner]], and former [[New York City Comptroller]] and [[New York City mayoral election, 2009|2009 mayoral nominee]] [[Bill Thompson (New York)|Bill Thompson]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nyccfb.info/reports/candidate_13.htm | title=Candidates 2013 Citywide Elections | publisher=New York City Campaign Finance Board | access-date=July 31, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053635/http://www.nyccfb.info/reports/candidate_13.htm | archive-date=September 21, 2013 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/04/14/nyregion/mayoral-candidates.html | title=A Viewer's Guide to the Mayoral Candidates | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=April 13, 2013 | accessdate=July 30, 2013 | author1=Michael Barbaro |author2=Tom Giratikanon }}</ref> After Weiner joined the race in April, early polls showed de Blasio in fourth or fifth among the candidates.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} Despite his poor starting position, de Blasio gained the endorsements of major Democratic clubs, such as the [[Barack Obama Democratic Club of Upper Manhattan]], and New York City's largest [[trade union]], [[Service Employees International Union|SEIU]] [[1199SEIU United Healthcare Workers East|Local 1199]]. Celebrities such as [[Alec Baldwin]] and [[Sarah Jessica Parker]] endorsed him, as did prominent politicians such as former Vermont Governor [[Howard Dean]] and U.S. Congresswoman [[Yvette Clarke]].<ref name=\"nydaily-sarahjessicaparker\">{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/sarah-jessica-parker-backs-de-blasio-mayor-article-1.1325650 | title=Sarah Jessica Parker Backs Bill de Blasio | work=[[New York Daily News]] | date=April 23, 2013 | accessdate=July 31, 2013 | author=Erin Durkin}}</ref><ref name=\"nydaily-alecbaldwin\">{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/alec-baldwin-backs-bill-de-blasio-nyc-mayor-article-1.1215458 | title=Alec Baldwin Names Bill De Blasio as His Pick for Next New York City Mayor, Knocks Christine Quinn as 'Untrustworthy' | work=[[New York Daily News]] | date=December 7, 2012 | accessdate=July 31, 2013 | author=Kristen A. Lee}}</ref> By August, singer [[Harry Belafonte]] and actress [[Susan Sarandon]] had endorsed de Blasio.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2013/08/celebrities-in-bill-de-blasio-new-video-ad.html | title=All the Celebrities in Bill de Blasio's New Ad|work=[[New York Magazine]] | date=August 27, 2013 | accessdate=September 20, 2013 | author=Joe Coscarelli}}</ref>\n\nDe Blasio gained media attention during the campaign when he and a dozen others, including city councillor [[Stephen Levin (councillor)|Stephen Levin]], were arrested while protesting the closing of [[University Hospital of Brooklyn at Long Island College Hospital|Long Island College Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/brooklyn/pols-rally-save-long-island-college-hospital-article-1.1402934 | title=Bill de Blasio, Dan Squadron and Other Brooklyn Pols Storm LICH After SUNY Sends in Closure Plan | work=[[New York Daily News]] | date=July 18, 2013 | accessdate=July 31, 2013 | author=Simone Weichselbaum}}</ref> De Blasio and Levin were released a few hours later with disorderly conduct summonses. Fellow Democratic mayoral hopefuls Weiner and City Comptroller [[John Liu]] were also at the protest but were not arrested.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/11/nyregion/3-rivals-join-a-protest-but-just-one-wants-to-be-arrested-and-is.html | title=De Blasio Arrested, Just as He Wanted | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=July 10, 2013 | accessdate=July 30, 2013 | author=Anemona Hartocollis}}</ref>\n\nDuring his mayoral campaign, de Blasio outlined a plan to raise taxes on residents earning more than $500,000 a year to pay for universal [[pre-kindergarten]] programs and to expand after-school programs at [[middle school]]s.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-10-04/de-blasio-proposes-nyc-tax-surcharge-on-wealthy-for-schools.html | title=De Blasio Proposes NYC Tax Surcharge on Wealthy for Schools | work=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=October 4, 2012 | accessdate=August 14, 2013 | author=Henry Goldman}}</ref><ref name=\"wfuv\">{{cite news | url=http://www.wfuv.org/news/news-politics/130812/close-nycs-mayoral-candidates-bill-de-blasio-d | title=Up Close With NYC's Mayoral Candidates: Bill de Blasio (D) | work=WFUV 90.7 FM Public Radio from Fordham University | date=August 12, 2013 | accessdate=August 14, 2013 | author=Ann Pierret}}</ref> He also pledged to invest $150 million annually into the [[City University of New York]] to lower tuition and improve degree programs.<ref name=\"wfuv\"/> In September 2013, de Blasio voiced his opposition to [[Charter schools in the United States|charter schools]], maintaining that their funding saps resources from classes like art, physical education and after-school programs. He outlined a plan to discontinue the policy of offering rent-free space to the city's 183 charter schools and to place a moratorium on the co-location of charter schools in public school buildings.<ref name=\"nyt-charterschools\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/09/nyregion/charter-schools-fear-having-de-blasio-for-a-landlord.html | title=City's Charter Schools Fear Having de Blasio for a Landlord | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=October 8, 2013 | accessdate=November 6, 2013 | author=Javier C. Hern\u00e1ndez}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, the de Blasio campaign released a television advertisement featuring de Blasio's then-15-year-old son, Dante, talking about his father's plans to \"'really break from the Bloomberg years.'\"<ref name=\"Gray\">{{cite web | url=http://nation.time.com/2013/09/11/the-ad-that-won-the-new-york-mayors-race/ | title= The Ad That Won the New York Mayor's Race| work=Time Magazine | last=Gray | first=Eliza | date=September 11, 2013 | accessdate=January 31, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/election/bill-de-blasio-nimble-campaign-made-mayor-article-1.1507754| title= How Bill de Blasio's nimble 2013 mayoral election campaign got Democratic Party back into Gracie Mansion| work=New York Daily News | last=Karni | first=Annie | date=November 5, 2013 | accessdate=January 31, 2018}}</ref> [[Time (magazine)|TIME]] called it \"The Ad That Won the New York Mayor's Race,\" noting that after it ran, \"de Blasio built a steady lead that he never relinquished.\"<ref name=\"Gray\"/> Quinn was attacked by a number of groups including [[NYCLASS (New Yorkers for Clean, Livable, and Safe Streets)|NYCLASS]] with their \"Anybody But Quinn\" campaign, allowing de Blasio to move up in the polls. By mid-August he emerged as the new leader among the Democrats.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/14/nyregion/new-poll-suggests-that-de-blasio-is-now-first-among-voters.html | title=New Poll Suggests That de Blasio Is Now First Among Voters | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=August 14, 2013 | accessdate=September 20, 2013 | author=David W. Chen}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/pac-pummels-nyc-mayor-wannabe-quinn-article-1.1386683|title=PAC pummels NYC mayor wannabe Quinn|work=NY Daily News|access-date=2017-05-04|language=en}}</ref> He reached 43% in a Quinnipiac poll released a week before the primary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quinnipiac.edu/news-and-events/quinnipiac-university-poll/new-york-city/release-detail?ReleaseID=1948 |title=De Blasio Surges Past 40% In New York City Mayoral Race |publisher=[[Quinnipiac University]] |date=September 3, 2013|accessdate=January 11, 2015}}</ref> Preliminary results of the September 11 primary showed de Blasio with 40.1% of the votes, slightly more than the 40% needed to avoid a runoff.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/race-for-new-york-mayors-office-sees-bill-de-blasio-edging-it-8810245.html | title=Race for New York Mayor's office sees Bill De Blasio edging it | work=[[The Independent]] | date=September 11, 2013 | accessdate=September 11, 2013 | author=Nikhil Kumar}}</ref>\n\nOn September 16, second-place finisher [[Bill Thompson (New York)|Bill Thompson]] conceded, citing the unlikelihood of winning a runoff even if uncounted absentee and military ballots pushed de Blasio below the 40% threshold. Thompson's withdrawal made de Blasio the Democratic nominee against Republican [[Joe Lhota]] in the general election.<ref name=\"nyt-thompsoncedes\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/17/nyregion/thompson-to-concede-to-de-blasio-in-mayoral-primary.html?hp | title=A Display of Democratic Unity as Thompson Cedes to de Blasio | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=September 16, 2013 | accessdate=September 20, 2013 | author=Michael M. Grynbaum}}</ref> Exit polls showed that the issue that most aided de Blasio's primary victory was his unequivocal opposition to \"stop and frisk.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nybooks.com/blogs/nyrblog/2013/sep/23/how-different-de-blasio/|title=How Different is de Blasio?|author=Michael Greenberg|newspaper=[[New York Review of Books]]|date=September 23, 2013}}</ref> After the primary, de Blasio was announced as the nominee of the [[Working Families Party]].<ref name=\"WFP\">{{cite press release | url=http://www.workingfamiliesparty.org/2013/09/working-families-party-leaders-back-bill-de-blasio-for-mayor-of-new-york-city | title=Working Families Party Leaders Back Bill de Blasio for Mayor of New York City | publisher=[[Working Families Party]] | date=September 12, 2013 | accessdate=September 16, 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007052042/http://www.workingfamiliesparty.org/2013/09/working-families-party-leaders-back-bill-de-blasio-for-mayor-of-new-york-city/ | archivedate=October 7, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> In the general election, he defeated Lhota in a landslide with 72.2% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vote.nyc.ny.us/downloads/pdf/results/2013/2013GeneralElection/00001100000Citywide%20Mayor%20Citywide%20Recap.pdf |title=Mayor \u2013 Citywide Recap | publisher= NYC Board of Elections | accessdate=November 5, 2013}}</ref> Voter turnout for the election set a new record low of only 24% of registered voters, which ''[[The New York Times]]'' attributed to the expectation of a landslide in the heavily Democratic city.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/news/election-2013/2013/11/06/new-york-turnout-appears-headed-for-record-low | title=New York: Voter Turnout Appears to Be Record Low | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=November 6, 2013 | author=Sam Roberts}}</ref> The campaign finance activities of the de Blasio 2013 committee reportedly became the subject of a federal corruption investigation led by U.S. Attorney [[Preet Bharara]]. Other government authorities were also involved in investigations, some of which reportedly overlapped, including whether campaign donors received preferential treatment from City Hall.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2016/06/guide-to-mayor-de-blasios-investigations.html | title=A Beginner's Guide to the Many Investigations Involving Mayor Bill de Blasio | work=New York | date=June 9, 2016 | accessdate=November 6, 2016 | author=Caroline Bankoff}}</ref> The investigation ended in March 2017 with no charges.\n\n=== 2017 election ===\n{{Main|2017 New York City mayoral election}}\nIn 2017, de Blasio won reelection to a second term, defeating Republican Assemblywoman [[Nicole Malliotakis]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/new-york-general-elections|title=Election Results: De Blasio Wins Second Term as New York City Mayor|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> 65.2%-27.2%.<ref>https://www.vote.nyc.ny.us/downloads/pdf/election_results/2017/20171107General%20Election/00001100000Citywide%20Mayor%20Citywide%20Recap.pdf</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n[[File:The Prime Minister, Shri Narendra Modi meeting the Mayor of New York, Mr. Bill de Blasio, in New York on September 26, 2014.jpg|thumb|De Blasio and Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] in New York on September 26, 2014]]\nDe Blasio was sworn into office on January 1, 2014, by former President [[Bill Clinton]]. In his inaugural address, he reiterated his campaign pledge to address \"economic and social inequalities\" within the city.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/02/nyregion/bill-de-blasio-inauguration.html | title=Taking Office, de Blasio Vows to Fix Inequity | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=January 1, 2014 | author=Michael M. Grynbaum}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' noted that \"The elevation of an assertive, tax-the-rich liberal to the nation's most prominent municipal office has fanned hopes that hot-button causes like universal prekindergarten and low-wage worker benefits... could be aided by the imprimatur of being proved workable in New York.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/01/nyregion/de-blasio-draws-all-liberal-eyes-to-new-york-city.html | title=De Blasio Draws All Liberal Eyes to New York City | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=December 31, 2013 | author=Michael M. Grynbaum.}}</ref>\n[[File:No NYC Hypocrisy rally & march (33783880945).jpg|thumb|''No NYC Hypocrisy'' rally in April 2017]]\n\nIn the first weeks of de Blasio's mayoralty, New York City was struck by a series of snowstorms.<ref name=\"politicker20140212\">{{cite news | url=http://politicker.com/2014/02/de-blasio-adds-35-million-to-snow-removal-budget/ | title=De Blasio Adds $35 Million to Snow Removal Budget | work=[[Politicker]] | date=February 12, 2014 | accessdate=February 15, 2014 | author=Kelly Weill}}</ref> De Blasio was criticized by [[Upper East Side]] residents who said efforts to clear the snow seemed to be lagging in their neighborhood.<ref name=nydn20140123>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/mayor-de-blasio-dismisses-claim-plows-skipped-ues-article-1.1587823 | title=Mayor de Blasio Admits Mistakes in Snow Removal on New York's Upper East Side | work=[[New York Daily News]] | date=January 23, 2014 | accessdate=February 15, 2014 | author1=Annie Karni |author2=Edgar Sandoval |author3=Corky Siamaszk}}</ref> De Blasio apologized the next day, saying that \"more could have been done to serve the Upper East Side.\"<ref name=nydn20140123/> On February 13, heavy snowstorms hit the East Coast again. Under instructions from De Blasio and School Chancellor [[Carmen Fari\u00f1a]], the city's public schools were kept open. This decision was criticized by teacher unions, parents and the media as up to 9.5 inches of snow fell that day.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/14/us/winter-storm.html | title=Winter Offensive Takes Toll on East Coast | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=February 13, 2014 | accessdate=February 15, 2014 | author=Marc Santora}}</ref> By the middle of February, the city had added $35 million to the [[New York City Department of Sanitation|Sanitation Department]]'s budget for snow removal.<ref name=\"politicker20140212\"/>\n\nIn July 2014, de Blasio signed a bill that created [[City identification card|municipal identification cards]] for all residents regardless of immigration status, helping them secure access to city services.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mayor de Blasio Signs Legislation to Create Municipal ID Card|url=http://www1.nyc.gov/office-of-the-mayor/news/345-14/mayor-de-blasio-signs-legislation-create-municipal-id-card |publisher=City of New York|date=July 20, 2014|accessdate=September 16, 2014}}</ref> Homeless New Yorkers are also eligible to obtain the [[IDNYC]] cards so long as they register a \"care of\" address. The IDNYC card program was launched January 1, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsday.com/news/new-york/nyc-muni-id-details-unveiled-1.9685723 |title=NYC municipal ID card details unveiled |work=[[Newsday]] |date=December 5, 2014 |accessdate=January 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDe Blasio has had mixed approval ratings during his mayoralty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://poll.qu.edu/new-york-city/release-detail?ReleaseID=2475|title=QU Poll Release Detail|publisher=[[Quinnipiac University]]|website=QU Poll|language=en|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20170731/POLITICS/170739990/mayor-bill-de-blasios-popularity-takes-a-dive-amid-subway-crisis-as-quinnipiac-poll-finds-his-approval-at-about-50-percent|title=De Blasio's popularity takes a dive amid subway crisis|last=Bredderman|first=Will|work=Crain's New York Business|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/06/magazine/mayor-bill-de-blasio-2020-campaign.html|title=How Bill de Blasio Went From Progressive Hope to Punching Bag|last=Flegenheimer|first=Matt|date=2019-08-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-09-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n====9/11 attacks====\nIn 2016, de Blasio expressed support for the [[Justice Against Sponsors of Terrorism Act]] that would allow relatives of victims of the [[September 11 attacks]] to sue [[Saudi Arabia]] for its government's [[Alleged Saudi role in September 11 attacks|alleged role in the attacks]].<ref>\"[http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/saudi-government-didn-fund-terrorists-obama-aide-article-1.2605678 Mayor de Blasio joins Democrats in calling on President Obama to go after Saudi Arabia on 9/11 ties]\". ''[[New York Daily News]]''. April 19, 2016.</ref>\n\n==== Affordable housing ====\nA key aim of de Blasio's mayoral tenure has been to build more affordable housing, with a goal of 200,000 units.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.nyc.gov/site/housing/problem/problem.page|title=Problem \u2013 NYC Housing Plan|website=www1.nyc.gov|access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref> His plan passed the City Council,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20161019/EXPERT/161019847/why-mayor-bill-de-blasios-affordable-housing-plan-is-in-trouble-as-opponents-of-rezoning-such-as-council-member-ydanis-rodriguez-and-critics-like-jimmy-van-bremer-mount-opposition|title=Why de Blasio's affordable housing plan is in trouble [in 5 steps]|last=Anuta|first=Joe|work=Crain's New York Business|access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref> but has been controversial. Groups such as the [[New York Communities for Change]] have come out against certain aspects of the plan, arguing that it promotes [[gentrification]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://shakingnews.com/blog/2017/05/03/affordable-for-whom-nyc-affordable-housing/|title=Affordable for Whom?&nbsp;The Tragically&nbsp;Misguided Arguments about Affordable Housing in NYC \u2013 ShakingNews|date=2017-05-03|work=ShakingNews|access-date=2017-05-04|language=en-US}}</ref> Relatedly, in April 2017 the state government renewed the [[421-a tax abatement|421-a tax abatement program]] after unions and developers made a deal on wages in qualifying construction projects.<ref name=\"421-a\">{{cite news|last1=Fink|first1=Zach|title=Tax Abatement for Developers Has Passed in State Budget, But Critics are Not Sold|url=http://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/politics/2017/04/15/421-a-tax-abatement-developers-state-budget-critics-skeptical.html|accessdate=June 5, 2017|publisher=NY 1|date=April 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Atlantic Avenue (New York City)|Atlantic Avenue]], in the [[East New York]] neighborhood of [[Brooklyn]], which has been scarred by decades of poverty and crime, was the first test and focus of de Blasio's strategy on affordable housing, one of the policy initiatives central to his platform of reducing inequality. Since 2012, city planners have been working to bring residents to forums to consult on the process. The plan is to \"invite developers to build up local streets in exchange for more units of affordable housing.\" They will invest in new trees, parks, sidewalks, schools, shops, and restaurants that will lead to better services.<ref name=\"NYT_2015\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/04/nyregion/an-obstacle-to-mayor-de-blasios-affordable-housing-plan-neighborhood-resistance.html?smid=tw-nytimes | title=Some See Risk in de Blasio's Bid to Add Housing | work=New York Times | date=February 3, 2015 | accessdate=February 8, 2015 | location=New York | pages=A1 | first2=Mireya | last2=Navarro | first1=Vivian | last1=Yee}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, de Blasio and Secretary of Housing and Urban Development [[Ben Carson]] reached an agreement to change the operations of the New York City Housing Authority. The agreement created \"specific requirements and milestones to address the serious health and safety hazards at NYCHA properties, including lead-based paint, mold, heat, vermin, among others\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2019/01/31/nycha-hud-ben-carson-bill-de-blasio/|title=NYC, Feds Reach Agreement To Overhaul Struggling NYCHA|first=David Baker|last=says|date=January 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Budget====\nIn 2019, ''City Journal'' reported that during the de Blasio administration, \"New York City\u2019s budget has expanded by some $20 billion, and is expected to total about $93 billion for the coming fiscal year. Expenditures have ballooned three times as fast as the rate of inflation\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.city-journal.org/de-blasio-expanding-city-spending |title=De Blasio has enjoyed a spending spree, expanded NYC's budget every year |publisher=City Journal |date=2019-04-24 |accessdate=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\n====Charter schools====\nDe Blasio's decision to deny the use of public space to several New York City [[charter school]]s provoked controversy among advocates of [[school vouchers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/30/nyregion/carranza-charter-schools-deblasio.html|title=With School Visits, Chancellor Signals a Softer Stance on Charters|newspaper=New York Times|accessdate=15 October 2018}}</ref> The decision overturned a Bloomberg administration arrangement that allowed for \"co-locations\", where charter schools were housed in public school buildings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/03/04/why-is-progressive-hero-bill-de-blasio-throwing-charter-schools-out-of-new-york-city.html|title=Why Is Progressive Hero Bill de Blasio Throwing Charter Schools Out of New York City?|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|author=Conor P. Williams|date=March 3, 2014|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref> De Blasio also revoked $200 million of capital funding earmarked for charter schools.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/education/gov-cuomo-airs-support-charter-schools-article-1.1710958 | title=Gov. Cuomo Boosts Charter Schools, Going Over Mayor de Blasio's Head \u2014 Again | work=[[Daily News (New York)|The New York Daily News]] | date=March 4, 2014 | accessdate=March 30, 2014 | author1=Kenneth Lovett |author2=Glenn Blain}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' emphasized that de Blasio approved 14 charter school co-locations and denied just three, suggesting that he was being unfairly cast as opposed to charter schools.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nytimes.com/2014/03/09/nyregion/de-blasio-and-cuomos-tangled-narratives.html |author=Ginia Bellafante |title=How de Blasio's Narrative Got Hijacked |work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 6, 2014 |accessdate=March 27, 2014}}</ref> Approximately two months after the initial decision, the mayor's office announced that it had found space for the three schools. The city would lease three buildings, which were previously used for Catholic schools, from the [[Archdiocese of New York]], and renovate and maintain them. The three charter schools are run by [[Success Academy Charter Schools]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/27/nyregion/new-york-finds-space-for-3-charter-schools.html?smid=fb-share&_r=0 | title=New York Finds Space for 3 Charter Schools | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=April 26, 2014 | accessdate=April 28, 2014 | author=Daniel E. Slotnik}}</ref>\n\n====Environmental issues====\nDe Blasio supports the [[Green New Deal]]. In April 2019 he announced his support for legislation to ban the construction of glass and steel skyscrapers in New York City, citing environmental concerns and contribution to global warming.<ref>\"[https://www.crainsnewyork.com/politics/de-blasio-insists-his-ban-glass-and-steel-buildings-real De Blasio insists his ban on glass-and-steel buildings is real]\". ''[[Crain's New York]]''. April 29, 2016.</ref> De Blasio also criticized the development at [[Hudson Yards (development)|Hudson Yards]] in Manhattan as an example of \"the wrong way to do things\".<ref>\"[https://ny.curbed.com/2019/4/24/18514203/nyc-bill-de-blasio-glass-skyscraper-ban De Blasio\u2019s \u2018glass skyscraper ban,\u2019 explained]. ''[[Curbed]]''. April 24, 2019.</ref>\n\n====Israel====\n[[File:De Blasio at Celebrate Israel Parade (8927511453).jpg|thumb|De Blasio at the [[Celebrate Israel Parade]] in June 2013]]\nOn February 14, 2019, while addressing a rally in New York City about combatting [[antisemitism]], De Blasio said: \"Maybe some people don\u2019t realize it, but when they support the [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions|BDS]] movement, they are affronting the right of Israel to exist and that is unacceptable.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=New York Mayor Condemns BDS, Calls to Stamp Out anti-Semitism |url=https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/.premium-new-york-mayor-condemns-bds-calls-to-stamp-out-anti-semitism-1.6938298 |work=Haaretz |date=February 15, 2019}}</ref> De Blasio condemned [[Ilhan Omar]]'s remarks about Israel and [[Israel lobby in the United States|pro-Israel lobbyists]] as \"absolutely unacceptable\" and \"illogical\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Ilhan Omar: US House votes amid anti-Semitism row |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-47488272 |publisher=BBC |date=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Marijuana legalization====\nIn December 2018, De Blasio announced his support for marijuana legalization in New York City, calling it a \"once-in-a-generation opportunity to get a historic issue right for future New Yorkers.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2018/12/20/de-blasio-endorses-legalizing-marijuana-in-nyc/ |title=De Blasio: Legalizing Marijuana In NYC Is 'Once-In-A-Generation Opportunity' |date=2018-12-20 |language=en |access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref> He worked with a marijuana task force to produce a report on licensing and regulation, which was released along with a letter of endorsement.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/which-states-legalization-marijuana-2019=-1275736 |title=Experts predict 2019 will be a \"real game-changer\" for marijuana legalization. Here's where it could be legal next |last=Hutzler |first=Alexandra |date=2019-01-01 |website=Newsweek |language=en |access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref>\n\n====Mohel disclosure rule====\nIn 2015, de Blasio repealed a requirement that [[mohel]]s inform parents of the risks of [[Brit milah#Metzitzah B'Peh|metzitzah b'peh]], an oral circumcision ritual that was linked to 17 cases of infant herpes, brain damage, and two deaths since 2000.<ref>{{cite news|title=NYC, Orthodox Jews in Talks Over Ritual After Herpes Cases|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2015/02/21/nyc-orthodox-jews-in-talks-over-ritual-after-herpes-cases/23798751/|author=Associated Press|accessdate=23 August 2016|work=USA Today|agency=Associated Press|date=February 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/13/nyregion/regulation-of-circumcision-method-divides-some-jews-in-new-york.html|title=Denouncing City's Move to Regulate Circumcision|date=September 13, 2012|work=The New York Times|last1=Otterman|first1=Sharon|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref> The rule was passed by the city's Board of Health in 2012, required parents to sign a consent form, and had been called an infringement on religious freedom by ultra-Orthodox Jewish leaders, who sued the city in federal court<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/25/nyregion/de-blasio-set-to-waive-rule-requiring-consent-form-for-circumcision-ritual.html|title=Mayor de Blasio Is Set to Ease Rules on Circumcision Ritual|date=February 25, 2015|work=The New York Times|last1=Grynbaum|first1=Michael M.|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref> and pressed their followers not to comply.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/15/nyregion/mayor-de-blasio-and-rabbis-near-accord-on-new-circumcision-rule.html|title=Mayor de Blasio and Rabbis Near Accord on New Circumcision Rule|date=January 15, 2015|work=The New York Times|last1=Otterman|first1=Sharon|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref> After de Blasio installed allies and donors on New York City's Board of Health,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/10/nyregion/de-blasio-puts-allies-on-panel-hearing-circumcision-plan.html|title=De Blasio Puts Allies on Panel Hearing Circumcision Plan|date=June 10, 2015|work=The New York Times|last1=Grynbaum|first1=Michael M.|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref> a new policy stated that mohels could be banned for life if they tested positive for herpes and the DNA strain matched the infant's, but only after a child has been infected, and not when a mohel tests positive but his DNA strain does not match the infant's.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/de-blasio-administration-scraps-circumcision-ritual-rules-article-1.2128239|title=De Blasio administration scraps consent rules for Jewish circumcision ritual|website=NY Daily News|first=Reuven|last=Blau|date=February 24, 2015}}</ref> It was revealed that the city did not disclose new infections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forward.com/news/321465/new-circumcision-rules-metzitzah-dont-ask-dont-tell/|title=New Controversial Circumcision Rite Rules: Don't Ask, Don't Tell|author=Paul Berger|date=September 25, 2015|work=The Forward|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref> Since the change was made, several children have been infected with the disease after undergoing the ritual.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/manhattan/nyc-barred-men-practicing-jewish-circumcision-article-1.3013127|title=NYC bars two men from practicing Jewish circumcision after infants contract herpes|website=NY Daily News|first=Jillian Jorgensen, Erin|last=Durkin|date=March 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====NYPD relations====\n{{Expand section|date=May 2019}}\n[[File:NYC Mike Brown-Ferguson protest Pace University.JPG|thumb|right|New Yorkers demonstrating against police brutality at [[Pace University]] in November 2014|279x279px]]\nDuring his mayoral tenure, de Blasio's relationship with the New York City Police Department has been described as \"strained\",<ref name=\"time.com\">{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3644168/new-york-police-de-blasio-wenjian-liu-rafael-ramos/|title=Why New York Cops Hate Mayor de Blasio|website=Time}}</ref> \"combative\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/05/nyregion/bill-deblasio-police-crime.html|title=De Blasio Kept Crime Down in First Term. His Next Goal: Nicer Police.|first1=J. David|last1=Goodman|first2=Al|last2=Baker|date=November 5, 2017|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2017/07/07/new-york-city-mayor-de-blasio-slammed-for-trump-protesting-germany-trip-as-city-mourns-officers-death/|title=New York mayor on Germany trip: The world should know that Americans don't align with Trump|website=Washington Post}}</ref> and \"frosty\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/07/11/bill-de-blasio-g-20-backlash-240412|title=De Blasio faces Germany trip backlash|first1=Gloria|last1=Pazmino|first2=Laura|last2=Nahmias|website=POLITICO}}</ref>\n\nOpposition to [[Stop-and-frisk in New York City|the NYPD's \"stop and frisk\" policy]] was a centerpiece of De Blasio's campaign.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://nation.time.com/2014/01/30/stop-and-frisk-bill-de-blasio-michael-bloomberg-appeal-crime |title=New NYC Mayor Drops Stop-and-Frisk Appeal |work=[[Time Magazine]] |date= January 30, 2014 |author=Eliana Dockterman}}</ref> The practice had been challenged by civil rights groups in federal court, where it was [[Floyd v. City of New York|ruled unconstitutional in 2013]]. The federal appeal of this decision filed by the Bloomberg administration was dropped by de Blasio upon taking office. He vowed to settle cases with claimants who had ongoing litigation against the police for stop and frisk arrests. The NYPD union appealed the decision without de Blasio's support, and was rejected.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/01/nyregion/police-unions-cant-intervene-in-stop-and-frisk-cases-appeals-panel-rules.html |title=Unions' Bid for Role in Stop-and-Frisk Suits Is Rejected by Court |author=Benjamin Weiser|work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 31, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDe Blasio selected [[Bill Bratton]] for [[New York City Police Commissioner]], a position he had held under Mayor [[Rudy Giuliani]]. Bratton, who introduced [[Frisking|stop and frisk]] under Giuliani, promised it would be used \"legally, respectfully\" and less frequently.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/bratton-miller-on-stop-and-frisk-and-job-qualifications/ | title=NYPD's Bratton, Miller on stop-and-frisk and job qualifications | work=[[CBS News]] | date=January 9, 2014 | author=Shoshana Davis}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/12/27/new-yorkers-against-bratton_n_4509200.html | title=New Group Launches Fight Against de Blasio's Top Cop | work=[[The Huffington Post]] | date=December 27, 2013 | author=Saki Knafo}}</ref> Some de Blasio supporters were disappointed with Bratton's appointment.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.latinpost.com/articles/4807/20131215/mayor-elect-bill-de-blasio-selects-stop-frisk-innovator-william.htm | title=Bill de Blasio Mayor: NYC Mayor-elect Selects Stop-and-Frisk Innovator William Bratton as Police Commissioner; Latino Candidates Snubbed? | work=Latin Post | date=December 15, 2013 | author=Nicole Akoukou Thompson}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2014, de Blasio came under criticism for calling the police shortly after one of his supporters was detained by police. Pastor Bishop Orlando Findlayter\u2014the founder of the New Hope Christian Fellowship Church, and a friend of de Blasio\u2014was pulled over for failing to signal on a left turn. Findlayter was then detained by police on outstanding warrants and driving with a suspended license.<ref name=Bishop1>{{cite news|url=https://nytimes.com/2014/02/12/nyregion/mayors-call-did-not-prompt-pastors-release-police-say.html |title=Mayor's Call Did Not Prompt Pastor's Release Police Say |work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Joseph Goldstein|date=February 12, 2014 |accessdate=March 30, 2014}}</ref> De Blasio is alleged to have called the police on Findlayter's behalf. Findlayter was released shortly thereafter. In a press conference, de Blasio told reporters that while he had called the police to make an inquiry regarding Findlayter's arrest he did not ask the police to release him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/de-blasio-not-bishop-released-article-1.1613284|title=De Blasio: I Did Not Ask for Bishop to be Released|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=February 13, 2014|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref> A spokesperson for the mayor said that de Blasio's call occurred after the police already had decided to release Findlayter.<ref name=Bishop1/> While both the police and City Hall denied that De Blasio asked for preferential treatment, City Comptroller [[Scott M. Stringer]] said De Blasio's behavior was problematic because \"the mayor shouldn't be involved in any way about somebody's arrest.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nytimes.com/2014/02/13/nyregion/mayors-judgment-debated-after-his-call-to-police-about-a-supporters-arrest.html |title=Mayor judgement debated after his call to police about a supporters arrest |work='The New York Times  |author=Michael M. Grynbaum |date=February 13, 2014 |accessdate=March 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn December 3, 2014, following a [[Grand juries in the United States|grand jury]] decision not to indict NYPD officer Daniel Pantaleo in the [[death of Eric Garner]], de Blasio said in a speech that he and his [[African American]] wife, [[Chirlane McCray]], had had many conversations<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2014/dec/21/mayor-bill-de-blasio-police-two-nypd-officers-shot-dead|title=De Blasio at Centre of Police Storm After Two NYPD Officers Shot Dead|author=Amanda Holpuch|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=December 21, 2014|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref> with their biracial son about taking \"special care in any encounters he has with the police officers who are there to protect him.\"<ref name=Garner>{{cite news|author=Erin Durkin|title=De Blasio Talks of Worries for Son Dante After Grand Jury Declines to Indict Cop in Eric Garner Death|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/nyc-crime/de-blasio-talks-biracial-son-eric-garner-grand-jury-article-1.2032253|newspaper=[[New York Daily News]]|date=December 3, 2014|accessdate=December 15, 2014}}</ref> De Blasio also \"offered qualified support for protesters after the grand jury decision not to charge the officer involved in the chokehold death of Eric Garner in New York City\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-police-idUSKBN0KD06A20150104|title=Hundreds of police turn backs on NYC mayor at slain officer's funeral|last=Malo|first=Sebastien|date=2015-01-04|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-01-02|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfter New York City police officers Wenjian Liu and Rafael Ramos were killed in an ambush in December 2014, \"cops and union leaders publicly rebuked [de Blasio], arguing [that] his earlier remarks had stoked anti-police sentiment.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3644168/new-york-police-de-blasio-wenjian-liu-rafael-ramos/|title=Why New York Cops Hate Mayor de Blasio|last=Altman|first=Alex|date=December 22, 2014|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-01-02}}</ref> When de Blasio eulogized the two fallen officers, hundreds of their fellow police officers turned their backs on him.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFollowing the murder of New York City police officer Miosotis Familia in July 2017, de Blasio received further criticism for not attending Familia's vigil. Many officers again turned their backs on him when he spoke at a service for Familia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L_S3KauQWqk|title=NYPD officers turn their backs on Mayor de Blasio at slain officer's funeral|first=Fox|last=News|publisher=YouTube|date=12 July 2017|accessdate=14 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2017/07/11/de-blasio-greeted-by-turned-backs-at-familia-funeral-113318|title=Protesters turn their backs on de Blasio at officer's funeral|first=Gloria|last=Pazmino|website=Politico PRO}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, de Blasio criticized former mayor Michael Bloomberg's apology for the [[stop and frisk]] policy, tweeting, \"This is LONG overdue and the timing is transparent and cynical. With all due respect to my predecessor, we\u2019ve spent six years undoing the damage he created with this bankrupt policy. We ended stop and frisk AND drove down crime. Actions speak louder than words.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Mayor Bill de BlasioVerified account |url=https://twitter.com/NYCMayor/status/1196130583409283072 |title=Mayor Bill de Blasio on Twitter: \"This is LONG overdue and the timing is transparent and cynical. With all due respect to my predecessor, we\u00e2\u20ac\u2122ve spent six years undoing the damage he created with this bankrupt policy. We ended stop and frisk AND drove down crime. Actions speak louder than words.\u00e2\u20ac\u015a https://t.co/86mLlyJefs\" |publisher=Twitter.com |date= |accessdate=2020-01-22}}</ref> Police Benevolent Association President [[Patrick Lynch (police officer)|Patrick Lynch]] joined the Mayor in criticizing Bloomberg's apology as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pix11.com/2019/11/17/too-little-too-late-pat-lynch-police-union-president-slams-bloomberg-stop-and-frisk-apology|title='Too little, too late': Police union president slams Bloomberg 'stop and frisk' apology|date=November 17, 2019|website=WPIX}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/11/17/police-union-de-blasio-blast-bloomberg-over-stop-and-frisk-apology/|title=Police union, de Blasio blast Bloomberg over stop-and-frisk apology|first1=Carl|last1=Campanile|first2=Craig|last2=McCarthy|first3=Aaron|last3=Feis|date=November 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Technology and innovation====\nWhen de Blasio appointed [[Minerva Tantoco]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20140916/TECHNOLOGY/140919903/new-tech-czar-makes-big-app-decision|title=New tech czar makes big app decision|date=September 16, 2014|website=Crain's New York Business}}</ref> as the city's chief technology officer in fall 2014, he said her goal would be to \"develop and implement a coordinated strategy for technology and innovation, for how this city as a whole is going to approach the role of technology in our everyday lives, in our economy, in our schools, in our civic participation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://subscriber.politicopro.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2016/03/city-tech-approach-gets-mixed-grades-two-years-in-099483|title=City tech approach gets mixed grades two years in|last=Miranda Neubauer|website=Politico PRO|language=en|access-date=2019-03-29}}</ref>\n\nAlong with Governor Cuomo, de Blasio supported moving [[Amazon (company)|Amazon's]] [[headquarters]] to [[Long Island City]] in the [[Amazon HQ2]] search, and worked with Cuomo to develop a benefits package from New York City and State funds totaling $2.988 billion.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |last1=Raskin |first1=Sam |title=Amazon's HQ2 deal with New York, explained |url=https://ny.curbed.com/2018/11/16/18098589/amazon-hq2-nyc-queens-long-island-city-explained |website=Curbed New York |accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref> In November 2018, Long Island City was selected as one of two sites for HQ2, along with [[Crystal City, Arlington, Virginia|Crystal City]] in Virginia, directly outside of [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, D.C]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> Long Island City's selection as a site for Amazon's HQ2 was controversial before and after it happened, and was protested by local residents, community organizations, and politicians. After receiving pushback, Amazon withdrew its plans to open HQ2 in Long Island City on February 14, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hanbury |first1=Mary |title=Mayor Bill de Blasio slams Amazon for scrapping its HQ2 project in New York City |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/mayor-bill-de-blasio-criticizes-amazon-cancel-hq2-2019-2 |website=Business Insider |accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref> De Blasio later criticized Amazon's decision.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/14/nyregion/amazon-hq2-queens.html |title=Amazon Pulls Out of Planned New York City Headquarters |date=February 14, 2019 |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190215000024/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/14/nyregion/amazon-hq2-queens.html |archive-date=February 15, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Transportation====\nIn 2014, de Blasio released a report dedicated to \"better transit for New York City.\" Some of the ideas brought up in the report were to rebuild [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Penn Station]]/[[Madison Square Garden]], create more [[bus rapid transit]] routes,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dnwssx4l7gl7s.cloudfront.net/deblasio/default/page/-/One%20New%20York%2C%20Rising%20Together%20-%20Transit.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150524211041/http://dnwssx4l7gl7s.cloudfront.net/deblasio/default/page/-/One%20New%20York%2C%20Rising%20Together%20-%20Transit.pdf|url-status=dead|title=Better Transit for New York City|archivedate=May 24, 2015}}</ref> and a \"Vision Zero\" initiative to reduce traffic-related deaths in the city.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/19/nyregion/de-blasio-unveils-plans-to-eliminate-traffic-deaths.html|title=De Blasio Outlines Steps to Eliminate Traffic Deaths|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Matt Flegenheimer|date=February 18, 2014|accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe \"Vision Zero\" initiative, inspired by a successful Swedish plan, saw a gradual decrease in pedestrian fatalities, from 299 in 2013 to 200 in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/01/nyregion/traffic-deaths-decrease-nyc.html|title=Traffic Deaths in New York City Drop to 200, a Record Low|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Emma G. Fitzsimmons|date=Jan 1, 2019|accessdate=September 5, 2019}}</ref> However, in 2019 there has been an increase in cyclist deaths, and de Blasio has discussed several proposals to combat cyclist deaths, including a $58.4 million plan<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/25/nyregion/nyc-bike-safety-deaths.html|title=After 17 Cyclists Die, New York City Makes $58.4 Million Plan|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Winnie Hu|date=July 25, 2019|accessdate=September 5, 2019}}</ref> and requiring cyclists to wear helmets and acquire licenses to operate a bicycle.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gothamist.com/news/de-blasio-mulls-mandatory-helmets-citi-bike-riders-licenses-all-cyclists|title=De Blasio Mulls Mandatory Helmets For Citi Bike Riders, Licenses For All Cyclists|newspaper=[[Gothamist]]|author=Christopher Robbins|date=September 4, 2019|accessdate=September 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905152047/https://gothamist.com/news/de-blasio-mulls-mandatory-helmets-citi-bike-riders-licenses-all-cyclists|archive-date=September 5, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWhile the de Blasio administration planned on increasing the rate at which bicycle racks were added in the city, the annual rate has instead fallen by 42 percent compared to the Bloomberg administration, reaching a new average of 1,633 new racks per year.{{When|date=October 2019}} Jon Orcutt, a spokesman for Bike New York, said \"Everybody's talking about [[Citi Bike]]s and scooters but it's the humble bike rack that needs more attention.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amny.com/transit/bike-racks-nyc-1.27886025|title=Competition is fierce as bike rack installations slow|website=am New York}}</ref>\n\n====Universal pre-kindergarten====\nAs mayor, de Blasio's signature initiative was the implementation of [[Universal preschool|Universal Pre-K]], the availability of publicly funded pre-kindergarten for all New York City residents.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/01/nyregion/deblasio-pre-k-program-nyc.html|title=Bright Spot for N.Y.'s Struggling Schools: Pre-K|last=Shapiro|first=Eliza|date=2019-01-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-05-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2014/02/de-blasio-presses-forward-with-pre-k-plan.html|title=Mayor de Blasio Presses Forward With Pre-K Plan -- NYMag|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York Magazine]]|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref> He sought to fund the program by increasing taxes on New York City residents earning $500,000 or more.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2014/01/08/pf/taxes/new-york-tax-de-blasio/|title=De Blasio's plan to tax the rich|author=Jeanne Sahadi|date=January 8, 2014|work=[[CNNMoney]]|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref> De Blasio's initiative has seen an increase in Universal Pre-K enrollment in New York City through 2015, with over 70% of pre-K expansions happening within the ZIP codes of the city's poorest quartile.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Shapiro|first1=Eliza|last2=Cheney|first2=Brendan|title=City Enrolls 68K in Pre-K, With Big Growth in Poorest Neighborhoods|url=http://www.capitalnewyork.com/article/city-hall/2015/12/8585999/city-enrolls-68k-pre-k-big-growth-poorest-neighborhoods|website=Politico}}</ref> In 2017 de Blasio proposed an expansion of the program to \"3-K\", to include three-year-olds. Preschool for three-year-olds would start in poorer neighborhoods, with the goal of covering the entire city, if the state or federal governments provided funding.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://shakingnews.com/blog/2017/04/24/de-blasio-announces-3-k-preschool-three-year-olds/|title=Mayor de Blasio Announces 3\u2013K Preschool for Three-Year Olds \u2013 ShakingNews|date=2017-04-24|work=ShakingNews|access-date=2017-05-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==2020 presidential campaign==\n{{short description|Mayor of New York City}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox U.S. federal election campaign\n|committee = de Blasio 2020\n|campaign = [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 presidential election]] ([[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|Democratic Party primaries]])\n|candidate = '''Bill de Blasio'''<br/>[[Mayor of New York City]] (2014\u2013present)\n|logo=Bill de Blasio 2020 presidential campaign logo.svg\n|status=Launched: May 16, 2019<br /> Suspended: September 20, 2019\n|cand_id =\n|fec_date =9/30/2019\n|affiliation = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]\n|headquarters = [[New York City|New York City, New York]]\n|key_people =\n|receipts =1417609.97<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docquery.fec.gov/cgi-bin/forms/C00706697/1358932/|title=Form 3P for de Blasio 2020|website=Federal Electoral Commission|date=October 15, 2019}}</ref> \n|slogan = Working People First<ref name=\"announcement\"/>\n|chant  =\n|homepage = {{URL|https://billdeblasio.com/}}\n}}\n\nOn May 16, 2019, de Blasio announced that he would seek the Democratic nomination for president after releasing a [[YouTube]] video in which he said, \"I\u2019m Bill de Blasio, and I\u2019m running for president because it\u2019s time we put working people first.\"<ref name=\"announcement\">{{cite news|author1=Julia Marsh|author2=Nolan Hicks|author3=Rich Calder|title=Bill de Blasio officially launches 2020 presidential campaign|url=https://nypost.com/2019/05/16/bill-de-blasio-officially-launches-2020-presidential-campaign/|accessdate=May 16, 2019|work=New York Post|date=May 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190516231227/https://nypost.com/2019/05/16/bill-de-blasio-officially-launches-2020-presidential-campaign/|archive-date=May 16, 2019}}</ref> He was the first incumbent mayor of New York City to run for president since [[John Lindsay]], who ran for the Democratic nomination in [[1972 Democratic Party presidential primaries|1972]].<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/politics/2019/03/28/as-bill-de-blasio-contemplates-2020-presidential-run-there-are-possible-warning-signs-from-john-lindsay-1972-campaign|title = As De Blasio Contemplates a Presidential Run, There are Possible Warning Signs from 1972|last = Cuza|first = Bobby|work = [[NY1]]|date = March 27, 2019|accessdate = July 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring his campaign, de Blasio expressed support for increasing the federal [[minimum wage]] to $15 an hour.<ref name=\"announcement\"/> On June 19, 2019, he said, \"We have to make sure there is a peace settlement in Afghanistan; it obviously has to involve the [[Taliban]]. Until that point, I don\u2019t think it\u2019s sensible to take out our troops.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=The Democratic candidates on foreign policy |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020-election/ |work=[[Foreign Policy]]}}</ref> De Blasio advocated a [[robot tax]] and proposed to make large corporations responsible for five years of income tax from jobs that are automated away.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/460162-de-blasio-proposes-robot-tax-to-counter-automation-job-losses|title=De Blasio proposes 'robot tax' to counter job losses from automation|first=Rachel|last=Frazin|publisher=The Hill|date=2019-09-05|accessdate=2019-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/9/9/20857510/bill-de-blasio-nyc-mayor-democratic-candidate-robot-tax-fawpa-proposal|title=New York City mayor and 2020 candidate Bill de Blasio wants a robot tax|first=Adi|last=Robertson|publisher=The Verge|date=2019-09-09|accessdate=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\nDespite his large margins of victory during his mayoral races, polls found de Blasio to be largely unpopular. ''[[The New York Times]]'' described his candidacy as a \"long shot\"'','' citing his low national poll numbers and inconsistent approval ratings in New York City''.''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/01/nyregion/dante-de-blasio-son-2020.html|title=Why 'Raising a Black Son' Is a de Blasio Campaign Theme|last=Mays|first=Jeffery C.|date=2019-07-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/10/nyregion/de-blasio-poll-donald-trump.html|title=Trump's Competition for Most Unpopular Politician in New York: de Blasio|last=Neuman|first=William|date=2019-06-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> A May 2019 [[Quinnipiac University Polling Institute|Quinnipiac University poll]] of New York City voters found that 76% did not want de Blasio to run for president. An April 2019 poll placed his approval rating at 42% in the city, with 44% of voters disapproving.<ref>{{cite news |title=New York City Mayor, First Lady Get Lukewarm Grades, Quinnipiac University Poll Finds; Voters Say 4-1 De Blasio Should Not Run For President |url=https://poll.qu.edu/new-york-city/release-detail?ReleaseID=2613 |accessdate=September 20, 2019 |publisher=Quinnipiac University |date=April 3, 2019}}</ref> Just before he suspended his campaign, his approval rating had dropped to 33%, with 58% disapproving.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Enten |first1=Harry |title=Voters don't like no shot campaigns. Just ask Bill de Blasio |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/17/politics/de-blasio-approval-rating/index.html |accessdate=September 20, 2019 |publisher=CNN |date=September 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDe Blasio attempted to position himself as a progressive in contrast to the at-the-time front-runner, former [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Joe Biden]]. He was hoping to challenge U.S. Senators [[Bernie Sanders]] of [[Vermont]] and [[Elizabeth Warren]] of [[Massachusetts]], both of whom were seen as leaders of the progressive wing of the Democratic party.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cole |first1=Devan |last2=Merica |first2=Dan |title=De Blasio drops out of 2020 presidential race |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/20/politics/bill-de-blasio-ends-presidential-campaign/index.html |accessdate= September 20, 2019 |publisher=CNN |date=September 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDe Blasio's campaign failed to gain traction. He was unable to qualify for [[2020 Democratic Party presidential debates and forums|Democratic primary debates]] in September and October, which were seen as necessary events for his campaign to maintain viability. He regularly polled at 0% among Democratic primary voters, including in his home state.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bill de Blasio: New York mayor pulls out of US presidential race |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-49766266|last1=Zurcher|first1=Anthony|accessdate=September 20, 2019 |publisher=BBC News |date=September 20, 2019}}</ref> After failing to qualify for the third round of primary debates,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/04/nyregion/de-blasio-2020-president.html|title=Bill de Blasio May End 2020 Presidential Bid Next Month|last=Mays|first=Jeffery C.|date=2019-09-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-09-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> de Blasio announced the suspension of his campaign on September 20, 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cole |first1=Devan |last2=Merica |first2=Dan |title=De Blasio drops out of 2020 presidential race |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/20/politics/bill-de-blasio-ends-presidential-campaign/index.html |accessdate=September 20, 2019 |publisher=CNN |date=September 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/may/16/bill-de-blasio-2020-presidential-campaign|title=Bill de Blasio announces 2020 presidential bid|work=The Guardian|last1=Durkin|first1=Erin|date=May 16, 2019|access-date=2019-05-16|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/09/20/bill-de-blasio-ends-2020-presidential-campaign-1506011|title=Bill de Blasio ends 2020 presidential campaign|website=[[Politico]]|author=Sally Goldenburg, Quint Forgey|date=September 20, 2019|accessdate=September 20, 2019}}</ref> On February 14, 2020, de Blasio endorsed Sanders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/02/14/de-blasio-to-endorse-sanders-115138|title=De Blasio to endorse Bernie Sanders|website=Politico|last1=Goldenburg|first1=Sally|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n\n===Endorsements===\n{{main|Endorsements in the 2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries#Bill de Blasio}}\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{main|Electoral history of Bill de Blasio}}\n\n==Personal life==\nDe Blasio and his wife, activist and poet [[Chirlane McCray]], met while both were working for Mayor Dinkins' administration and married in 1994.<ref name=wsj130101/> The couple honeymooned in Cuba in violation of a U.S. travel ban.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2013/09/24/lhota-de-blasio-needs-to-explain-himself-over-cuba-honeymoon-sandinista-support/|title=Lhota: De Blasio 'Needs To Explain Himself' Over Cuba Honeymoon, Sandinista Support|date=September 24, 2013|publisher=}}</ref> They lived in [[Park Slope|Park Slope, Brooklyn]], before moving into [[Gracie Mansion]],<ref name=mansion>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/de-blasio-finally-settles-down-at-gracie-mansion-1406600111 |title=De Blasio Finally Settles Down at Gracie Mansion |author=Mara Gay  |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=July 28, 2014 |accessdate=January 11, 2015}}</ref> the traditional residence of New York City mayors. They have two children: Dante, a graduate of [[Brooklyn Technical High School]] who graduated from [[Yale University]] in 2019,<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/20/nyregion/de-blasio-prods-graduates-to-challenge-injustice-and-son-to-take-a-joke.html?_r=0 | title=De Blasio Prods Graduates to Challenge Injustice (and Son to Take a Joke) | work=The New York Times | date=June 19, 2015 | accessdate=June 20, 2015 | author=Flegenheimer, Matt}}</ref> and Chiara, a student at [[Santa Clara University]] in California.<ref name=\"announcenyt\" /><ref name=\"wsj130101\">{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323820104578215653710530398 | title=Family in the Spotlight | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | date=January 1, 2013 | author=Michael Howard Saul}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.capitalnewyork.com/article/politics/2013/08/8533045/bill-de-blasio-and-brief-history-public-school-parents-mayor | title=Bill de Blasio and a Brief History of Public-School Parents for Mayor | work=Capital New York | date=August 23, 2013 | accessdate=September 8, 2013 | author=Dana Rubinstein | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130825235646/http://www.capitalnewyork.com/article/politics/2013/08/8533045/bill-de-blasio-and-brief-history-public-school-parents-mayor | archive-date=August 25, 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Chiara addressed her [[substance abuse|drug use]] and [[depression (mood)|depression]] in late December 2013, in a four-minute video the mayor's transition team released.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cnsnews.com/news/article/ny-mayor-elects-daughter-tells-substance-abuse-0 | title=NY Mayor-elect's Daughter Tells Of Substance Abuse | author=Jonathan Lemire | date=December 24, 2013 | accessdate=December 26, 2013 | agency=[[Associated Press]] | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150322194100/http://www.cnsnews.com/news/article/ny-mayor-elects-daughter-tells-substance-abuse-0 | archive-date=March 22, 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAt {{height|ft=6|in=5}}, de Blasio is the tallest mayor in New York City's history.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/02/nyregion/a-mayor-most-everybody-looks-up-to-even-when-he-slouches.html | title=A Mayor Most Everybody Looks Up To, Even When He Slouches | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=February 1, 2014 | accessdate=October 26, 2014 | author= Michael M. Grynbaum}}</ref>\n\nDe Blasio, an [[Italian Americans|Italian American]], regularly conducts interviews, press conferences, and speeches in [[Italian language|Italian]].<ref name=\"25facts\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/25-facts-new-nyc-mayor-de-blasio-article-1.1563171|title=25 Facts About New York City's New Mayor Bill de Blasio|date=January 1, 2014|work=[[New York Daily News]]}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=NYC Mayor's Office|title=Mayor Bill de Blasio Hosts Italian Media Roundtable|date=2014-05-16|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=19DfyGrW7MM|accessdate=2018-01-23}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=askanews|title=Il sindaco di New York Bill de Blasio conquista Capri|date=2014-07-22|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BR23pwU_enA|accessdate=2018-01-23}}</ref>\n\nDespite being mayor of New York, de Blasio is a passionate fan of the [[New York Yankees]]' archrivals, having said he has a \"deep devotion\" to the [[Boston Red Sox]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/cut4/new-yorks-next-mayor-could-be-a-diehard-red-sox-fan-update-he-won/c-57786916|title=New York's next mayor could be a diehard Red Sox fan (UPDATE: he won)|website=MLB.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/redsox/2019/03/02/new-york-city-mayor-bill-blasio-remains-big-red-sox-fan/bysoeBafQjlRUIa5AN3NmN/story.html|title=New York City\u2019s mayor, Bill de Blasio, remains a big Red Sox fan - The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nDe Blasio has described himself as \"[[spiritual but not religious]].\" His mother rejected her Roman Catholic roots and did not attend church in his early life.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bill de Blasio, New York's new 'spiritual but not religious' mayor |url=https://www.ncronline.org/news/parish/bill-de-blasio-new-yorks-new-spiritual-not-religious-mayor |website=National Catholic Reporter |accessdate=8 December 2019 |language=en |date=16 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Grynbaum |first1=Michael M. |title=De Blasio, Inspired by Francis, Describes an Evolving Relationship With Faith |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/23/nyregion/de-blasio-inspired-by-francis-describes-an-evolving-relationship-with-faith.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=8 December 2019 |date=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Net worth===\nAccording to [[Forbes]], De Blasio and his wife had a net worth of $2.5 million as of August 2019.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The Net Worth Of Every 2020 Presidential Candidate |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/danalexander/2019/08/14/heres-the-net-worth-of-every-2020-presidential-candidate/#c6bd69637c58 |accessdate=23 August 2019 |magazine=Forbes |date=14 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of mayors of New York City]]\n* [[List of mayors of the 50 largest cities in the United States]]\n\n== Notes ==\n<references group=\"lower-alpha\" />\n<references group=\"nb\" />\n\n== Citations ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{Cite news |last1=Neuman |first1=William |title=De Blasio Finds Biggest Win in Pre-K, but Also Lasting Consequences |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2017-10-31 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/31/nyregion/de-blasio-universal-pre-k.html |issn=0362-4331 |df=mdy-all }}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Bill de Blasio}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.nyc.gov/mayor nyc.gov/mayor Official mayoral website]\n* [http://www.billdeblasio.com/ Official campaign website]\n* {{C-SPAN|Bill de Blasio}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-civ}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stephen DiBrienza]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[New York City Council]]<br>from the 39th district|years=2002\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Brad Lander]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Betsy Gotbaum]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[New York City Public Advocate|Public Advocate of New York City]]|years=2010\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Letitia James]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael Bloomberg]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mayor of New York City]]|years=2014\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bill Thompson (New York politician)|Bill Thompson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[Mayor of New York City]]|years=[[New York City mayoral election, 2013|2013]], [[New York City mayoral election, 2017|2017]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{United States presidential election, 2020}}\n{{Mayors of New York City}}\n{{New York cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n{{Mayors of the largest cities in the world by GDP}}\n{{Mayors of the 50 largest U.S. cities}}\n{{New York City Public Advocate}}\n{{Democratic NYC mayoral nominees}}\n}}\n{{portal bar|Biography|New York City|Politics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:De Blasio, Bill}}\n[[Category:Bill de Blasio| ]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of French descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Lucanian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of New York City]]\n[[Category:New York City Public Advocates]]\n[[Category:New York City Council members]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:New York University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Park Slope]]\n[[Category:People from Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Cambridge, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:School of International and Public Affairs, Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Truman Scholars]]\n[[Category:United States Department of Housing and Urban Development officials]]\n[[Category:2004 United States presidential electors]]\n[[Category:2012 United States presidential electors]]\n[[Category:2016 United States presidential electors]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2020 United States presidential election]]\n", "name_user": "74.101.50.251", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed error)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bill_de_Blasio"}
{"title_page": "Ontario Veterinary College", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n|name            = Ontario Veterinary College\n| motto = Opus Veterinum Civibus\n| motto_lang = Latin\n| mottoeng = The Craft of the Veterinarian is for the Good of the Nation\n| established = {{start date and age|1862}}\n|type            = [[public university|Public]]\n| parent = University of Guelph\n| dean = Jeffrey Wichtel\n|city            = [[Guelph]], [[Ontario]]\n|country         = [[Canada]]\n| website = http://www.ovc.uoguelph.ca\n|logo            = \n|}}\n\nThe '''Ontario Veterinary College''' (OVC) is the oldest veterinary school in [[Canada]].  It  is located on the campus of the [[University of Guelph]] in [[Guelph]], [[Ontario]]. The OVC is one of five [[veterinary school]]s that offer the [[Doctor of Veterinary Medicine]], DVM program in [[Canada]]. The OVC was ranked 1st in Canada and 4th in the world for veterinary medicine by the QS World University Rankings 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=QS World University Rankings by Subject 2015 - Veterinary Science|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2015/veterinary-science#sorting=rank+region=+country=+faculty=+stars=false+search=|website=QS World University Rankings by Subject|publisher=QS|accessdate=9 May 2015|date = 2015-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nOriginally called ''Upper Canada Veterinary School'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ovc.uoguelph.ca/office-of-the-dean/history |title=History of OVC |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2006 |website=University of Guelph |publisher=University of Guelph |access-date=January 25, 2017}}</ref> the Ontario Veterinary College  was established in [[Toronto]] in 1862, by the [[Scotland|Scots]] Andrew Smith (veterinary surgeon) with some assistance from  [[Duncan McNab McEachran]], both graduates of the [[Royal (Dick) School of Veterinary Studies|Royal School of Veterinary Studies]] at the [[University of Edinburgh]]. The college adopted the current name  in 1867, the year of Canada's Confederation.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://ovc.uoguelph.ca/office-of-the-dean/history |title = History of OVC &#124; Ontario Veterinary College &#124; University of Guelph}}</ref> McEachran was a staff member but he considered the admission standards and academic requirements to be inadequate. He left after three years, moving to Montreal where he helped establish Montreal Veterinary College.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.gc.ca/web/article-en.do?nid=1033889 |title=Duncan McNab McEachran |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=February 15, 2016 |website=News, Government of Canada |publisher=Government of Canada |access-date= |quote= McEachran was asked by a former classmate to join the staff of Canada\u2019s first veterinary college}}</ref>\n\nThe school's first classes took place at 188 King Street West in 1861 and then at Agricultural Hall at Yonge and Queen Streets in 1862.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Barker |first1=CA |title=The Ontario Veterinary College: Temperance Street era |journal=The Canadian Veterinary Journal |date=November 1975 |volume=16 |issue=11 |pages=319\u201328 |pmid=1104138 |pmc=1697073 }}</ref> The first permanent site of the school was at Bay Street and Temperance Street in 1870 and University Avenue in 1914. By 1897, the college was affiliated with the [[University of Toronto]] and in 1908 it was acquired from Smith by the government of Ontario.\n\nIt later moved to [[Guelph]], [[Ontario]] (1922) and remained affiliated with the University of Toronto until it became a founding college of the [[University of Guelph]] in 1964.<ref>http://www.ovc.uoguelph.ca/aboutovc/history.shtml</ref> \nIn 1928 Miss E. B. Carpenter from Detroit was the first woman to graduate from a Canadian veterinary college.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Goodwin|first1=Charlie|title=50 Years a Country Vetrerinarian|date=1983|publisher=Mika Publishing|location=Belleville Ontario|page=21}}</ref> She was accepted to the school in 1923, one year after the [[Sex Disqualification (Removal) Act]] allowed Miss [[Aleen Cust]] to complete her exams at the [[Royal College of Veterinary Surgeons]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Goodwin|first1=Charlie|title=50 Years a Country Vetrerinarian|date=1983|publisher=Mika Publishing|location=Belleville Ontario|page=21}}</ref> The first woman to graduate from OVC was Dr. G. E. Fritz from New York, the first Canadian woman to graduate from OVC or any other Canadian veterinary college was Jean Rumney in 1939 and the second was [[Edith Williams]] in 1941, also a graduate of OVC.<ref>{{cite thesis|last=Perdue|first=Katherine Anne|date=June 2014|title=Writing Desire: The Love Letters of Frieda Fraser and Edith Williams\u2014Correspondence and Lesbian Subjectivity in Early Twentieth Century Canada|type=PhD|publisher=[[York University]]|url=https://yorkspace.library.yorku.ca/xmlui/bitstream/handle/10315/28211/Perdue_Katherine__A_2014_PhD.pdf?sequence=2 |access-date=25 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525175945/https://yorkspace.library.yorku.ca/xmlui/bitstream/handle/10315/28211/Perdue_Katherine__A_2014_PhD.pdf?sequence=2|archivedate=25 May 2017|location=Toronto, Ontario|page=}}</ref>  Today the majority of Canadian veterinary school graduates are women.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/canadian-colleges-of-veterinary-medicine/ | title=Canadian Colleges of Veterinary Medicine &#124; the Canadian Encyclopedia}}</ref>\n\nIn 1964 it became a founding college of the University of Guelph. The college severed ties with University of Toronto and its principal became the dean of the college.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ovc.uoguelph.ca/office-of-the-dean/history |title=History of OVC |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2006 |website=University of Guelph |publisher=University of Guelph |access-date=January 25, 2017}}</ref> The OVC celebrated its 150th anniversary in 2012.\n\n==About==\nThe OVC is the only veterinary college in the province of [[Ontario]], and one of only five current veterinary colleges across Canada.  (The other four are at the [[Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al]], [[University of Prince Edward Island]], the [[University of Saskatchewan]] and the [[University of Calgary]].) The [[University of Calgary]], which opened in 2008, is the youngest of the five, while the OVC is the oldest.<ref>{{cite web|title=About UCVM|url=http://www.vet.ucalgary.ca/about_UCVM|publisher=University of Calgary Veterinary Medicine|accessdate=29 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Changes==\nIn February 2008, OVC was granted $9.5 million from the province of Ontario. The intent was to help the college develop a primary-care teaching hospital for small animals. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.ontario.ca/archive/en/2008/02/12/Ontario-invests-in-new-hospital-at-Ontario-Veterinary-College.html |title=Ontario invests in new hospital at Ontario Veterinary College |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=February 12, 2008  |website=News Ontario |publisher=Province of Ontario |access-date=January 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Hill's Primary Healthcare Centre opened during the summer of 2010  as a veterinary clinic and an educational facility for all veterinary students.  A new state-of-the-art Pathobiology building opened in the fall of 2010.  A new large animal isolation facility serves to treat equine patients at high-risk for infectious disease.\n\nIn March 2016, the provincial government announced a $23 million grant to add a new building and to renovate the animal hospital. The plan was to  add new classrooms and labs, to install new equipment and to improve biosecurity and infection control.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/guelph-vet-college-province-funding-23-million-1.3497878 |title=Ontario Vet College gets $23M for learning space, equipment |author=staff writer |date=March 18, 2016 |website=CBC News |publisher=CBC |access-date=January 25, 2017 |quote=College at University of Guelph transforms to meet the needs of students}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\nThe main OVC building is located on Gordon St. at College St. in Guelph, Ontario.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ovc.uoguelph.ca/visiting-college |title=OVC Visiting the College |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2016 |website=University of Guelph, OVC |publisher=University of Guelph |access-date=January 25, 2017}}</ref> The Dean's Office is at 50 Stone Road, Guelph.\n\n==Academics==\nOVC offers bachelor's degrees in bio-medical science, but its primary degree offering is the DVM ([[Doctor of Veterinary Medicine]]).  The College also offers DVSc, PhD, MSc, MPH, and Diploma programs at the graduate level. The DVM program is one of the most competitive in the world.  The annual number of places available in the [[Doctor of Veterinary Medicine]] (DVM) program is ''120 seats with 105 for Canadians with Ontario residency and 15 for non-Canadians''.\n\n==Student life==\nEach year 120 student veterinarians are admitted to the school, after successfully completing the highly competitive application and interview processes. Student veterinarians at OVC can usually be found studying in the Lifetime Learning Center, having a coffee in the Pathobiology building, or playing hocking at the Gryphon Center. A tradition at OVC is the naming of each class with a mascot and a colour. This mascot represents the class throughout the four phases, and is used regularly in conjunction with not only academics, but also intramural sports. Hockey plays a large part in these intramurals, with rivalries coming to a head in a college wide \"Challenge Cup\" tournament, held each year in March. \n\nPast Classes have included:\n*The 2000 Green Dragons,\n*The 2001 Purple Otters,\n*The 2002 Silver Polar Bears,\n*The 2003 Cougars,\n*The 2004 Falcons,\n*The 2005 Red Foxes,\n*The 2006 Broncos\n*The 2007 Golden Grizzlies\n*The 2008 Blue [[Canadian Eskimo Dog|Qimmiqs]]\n*The 2009 Jade Jaguars\n*The 2010 Crimson Crocodiles <ref>http://www.uoguelph.ca/~crocs10/CrimsonCrocs.html</ref>\n*The 2011 Black Mambas\n*The 2012 Silver Foxes\n*The 2013 Golden Phoenixes\n*The 2014 Emerald Elephants\n*The 2015 Scarlet Stags\n*The 2016 Cobalt Caracals\n*The 2017 Violet Komodos\n*The 2018 Ivory Owls\n*The 2019 Golden Krakens\n\nCurrent Classes are:\n*The 2020 Ruby Rhinos\n*The 2021 Sapphire Snow Leopards\n*The 2022 Jade Jackals\n*The 2023 Opal Otters\n\n==Notable professors==\nDr. W. J. R. Fowler taught equine surgery, materia medica, sporadic diseases, and lameness in horses. Fowler was recognized internationally, and had already taught at Ontario Veterinary College for over 55 years under 5 principles.\n\nDr. F. W. Schofield taught pathology, parasitology and bacteriology. He was also a missionary, travelling around the world preaching Christianity in his off time.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Goodwin|first1=Charlie|title=50 Years A Country Veterinarian|date=1983|publisher=Mika Publishing|location=Belleville, Ontario}}</ref>\n\nDr. Ronald G. Watkin taught bacteriology, milk hygiene, and diseases in poultry. He was an acclaimed research scientist. Ronald retired with Dr. Scofield in 1955.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Drs. Frank W. Schofield And Ronald Gwatkin Retire. |journal=Canadian Journal of Comparative Medicine and Veterinary Science |date=July 1955 |volume=19 |issue=7 |pages=199\u2013200 |pmid=17648826 |pmc=1614101 }}</ref>\n\nPrincipal Charles D. McGilvray was the 3rd principal of the school from 1918 to 1945.  He taught contagious diseases, special therapeutics, and sanitary service subjects.  He obtained the nickname \"Shot-gun Charlie\" from his handling of Glanders Disease in Manitoba between 1905 and 1910.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://alumni.ovc.uoguelph.ca/post/9039632684/charles-d-mcgilvray-ovc-1900-3rd-principal-of-ovc |title = Charles D. McGilvray (OVC 1900), 3rd Principal of OVC (1918-1945)}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[College of Veterinarians of Ontario]]\n*[[University of Guelph]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ovc.uoguelph.ca/ Ontario Veterinary College]\n*[http://www.uoguelph.ca University of Guelph]\n\n{{University of Guelph |state=expanded}}\n{{Veterinary schools in Canada}}\n\n{{wiktionary}}\n\n{{coord|43.53115|N|80.23233|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1862]]\n[[Category:University of Guelph|Veterinary]]\n[[Category:Veterinary schools in Canada]]\n[[Category:1862 establishments in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n|name            = Ontario Veterinary College\n| motto = Opus Veterinum Civibus\n| motto_lang = Latin\n| mottoeng = The Craft of the Veterinarian is for the Good of the Nation\n| established = {{start date and age|1862}}\n|type            = [[public university|Public]]\n| parent = University of Guelph\n| dean = Jeffrey Wichtel\n|city            = [[Guelph]], [[Ontario]]\n|country         = [[Canada]]\n| website = http://www.ovc.uoguelph.ca\n|logo            = \n|}}\n\nThe '''Ontario Veterinary College''' (OVC) is the oldest veterinary school in [[Canada]].  It  is located on the campus of the [[University of Guelph]] in [[Guelph]], [[Ontario]]. The OVC is one of five [[veterinary school]]s that offer the [[Doctor of Veterinary Medicine]], DVM program in [[Canada]]. The OVC was ranked 1st in Canada and 4th in the world for veterinary medicine by the QS World University Rankings 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=QS World University Rankings by Subject 2015 - Veterinary Science|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2015/veterinary-science#sorting=rank+region=+country=+faculty=+stars=false+search=|website=QS World University Rankings by Subject|publisher=QS|accessdate=9 May 2015|date = 2015-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nOriginally called ''Upper Canada Veterinary School'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ovc.uoguelph.ca/office-of-the-dean/history |title=History of OVC |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2006 |website=University of Guelph |publisher=University of Guelph |access-date=January 25, 2017}}</ref> the Ontario Veterinary College  was established in [[Toronto]] in 1862, by the [[Scotland|Scots]] Andrew Smith (veterinary surgeon) with some assistance from  [[Duncan McNab McEachran]], both graduates of the [[Royal (Dick) School of Veterinary Studies|Royal School of Veterinary Studies]] at the [[University of Edinburgh]]. The college adopted the current name  in 1867, the year of Canada's Confederation.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://ovc.uoguelph.ca/office-of-the-dean/history |title = History of OVC &#124; Ontario Veterinary College &#124; University of Guelph}}</ref> McEachran was a staff member but he considered the admission standards and academic requirements to be inadequate. He left after three years, moving to Montreal where he helped establish Montreal Veterinary College.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.gc.ca/web/article-en.do?nid=1033889 |title=Duncan McNab McEachran |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=February 15, 2016 |website=News, Government of Canada |publisher=Government of Canada |access-date= |quote= McEachran was asked by a former classmate to join the staff of Canada\u2019s first veterinary college}}</ref>\n\nThe school's first classes took place at 188 King Street West in 1861 and then at Agricultural Hall at Yonge and Queen Streets in 1862.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Barker |first1=CA |title=The Ontario Veterinary College: Temperance Street era |journal=The Canadian Veterinary Journal |date=November 1975 |volume=16 |issue=11 |pages=319\u201328 |pmid=1104138 |pmc=1697073 }}</ref> The first permanent site of the school was at Bay Street and Temperance Street in 1870 and University Avenue in 1914. By 1897, the college was affiliated with the [[University of Toronto]] and in 1908 it was acquired from Smith by the government of Ontario.\n\nIt later moved to [[Guelph]], [[Ontario]] (1922) and remained affiliated with the University of Toronto until it became a founding college of the [[University of Guelph]] in 1964.<ref>http://www.ovc.uoguelph.ca/aboutovc/history.shtml</ref> \nIn 1928 Miss E. B. Carpenter from Detroit was the first woman to graduate from a Canadian veterinary college.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Goodwin|first1=Charlie|title=50 Years a Country Vetrerinarian|date=1983|publisher=Mika Publishing|location=Belleville Ontario|page=21}}</ref> She was accepted to the school in 1923, one year after the [[Sex Disqualification (Removal) Act]] allowed Miss [[Aleen Cust]] to complete her exams at the [[Royal College of Veterinary Surgeons]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Goodwin|first1=Charlie|title=50 Years a Country Vetrerinarian|date=1983|publisher=Mika Publishing|location=Belleville Ontario|page=21}}</ref> The first woman to graduate from OVC was Dr. G. E. Fritz from New York, the first Canadian woman to graduate from OVC or any other Canadian veterinary college was Jean Rumney in 1939 and the second was [[Edith Williams]] in 1941, also a graduate of OVC.<ref>{{cite thesis|last=Perdue|first=Katherine Anne|date=June 2014|title=Writing Desire: The Love Letters of Frieda Fraser and Edith Williams\u2014Correspondence and Lesbian Subjectivity in Early Twentieth Century Canada|type=PhD|publisher=[[York University]]|url=https://yorkspace.library.yorku.ca/xmlui/bitstream/handle/10315/28211/Perdue_Katherine__A_2014_PhD.pdf?sequence=2 |access-date=25 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525175945/https://yorkspace.library.yorku.ca/xmlui/bitstream/handle/10315/28211/Perdue_Katherine__A_2014_PhD.pdf?sequence=2|archivedate=25 May 2017|location=Toronto, Ontario|page=}}</ref>  Today the majority of Canadian veterinary school graduates are women.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/canadian-colleges-of-veterinary-medicine/ | title=Canadian Colleges of Veterinary Medicine &#124; the Canadian Encyclopedia}}</ref>\n\nIn 1964 it became a founding college of the University of Guelph. The college severed ties with University of Toronto and its principal became the dean of the college.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ovc.uoguelph.ca/office-of-the-dean/history |title=History of OVC |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2006 |website=University of Guelph |publisher=University of Guelph |access-date=January 25, 2017}}</ref> The OVC celebrated its 150th anniversary in 2012.\n\n==About==\nThe OVC is the only veterinary college in the province of [[Ontario]], and one of only five current veterinary colleges across Canada.  (The other four are at the [[Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al]], [[University of Prince Edward Island]], the [[University of Saskatchewan]] and the [[University of Calgary]].) The [[University of Calgary]], which opened in 2008, is the youngest of the five, while the OVC is the oldest.<ref>{{cite web|title=About UCVM|url=http://www.vet.ucalgary.ca/about_UCVM|publisher=University of Calgary Veterinary Medicine|accessdate=29 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Changes==\nIn February 2008, OVC was granted $9.5 million from the province of Ontario. The intent was to help the college develop a primary-care teaching hospital for small animals. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.ontario.ca/archive/en/2008/02/12/Ontario-invests-in-new-hospital-at-Ontario-Veterinary-College.html |title=Ontario invests in new hospital at Ontario Veterinary College |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=February 12, 2008  |website=News Ontario |publisher=Province of Ontario |access-date=January 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Hill's Primary Healthcare Centre opened during the summer of 2010  as a veterinary clinic and an educational facility for all veterinary students.  A new state-of-the-art Pathobiology building opened in the fall of 2010.  A new large animal isolation facility serves to treat equine patients at high-risk for infectious disease.\n\nIn March 2016, the provincial government announced a $23 million grant to add a new building and to renovate the animal hospital. The plan was to  add new classrooms and labs, to install new equipment and to improve biosecurity and infection control.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/guelph-vet-college-province-funding-23-million-1.3497878 |title=Ontario Vet College gets $23M for learning space, equipment |author=staff writer |date=March 18, 2016 |website=CBC News |publisher=CBC |access-date=January 25, 2017 |quote=College at University of Guelph transforms to meet the needs of students}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\nThe main OVC building is located on Gordon St. at College St. in Guelph, Ontario.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ovc.uoguelph.ca/visiting-college |title=OVC Visiting the College |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2016 |website=University of Guelph, OVC |publisher=University of Guelph |access-date=January 25, 2017}}</ref> The Dean's Office is at 50 Stone Road, Guelph.\n\n==Academics==\nOVC offers bachelor's degrees in bio-medical science, but its primary degree offering is the DVM ([[Doctor of Veterinary Medicine]]).  The College also offers DVSc, PhD, MSc, MPH, and Diploma programs at the graduate level. The DVM program is one of the most competitive in the world.  The annual number of places available in the [[Doctor of Veterinary Medicine]] (DVM) program is ''120 seats with 105 for Canadians with Ontario residency and 15 for non-Canadians''.\n\n==Student life==\nA tradition at OVC is the naming of each class with a mascot and a colour. This mascot represents the class throughout the four phases, and is used regularly in conjunction with not only academics, but also intramural sports. Hockey plays a large part in these intramurals, with rivalries coming to a head in a college wide \"Challenge Cup\" tournament, held each year in March.\n\nPast Classes have included:\n*The 2000 Green Dragons,\n*The 2001 Purple Otters,\n*The 2002 Silver Polar Bears,\n*The 2003 Cougars,\n*The 2004 Falcons,\n*The 2005 Red Foxes,\n*The 2006 Broncos\n*The 2007 Golden Grizzlies\n*The 2008 Blue [[Canadian Eskimo Dog|Qimmiqs]]\n*The 2009 Jade Jaguars\n*The 2010 Crimson Crocodiles <ref>http://www.uoguelph.ca/~crocs10/CrimsonCrocs.html</ref>\n*The 2011 Black Mambas\n*The 2012 Silver Foxes\n*The 2013 Golden Phoenixes\n*The 2014 Emerald Elephants\n*The 2015 Scarlet Stags\n*The 2016 Cobalt Caracals\n*The 2017 Violet Komodos\n*The 2018 Ivory Owls\n*The 2019 Golden Krakens\n\nCurrent Classes are:\n*The 2020 Ruby Rhinos\n*The 2021 Sapphire Snow Leopards\n*The 2022 Jade Jackals\n*The 2023 Opal Otters\n\n==Notable professors==\nDr. W. J. R. Fowler taught equine surgery, materia medica, sporadic diseases, and lameness in horses. Fowler was recognized internationally, and had already taught at Ontario Veterinary College for over 55 years under 5 principles.\n\nDr. F. W. Schofield taught pathology, parasitology and bacteriology. He was also a missionary, travelling around the world preaching Christianity in his off time.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Goodwin|first1=Charlie|title=50 Years A Country Veterinarian|date=1983|publisher=Mika Publishing|location=Belleville, Ontario}}</ref>\n\nDr. Ronald G. Watkin taught bacteriology, milk hygiene, and diseases in poultry. He was an acclaimed research scientist. Ronald retired with Dr. Scofield in 1955.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Drs. Frank W. Schofield And Ronald Gwatkin Retire. |journal=Canadian Journal of Comparative Medicine and Veterinary Science |date=July 1955 |volume=19 |issue=7 |pages=199\u2013200 |pmid=17648826 |pmc=1614101 }}</ref>\n\nPrincipal Charles D. McGilvray was the 3rd principal of the school from 1918 to 1945.  He taught contagious diseases, special therapeutics, and sanitary service subjects.  He obtained the nickname \"Shot-gun Charlie\" from his handling of Glanders Disease in Manitoba between 1905 and 1910.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://alumni.ovc.uoguelph.ca/post/9039632684/charles-d-mcgilvray-ovc-1900-3rd-principal-of-ovc |title = Charles D. McGilvray (OVC 1900), 3rd Principal of OVC (1918-1945)}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[College of Veterinarians of Ontario]]\n*[[University of Guelph]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ovc.uoguelph.ca/ Ontario Veterinary College]\n*[http://www.uoguelph.ca University of Guelph]\n\n{{University of Guelph |state=expanded}}\n{{Veterinary schools in Canada}}\n\n{{wiktionary}}\n\n{{coord|43.53115|N|80.23233|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1862]]\n[[Category:University of Guelph|Veterinary]]\n[[Category:Veterinary schools in Canada]]\n[[Category:1862 establishments in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Kteal", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStudent life:added info about student life.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ontario_Veterinary_College"}
{"title_page": "Hispanic National Bar Association", "text_new": "\n\n{{Infobox Organization\n| name = Hispanic National Bar Association\n| type = \n| headquarters = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States of America|United States]]\n| mission = To improve the quality and the administration of justice by advocating for the interests of Hispanic attorneys, judges, law professors, paralegals, legal assistants and law students.<ref name= \"990-2013\">[http://www.guidestar.org/FinDocuments/2014/521/333/2014-521333974-0bdf7813-9O.pdf Form 990: Return of Organization Exempt from Income Taxes]\". ''Hispanic National Bar Association''. [[Guidestar]]. October 31, 2014.</ref>\n| tax_id = \n| employees = \n| employees_year = \n| volunteers = \n| volunteers_year = \n| revenue = \n| revenue_year = \n| expenses = \n| expenses_year = \n| status = [[501(c)(6)]] professional association<ref name= \"990-2013\"/>\n| leader_name = Irene Oria<ref name= board>\"[http://hnba.com/board/ Board of Directors]\". ''Hispanic National Bar Association''. Accessed on June 8, 2016.</ref>\n| leader_title = [[President (corporation)|National President]]\n| leader_name2 = Alba Cruz-Hacker<ref name= board/>\n| leader_title2 = [[Chief Operating Officer]] and [[Executive Director]]\n| founded = {{start date and age|1972|03|20}}<ref name= cacorp/>\n| website = {{URL|http://www.hnba.com/}}\n}}The '''Hispanic National Bar Association''' ('''HNBA''') is a [[501(c)(6)]] organization representing [[Hispanic]]s in the legal profession, including [[Lawyer|attorneys]], [[judge]]s, [[law professor]]s, [[Paralegal|legal assistant and paralegals]], and [[law student]]s in the [[United States]] and its [[Territories of the United States|territories]].\n\n==History==\nThe organization was founded in California on March 20, 1972, as '''La Raza National Lawyers Association''';<ref name= cacorp>\"[http://kepler.sos.ca.gov/ La Raza National Lawyers Association] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315010639/http://kepler.sos.ca.gov/ |date=2015-03-15 }}\". ''Business Entity Detail''. California Secretary of State. Accessed on June 8, 2016.</ref> its first president was Mario G. Obledo.<ref name=history>{{cite web| url=http://www.hnba.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/40-Things1.pdf| title=Click here for 40 Things You Might Not Know About The HNBA!| publisher=Hispanic National Bar Association| accessdate=2012-08-17}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The organization's name was changed to Hispanic National Bar Association and reincorporated in the District of Columbia in 1984.<ref name= corp>\"[https://corp.dcra.dc.gov/BizEntity.aspx/ViewEntityData?entityId=2784306 Hispanic National Bar Association (The)]\". ''[[District of Columbia Department of Consumer and Regulatory Affairs]]''. [[Government of the District of Columbia]]. Accessed on June 8, 2016.</ref>\n\n==Purpose==\nThe association represents the interests of the more than 100,000 Hispanic attorneys, judges, law professors, law students and paralegals in the United States, Puerto Rico, and the U.S. Virgin Islands. National officers are elected by the membership at large, and Regional Presidents are elected by their regional members. \n\nIndividual attorneys may join, and local Hispanic [[bar association]]s may become affiliated with the HNBA. The HNBA collaborates with the local Hispanic bars in over 100 cities in the United States, with other specialty bars, and with the American Bar Association.  This group assists Hispanic Americans in defending their rights and improving their opportunities.<ref name=\"Schultz2000\">{{cite book |last=Schultz |first=Jeffrey D. |title=Encyclopedia of Minorities in American Politics: Hispanic Americans and Native Americans |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sfmPmrL0N3kC&pg=PA467 |date=January 2000 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |isbn=978-1-57356-149-5 |page=467}}</ref>\n\n==Educational Activities==\nThrough our signature events, the HNBA Annual Convention and the Corporate Counsel Conference, we offer cutting-edge continuing legal education (CLE) sessions, which qualify for CLE credits in all U.S. jurisdictions. Our CLE sessions feature practitioners and leading experts from across the country, addressing legal trends on a wide range of topics. As a nationwide approved provider of minimum/mandatory continuing legal education (MCLE), the HNBA offers continuing legal education training to between 1,200 and 1,600 minority legal professionals each year. The HNBA also has a number of educational pipeline initiatives (from high school to law school) that support the training and educational advancement of young Latinx individuals such as: the Uvaldo Herrera National Moot Court Competition, the HNBA Intellectual Property Law Institute (IPLI), Law School Sin L\u00edmites (LSSL), and the Youth Symposium. \n\n==List of past presidents==\nPast presidents of the HNBA are as follows:<ref>[http://hnba.com/about-us/ \"About Us\"], HNBA.  Accessed September 17, 2016.</ref>\n*Mario G. Obledo, 1972-1977\n*Benjamin Aranda III, 1977-1980\n*John Roy Castillo, 1980-1981\n*Robert Maes, 1981-1982\n*Lorenzo Arredondo, 1982-1983\n*[[Mari Carmen Aponte]], 1983-1984\n*Gilbert F. Casellas, 1984-1985\n*Robert Mendez, 1985-1986\n*William Mendez, 1986-1987\n*Michael Martinez, 1987-1988\n*Mark Gallegos, 1988-1989\n*Jimmy Gurule, 1989-1990\n*Robert J. Ruiz, 1990-1991\n*Dolores Atencio, 1991-1992\n*Carlos Ortiz, 1992-1993\n*Wilfredo Caraballo, 1993-1994\n*Mary T. Hernandez, 1994-1995\n*Jose Gaitan, 1995-1996\n*Hugo Chaviano, 1996-1997\n*Gregory Vega, 1997-1998\n*Lillian Apodaca, 1998-1999\n*Alice Velazquez, 1999-2000\n*Rico Rafael Santiago, 2000-2001\n*Angel G. Gomez, 2001-2002\n*Duard D. Bradshaw, 2002-2003\n*Carlos Singh, 2003-2004\n*Alan Varela, 2004-2005\n*Nelson A. Castillo, 2005-2006\n*[[Jimmie V. Reyna]], 2006-2007\n*Victor M. Marquez, 2007-2008\n*Ramona E. Romero, 2008-2009\n*Roman D. Hernandez, 2009-2010\n*Diana Sen, 2010-2011\n*Benny Agosto, Jr., 2011-2012\n*Peter M. Reyes, Jr., 2012-2013\n*Miguel Alexander Pozo, 2013-2014\n*Cynthia D. Mares, 2014-2015\n*Robert T. Maldonado, 2015-2016\n*Pedro Torres-D\u00edaz, 2016-2017\n*Erica V. Mason, 2017-2018\n*Jennifer Salinas, 2018-2019\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.hnba.com/}}\n* [http://www.larazalawyers.net  California La Raza Lawyers]\n* [http://www.mabalawyers.org  Mexican American Bar Association of Los Angeles County]\n* [http://www.prba.net Puerto Rican Bar Association website]\n\n{{State bar associations navbox}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:American bar associations]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1972]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American professional organizations]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:501(c)(6) nonprofit organizations]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Infobox Organization\n| name = Hispanic National Bar Association\n| type = \n| headquarters = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States of America|United States]]\n| mission = To improve the quality and the administration of justice by advocating for the interests of Hispanic attorneys, judges, law professors, paralegals, legal assistants and law students.<ref name= \"990-2013\">[http://www.guidestar.org/FinDocuments/2014/521/333/2014-521333974-0bdf7813-9O.pdf Form 990: Return of Organization Exempt from Income Taxes]\". ''Hispanic National Bar Association''. [[Guidestar]]. October 31, 2014.</ref>\n| tax_id = \n| employees = \n| employees_year = \n| volunteers = \n| volunteers_year = \n| revenue = \n| revenue_year = \n| expenses = \n| expenses_year = \n| status = [[501(c)(6)]] professional association<ref name= \"990-2013\"/>\n| leader_name = Irene Oria<ref name= board>\"[http://hnba.com/board/ Board of Directors]\". ''Hispanic National Bar Association''. Accessed on June 8, 2016.</ref>\n| leader_title = [[President (corporation)|National President]]\n| leader_name2 = Alba Cruz-Hacker<ref name= board/>\n| leader_title2 = [[Chief Operating Officer]] and [[Executive Director]]\n| founded = {{start date and age|1972|03|20}}<ref name= cacorp/>\n| website = {{URL|http://www.hnba.com/}}\n}}The '''Hispanic National Bar Association''' ('''HNBA''') is a [[501(c)(6)]] organization representing [[Hispanic]]s in the legal profession, including [[Lawyer|attorneys]], [[judge]]s, [[law professor]]s, [[Paralegal|legal assistant and paralegals]], and [[law student]]s in the [[United States]] and its [[Territories of the United States|territories]].\n\n==History==\nThe organization was founded in California on March 20, 1972, as '''La Raza National Lawyers Association''';<ref name= cacorp>\"[http://kepler.sos.ca.gov/ La Raza National Lawyers Association] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315010639/http://kepler.sos.ca.gov/ |date=2015-03-15 }}\". ''Business Entity Detail''. California Secretary of State. Accessed on June 8, 2016.</ref> its first president was Mario G. Obledo.<ref name=history>{{cite web| url=http://www.hnba.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/40-Things1.pdf| title=Click here for 40 Things You Might Not Know About The HNBA!| publisher=Hispanic National Bar Association| accessdate=2012-08-17}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The organization's name was changed to Hispanic National Bar Association and reincorporated in the District of Columbia in 1984.<ref name= corp>\"[https://corp.dcra.dc.gov/BizEntity.aspx/ViewEntityData?entityId=2784306 Hispanic National Bar Association (The)]\". ''[[District of Columbia Department of Consumer and Regulatory Affairs]]''. [[Government of the District of Columbia]]. Accessed on June 8, 2016.</ref>\n\n==Purpose==\nThe association represents the interests of the more than 100,000 Hispanic attorneys, judges, law professors, law students and paralegals in the United States, Puerto Rico, and the U.S. Virgin Islands. National officers are elected by the membership at large, and Regional Presidents are elected by their regional members. \n\nIndividual attorneys may join, and local Hispanic [[bar association]]s may become affiliated with the HNBA. The HNBA collaborates with the local Hispanic bars in over 100 cities in the United States, with other specialty bars, and with the American Bar Association.  This group assists Hispanic Americans in defending their rights and improving their opportunities.<ref name=\"Schultz2000\">{{cite book |last=Schultz |first=Jeffrey D. |title=Encyclopedia of Minorities in American Politics: Hispanic Americans and Native Americans |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sfmPmrL0N3kC&pg=PA467 |date=January 2000 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |isbn=978-1-57356-149-5 |page=467}}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\nThe HNBA holds an annual convention, an Annual Mid-Year Conference and Moot Court Competition, an Annual Legislative Day and an Annual International Conference open to all attorneys and affiliates from around the country. Each year, the HNBA also organizes a variety of events for lawyers and law students throughout its 19 regions, and several community outreach and education initiatives.\n\nThe HNBA sometimes condemns rhetoric that it perceives as \"divisive and racist\" and aimed at immigrants. For example, in response to [[Donald Trump]]'s comments regarding illegal immigration from Mexico to the United States, and Trump's derogatory remarks about some of those immigrants, the group's president issued a press release in July 2015 calling for a boycott of all Donald Trump-owned businesses.<ref>{{cite web |last=Olen |first=Helaine |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/moneybox/2016/06/07/every_bogus_claim_in_donald_trump_s_defense_of_trump_university.html# |title=Every bogus claim in Donald Trump's defense of Trump University |date=June 7, 2016 |work=Slate Magazine |accessdate=June 9, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://us4.campaign-archive2.com/?u=df9a27c10b6d6ba38ba001440&id=f8a4a02241&e=cd8fc1ccd9|title=PRESS RELEASE: The Hispanic National Bar Association Rejects Trump's Racist Assertions|website=us4.campaign-archive2.com|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=McConnell|first1=Dugald|last2=Todd|first2=Brian|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/06/08/politics/donald-trump-federal-judge-recusal/index.html|title=Requesting judge's recusal in Trump case could be risky, analysts say|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=June 9, 2016}}</ref><ref name=LAT>Moran, Greg.  [http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-trump-university-20160614-snap-story.html \"Donald Trump fights to keep videos of his Trump University testimony private\"], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' (June 14, 2016).</ref>  Subsequently, in 2016, Trump criticized a member of the HNBA, Judge [[Gonzalo P. Curiel]], and the President of the HNBA issued a statement defending Curiel.<ref>Ortiz, Erik.  [http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2016-election/trump-university-case-who-federal-judge-gonzalo-curiel-n584096 \"Trump University Case: Who Is Federal Judge Gonzalo Curiel?\"], [[NBC News]] (June 2, 2016).</ref>\n\n==List of past presidents==\nPast presidents of the HNBA are as follows:<ref>[http://hnba.com/about-us/ \"About Us\"], HNBA.  Accessed September 17, 2016.</ref>\n*Mario G. Obledo, 1972-1977\n*Benjamin Aranda III, 1977-1980\n*John Roy Castillo, 1980-1981\n*Robert Maes, 1981-1982\n*Lorenzo Arredondo, 1982-1983\n*[[Mari Carmen Aponte]], 1983-1984\n*Gilbert F. Casellas, 1984-1985\n*Robert Mendez, 1985-1986\n*William Mendez, 1986-1987\n*Michael Martinez, 1987-1988\n*Mark Gallegos, 1988-1989\n*Jimmy Gurule, 1989-1990\n*Robert J. Ruiz, 1990-1991\n*Dolores Atencio, 1991-1992\n*Carlos Ortiz, 1992-1993\n*Wilfredo Caraballo, 1993-1994\n*Mary T. Hernandez, 1994-1995\n*Jose Gaitan, 1995-1996\n*Hugo Chaviano, 1996-1997\n*Gregory Vega, 1997-1998\n*Lillian Apodaca, 1998-1999\n*Alice Velazquez, 1999-2000\n*Rico Rafael Santiago, 2000-2001\n*Angel G. Gomez, 2001-2002\n*Duard D. Bradshaw, 2002-2003\n*Carlos Singh, 2003-2004\n*Alan Varela, 2004-2005\n*Nelson A. Castillo, 2005-2006\n*[[Jimmie V. Reyna]], 2006-2007\n*Victor M. Marquez, 2007-2008\n*Ramona E. Romero, 2008-2009\n*Roman D. Hernandez, 2009-2010\n*Diana Sen, 2010-2011\n*Benny Agosto, Jr., 2011-2012\n*Peter M. Reyes, Jr., 2012-2013\n*Miguel Alexander Pozo, 2013-2014\n*Cynthia D. Mares, 2014-2015\n*Robert T. Maldonado, 2015-2016\n*Pedro Torres-D\u00edaz, 2016-2017\n*Erica V. Mason, 2017-2018\n*Jennifer Salinas, 2018-2019\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.hnba.com/}}\n* [http://www.larazalawyers.net  California La Raza Lawyers]\n* [http://www.mabalawyers.org  Mexican American Bar Association of Los Angeles County]\n* [http://www.prba.net Puerto Rican Bar Association website]\n\n{{State bar associations navbox}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:American bar associations]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1972]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American professional organizations]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:501(c)(6) nonprofit organizations]]\n", "name_user": "Erikalopeztello", "label": "safe", "comment": "Previous info was outdated.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hispanic_National_Bar_Association"}
{"title_page": "Economic development in India", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2016}}\n\n{{main|Economy of India}}\n\nThe '''economic development in India''' followed [[socialist]]-inspired politicians for most of its independent history, including state-ownership of many sectors; [[India]]'s per capita income increased at only around [[Hindu rate of growth|1% annualised rate]] in the three decades after its independence.<ref name=\"oecd\"/> Since the mid-1980s, India has slowly opened up its markets through [[Economic reforms in India|economic liberalisation]]. After more fundamental reforms since 1991 and their renewal in the 2000s, India has progressed towards a [[free market economy]].<ref name=\"oecd\"/>\n \nIn the late 2000s, India's growth reached 7.5%, which will double the average income in a decade.<ref name=\"oecd\"/> IMF says that if India pushed more fundamental market reforms, it could sustain the rate and even reach the government's 2011 target of 10%.<ref name=\"oecd\"/> States have large responsibilities over their economies. The average annual [[Compound annual growth rate|growth rate]]s (2007\u201312) for [[Gujarat]] (13.86%), [[Uttarakhand]] (13.66%), [[Bihar]] (10.15%) or [[Jharkhand]] (9.85%) were higher than for [[West Bengal]] (6.24%), [[Maharashtra]] (7.84%), [[Odisha]] (7.05%), [[Punjab]] (11.78%) or [[Assam]] (5.88%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esopb.gov.in/static/PDF/GSDP/Statewise-Data/state%2520wise%2520data.pdf|work=[[Government of India]]|title=State Wise Data|accessdate=11 December 2016|date=29 February 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110192818/http://www.esopb.gov.in/static/PDF/GSDP/Statewise-Data/state%20wise%20data.pdf|archivedate=10 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> India is the [[List of countries by GDP (nominal)|sixth-largest]] economy in the world and the [[List of countries by GDP (PPP)|third largest]] by purchasing power parity adjusted exchange rates (PPP). On per capita basis, it ranks [[List of countries by GDP (nominal) per capita|140th]] in the world or [[List of countries by GDP (PPP) per capita|129th]] by PPP.\n\nThe economic growth has been driven by the expansion of the services that have been growing consistently faster than other sectors. It is argued that the pattern of Indian development has been a specific one and that the country may be able to skip the intermediate [[industrialisation]]-led phase in the transformation of its economic structure. Serious concerns have been raised about the jobless nature of the economic growth.<ref name=\"for example Novotny and Ramachandran 2010\">NOVOTN\u00dd, J., RAMACHANDRAN, N. (2010): Alternative to jobless growth? All-India context and a case of participatory development scheme from rural Tamil Nadu . Geografie, 115, 3, 330\u2013346. {{cite web |url=http://web.natur.cuni.cz/~pepino/Novotny_Ramachandran_2010_Alternative_to_jobless_growth.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-10-23 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721002035/http://web.natur.cuni.cz/~pepino/Novotny_Ramachandran_2010_Alternative_to_jobless_growth.pdf |archivedate=21 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orfonline.org/programme/economy-and-growth/|title=Economy and Growth|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007021132/http://www.orfonline.org/programme/economy-and-growth/|archivedate=7 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFavourable macroeconomic performance has been a necessary but not sufficient condition for the significant reduction of poverty amongst the Indian population. The rate of poverty decline has not been higher in the post-reform period (since 1991){{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}. The improvements in some other non-economic dimensions of social development have been even less favourable. The most pronounced example is an exceptionally high and persistent level of child malnutrition (46% in 2005\u20136).<ref name=\"Chatterjee 2007\">CHATTERJEE, P. (2007): Child malnutrition rises in India despite economic boom. The\nLancet, 369, No. 9571, pp. 1417\u20131418.</ref>\n\nThe progress of economic reforms in India is followed closely. The [[World Bank]] suggests that the most important priorities are public sector reform, infrastructure, agricultural and rural development, removal of labour regulations, reforms in lagging states, and HIV/AIDS.<ref>[http://www.worldbank.org.in/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/COUNTRIES/SOUTHASIAEXT/INDIAEXTN/0,,contentMDK:20195738~menuPK:295591~pagePK:141137~piPK:141127~theSitePK:295584,00.html India Country Overview 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522115104/http://www.worldbank.org.in/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/COUNTRIES/SOUTHASIAEXT/INDIAEXTN/0%2C%2CcontentMDK%3A20195738~menuPK%3A295591~pagePK%3A141137~piPK%3A141127~theSitePK%3A295584%2C00.html |date=22 May 2011 }}. [[World Bank]]</ref> For 2018, India ranked 77th in [[Ease of Doing Business Index]]. According to [[Index of Economic Freedom]] World Ranking an annual survey on economic freedom of the nations, India ranks 123rd as compared with China and Russia which ranks 138th and 144th respectively in 2014.\n\nAt the turn of the century India's GDP was at around US$480 billion. As economic reforms picked up pace, India's GDP grew five-fold to reach US$2.2 trillion in 2015 (as per IMF estimates).\n\nIndia's GDP growth during January\u2013March period of 2015 was at 7.5% compared to China's 7%, making it the fastest growing economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rt.com/business/230915-india-china-world-economy/|title=New GDP calculation puts India growing faster than China|work=RT International|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150211164749/http://rt.com/business/230915-india-china-world-economy/|archivedate=11 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2015/02/11/its-official-india-has-passed-china-to-become-the-worlds-fastest-growing-economy/|title=India Passes China to Become Fastest-Growing Economy|author=Eric Bellman|work=WSJ|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813003622/https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2015/02/11/its-official-india-has-passed-china-to-become-the-worlds-fastest-growing-economy/|archivedate=13 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/Economy/india-pegs-201415-gdp-growth-at-74-per-cent/article6874926.ece|title=India fastest growing economy|author=Puja Mehra|work=The Hindu|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205011840/http://www.thehindu.com/business/Economy/india-pegs-201415-gdp-growth-at-74-per-cent/article6874926.ece|archivedate=5 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> During 2014\u201315, India's GDP growth recovered marginally to 7.3% from 6.9% in the previous fiscal. During 2014\u201315, India's services sector grew by 10.1%, manufacturing sector by 7.1% & agriculture by 0.2%. Indian Economy grew at 7.6 & 7.1 in FY 2015\u201316 and FY 2016\u201317 respectively as major reforms had  taken place like Demonitisation and implementation of GST in FY 2016\u201317.The Economic Growth has Been Slow Down in 2017\u201318 and it is expected to grow at 6.7 and forecasted to Rebound by 8.2% in 2018\u201319{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}.\n\n== History ==\nPrior to [[Independence Day (India)|India's Independence,]] from the period of 1900 to 1947, per capita income in India had either declined or stagnated. Post-Independence, [[Jawaharlal Nehru|Jawaharal Nehru]] enacted an economic policy based on [[import substitution industrialization]]. The Nehru-Mahalanobis approach, often referred to as the [[Five-Year Plans of India|Second Five Year Plan]], emphasized the development of basic and heavy industries as a means of accelerating economic growth. These included steel, copper, petrochemicals, paper, coal, and oil.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Nehru Mahalanobis Model|last=Bhatia|first=V.G.|date=1990|work=Economic and Political Weekly|jstor = 4396620}}</ref> [[Prasanta Chandra Mahalanobis|Mahalanobis]] strived for India to reach autonomy, ridding any outstanding debts. Critics disagreed with this approach, stating that [[World Bank|World Bank's]] claim of Indian export prospects being low were falsified and due to India's inward-looking strategy, the growth opportunity of the world economy was missed.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2015|title=Editorial Note|journal=Social Scientist|volume=43|issue=3/4|pages=1\u20132|issn=0970-0293|jstor=24372931}}</ref> Nonetheless, over 1950\u20131965, India's acceleration of per capita income growth had increased an average of 1.7%, a value not exceeded since.\n\nThe discourse on the efficacy of the Nehru-Mahalanobis Strategy is commonly contested by economists. A criticism of the approach emphasizes the lack of resource allocation in the agriculture sector. It is argued that the misbalanced weightage towards the machine-making sector contributed to the increase in food-grain prices and thus, perpetuated poverty and malnutrition.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Patnaik|first=Prabhat|date=March 2015|title=The Nehru\u2013Mahalanobis Strategy|journal=Social Scientist|volume=43|issue=3/4|pages=3\u201310|jstor=24372932}}</ref> Defenders of the strategy claim that it sought to increase agricultural output by increasing the [[Incremental capital-output ratio|output-capital ratio]]. This agreeably would have been accomplished through [[Land reform|land-reforms]], something the strategy did not address, not indicating a problem with the strategy itself.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Agriculture==\n{{main|Agriculture in India}}\n[[File:Composition of indias agricultural output in 2003-04.png|thumb|300px|Composition of India's total production of foodgrains and commercial crops, in 2003\u201304, by weight]]\nIndia [[List of countries by GDP sector composition|ranks second]] worldwide in farm output. Agriculture and allied sectors like [[forestry]], logging and fishing accounted for 18.6% of the GDP in 2005, employed 60% of the total workforce<ref name=\"CIA\">{{cite web\n |title       = CIA&nbsp;\u2014 The World Factbook&nbsp;\u2014 India\n |publisher   = CIA\n |date        = 20 September 2007\n |url         = https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/in.html#Econ\n |accessdate  = 2 October 2007\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080611033144/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/in.html#Econ\n |archivedate = 11 June 2008\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> and despite a steady decline of its share in the GDP, is still the largest economic sector and plays a significant role in the overall socio-economic development of India. [[Crop yield|Yields]] per unit area of all crops have grown since 1950, due to the special emphasis placed on agriculture in the [[Five-year plans of India#First Plan .281951-1956.29|five-year plan]]s and steady improvements in [[irrigation]], technology, application of modern agricultural practices and provision of agricultural credit and subsidies since the [[Green revolution in India|green revolution]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}}\n\nIndia is the largest producer in the world of milk, cashew nuts, coconuts, tea, ginger, turmeric and black pepper.<ref>[http://www.ibpn.co.uk/agriculture.asp Agriculture sector] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071226040933/http://www.ibpn.co.uk/agriculture.asp |date=26 December 2007 }} Indo British Partnership network, Retrieved on December 2007</ref> It also has the world's largest cattle population (193&nbsp;million).<ref>Lester R. Brown [http://www.earth-policy.org/Updates/Update6.htm World's Rangelands Deteriorating Under Mounting Pressure] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080311003923/http://www.earth-policy.org/Updates/Update6.htm |date=11 March 2008 }} Earth Policy Institute, Retrieved on- February 2008</ref> It is the second largest producer of wheat, rice, sugar, groundnut and inland fish.<ref name=\"agrind\">[http://www.ficciagroindia.com/indian-agriculture/indian-agriculture.htm Indian agriculture] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080225074057/http://www.ficciagroindia.com/indian-agriculture/indian-agriculture.htm |date=25 February 2008 }} Agribusiness Information Centre, Retrieved on- February 2008</ref> It is the third largest producer of tobacco.<ref name=\"agrind\"/> India accounts for 10% of the world fruit production with first rank in the production of banana and [[sapota]], also known as chiku.<ref name=\"agrind\"/>\n\nThe required level of investment for the development of marketing, storage and cold storage infrastructure is estimated to be huge. The government has implemented various schemes to raise investment in marketing infrastructure. Amongst these schemes are ''Construction of Rural Go downs'', ''Market Research and Information Network'', and ''Development / Strengthening of [[Agricultural Marketing]] Infrastructure, Grading and Standardisation''.<ref>[http://india.gov.in/sectors/agriculture/agri_marketing.php Agriculture marketing] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080205003341/http://india.gov.in/sectors/agriculture/agri_marketing.php |date=5 February 2008 }} india.gov Retrieved on- February 2008</ref>\n\nMain problems in the agricultural sector, as listed by the World Bank, are:<ref name=\"agriculturepriorities\">[http://web.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/COUNTRIES/SOUTHASIAEXT/EXTSAREGTOPAGRI/0,,contentMDK:20273764~menuPK:548214~pagePK:34004173~piPK:34003707~theSitePK:452766,00.html India: Priorities for Agriculture and Rural Development] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090121122011/http://web.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/COUNTRIES/SOUTHASIAEXT/EXTSAREGTOPAGRI/0,,contentMDK:20273764~menuPK:548214~pagePK:34004173~piPK:34003707~theSitePK:452766,00.html |date=21 January 2009 }}. [[World Bank]]</ref>\n* India's large [[agricultural subsidies]] are hampering productivity-enhancing investment.\n* Overregulation of agriculture has increased costs, price risks and uncertainty.\n* Government interventions in labour, land, and credit markets.\n* Inadequate infrastructure and services.\n\n===Research and  development===\nThe [[Indian Agricultural Research Institute]] (IARI), established in 1905, was responsible for the research leading to the \"[[Indian Green Revolution]]\" of the 1970s. The [[Indian Council of Agricultural Research]] (ICAR) is the apex body in kundiure and related allied fields, including research and education.<ref>[http://www.iari.res.in/objectives.php Objectives] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071024132458/http://www.iari.res.in/objectives.php |date=24 October 2007 }} Indian agricultural research institute, Retrieved on December 2007</ref> The Union Minister of Agriculture is the President of the ICAR. The [[Indian Agricultural Statistics Research Institute]] develops new techniques for the design of agricultural experiments, analyses data in agriculture, and specialises in statistical techniques for animal and plant breeding.\nProf. [[M.S. Swaminathan]] is known as \"Father of the Green Revolution\" and heads the MS Swaminathan Research Foundation.<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/asia/asia/magazine/1999/990823/swaminathan1.html MS Swaminathan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080114015753/http://www.time.com/time/asia/asia/magazine/1999/990823/swaminathan1.html |date=14 January 2008 }} Times Inc. Retrieved on- 21 February 2008</ref> He is known for his advocacy of environmentally [[sustainable agriculture]] and sustainable [[food security]].\n\n==Industrial output==\n[[File:India industry.jpg|thumb|An industrial zone near [[Mumbai]]]]\nIndia is [[List of countries by GDP sector composition|tenth]] in the world in factory output. Manufacturing sector in addition to mining, [[quarrying]], electricity and gas together account for 27.6% of the GDP and employ 17% of the total workforce. Economic reforms introduced after 1991 brought foreign competition, led to privatisation of certain public sector industries, opened up sectors hitherto reserved for the public sector and led to an expansion in the production of fast-moving [[Final goods|consumer goods]]. In recent years, Indian cities have continued to liberalise, but excessive and burdensome business regulations remain a problem in some cities, like Kochi and Kolkata.<ref name=\"World Bank and International Financial Corporation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.doingbusiness.org/subnational/exploreeconomies/India2009.aspx|title=Doing Business in India 2009|publisher=[[World Bank]]|accessdate=8 June 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101007005506/http://doingbusiness.org/subnational/exploreeconomies/India2009.aspx|archivedate=7 October 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nPost-liberalisation, the Indian private sector, which was usually run by oligopolies of old family firms and required political connections to prosper was faced with foreign competition, including the threat of cheaper Chinese imports. It has since handled the change by squeezing costs, revamping management, focusing on designing new products and relying on low labour costs and [[technology]].<ref name=\"compete\">{{cite news|title=Indian manufacturers learn to compete |date=12 February 2004 |work=The Economist |url=http://economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=S%27%298%3C%2FPQ%3B%21%21P%214%0A |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://wayback.vefsafn.is/wayback/20071213195957/http://economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=S%27%298%3C%2FPQ%3B%21%21P%214%0A |archivedate=13 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nIndia [[List of countries by GDP sector composition|is fifteenth]] in services output. [[Tertiary sector of economic activity|Service industry]] employ [[Indian English|English-speaking Indian]] workers on the [[Supply and demand|supply side]] and on the demand side, has increased demand from foreign consumers interested in India's service exports or those looking to outsource their operations. [[Indian IT industry|India's IT industry]], despite contributing significantly to its [[balance of payments]], accounts for only about 1% of the total GDP or 1/50th of the total services.<ref name=\"Revolution\">{{cite journal|author1=Gordon, Jim|author2=Gupta, Poonam|title=Understanding India's Services Revolution|year=2003|version=12 November 2003|url=http://www.imf.org/external/np/apd/seminars/2003/newdelhi/gordon.pdf|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326211643/http://www.imf.org/external/np/apd/seminars/2003/newdelhi/gordon.pdf|archivedate=26 March 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring the Internet bubble that led up to 2000, heavy investments in undersea fibre-optic cables linked Asia with the rest of the world. The fall that followed the economic boom resulted in the auction of cheap fiber optic cables at one-tenth of their original price. This development resulted in widely available low-cost communications [[infrastructure]]. All of these investments and events, not to mention a swell of available talent, resulted in India becoming almost overnight the centre for outsourcing of Business process.<ref>What's Next for the Startup nation {{cite web|url=http://www.startup-nation.com/the-book/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-08-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120819031009/http://startup-nation.com/the-book/ |archivedate=19 August 2012 }}</ref> Within this sector and events, the [[ITES]]-[[Business process outsourcing|BPO]] sector has become a big employment generator especially amongst young college graduates. The number of professionals employed by IT and ITES sectors is estimated at around 1.3&nbsp;million as of March 2006. Also, Indian IT-ITES is estimated to have helped create an additional 3 million job opportunities through indirect, induced and in helpful manner have created employment.<ref>[http://india.gov.in/sectors/communication/ites_bpo.php ITES and BPO Services] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213174333/http://india.gov.in/sectors/communication/ites_bpo.php |date=13 February 2008 }} india.gov Retrieved on- February 2008</ref>\n\n==GDP growth rate==\nSince the economic liberalisation of 1991, India's GDP has been growing at a higher rate.<ref name=\"GDP growth\">[http://www.indexmundi.com/g/g.aspx?v=66&c=in&l=en India&nbsp;\u2013 GDP&nbsp;\u2013 real growth rate (%)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305185731/http://www.indexmundi.com/g/g.aspx?v=66&c=in&l=en |date=5 March 2012 }}.</ref> The following table has been collected from public data archives<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG?end=2017&locations=IN&start=2000|title=GDP growth (annual %) {{!}} Data|website=data.worldbank.org|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref> with data from the [[World Bank]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Growth (real) (%)\n|-\n| 2000 || 3.841\n|-\n| 2001 || 4.824\n|-\n| 2002 || 3.804\n|-\n| 2003 || 7.86\n|-\n| 2004 || 7.923\n|-\n| 2005 || 7.923\n|-\n| 2006 || 8.061\n|-\n| 2007 || 7.661\n|-\n| 2008 || 3.087\n|-\n| 2009 || 7.862\n|-\n| 2010 || 8.498\n|-\n| 2011 || 5.241\n|-\n| 2012 || 5.456\n|-\n| 2013 || 6.386\n|-\n| 2014 || 7.41\n|-\n| 2015 || 7.996\n|-\n| 2016 || 8.17\n|-\n| 2017\n|7.168\n|-\n| 2018\n|6.982\n|}\n\nGDP growth rate is unequal within India. For the year 2015\u201316, GDP growth rates of [[Andhra Pradesh]] (10.99%), [[Bihar]] (10.27%) and [[Madhya Pradesh]] (10.16%) were higher than [[Maharashtra]] (8%), [[Odisha]] (6.16%) and [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] (5.96%).<ref>{{cite news |title=AP stands 1st in India in GSDP growth rate |url=http://m.timesofindia.com/city/hyderabad/AP-stands-1st-in-India-in-GSDP-growth-rate/articleshow/52709609.cms |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |accessdate=5 April 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170604195054/http://m.timesofindia.com/city/hyderabad/AP-stands-1st-in-India-in-GSDP-growth-rate/articleshow/52709609.cms |archivedate=4 June 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Companies==\n47 Indian companies were listed in the [[Forbes Global 2000]] ranking for 2015.<ref name=\"fg2-2007\">{{cite news|title = Forbes Global 2000 (Ger-Ind)|url = https://www.forbes.com/global2000/list/|accessdate = 22 July 2015|url-status = live|archiveurl = http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20150408120044/https://www.forbes.com/global2000/list/|archivedate = 8 April 2015|df = dmy-all}}</ref> The 10 leading companies were:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n!World Rank !! Company !! class=\"unsortable\"|Logo !! Industry !! Revenue <br /> (billion $) !! Profits  <br /> (billion $) !! Assets  <br /> (billion $) !! Market Value  <br /> (billion $)\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|142 || align=\"left\" | [[Reliance Industries]] || align=\"center\" |   || align=\"left\" | Oil & Gas Operations || 71.7 ||  3.7    ||  76.6    || 42.9\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|152 || align=\"left\" | [[State Bank of India]] || align=\"center\" | [[File:SBI-logo.svg|40px|State Bank of India logo]] || align=\"left\"|Banking || 40.8 ||  2.3    ||  400.6    || 33\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|183 || align=\"left\" | [[Oil and Natural Gas Corporation]] || align=\"center\" |  || align=\"left\" |Oil & Gas Operations ||  28.7    ||  4.4    ||  59.3    || 43.7\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|263 || align=\"left\" | [[Tata Motors]] || ||| || 42.3 || 2.7 ||  34.7    || 28.8\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|283 || align=\"left\" | [[ICICI Bank]] || align=\"center\" | [[File:ICICI Bank Logo.svg|54px]] || align=\"left\"  | Banking ||  14.2    || 1.9 || 124.8 || 30\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|431 || align=\"left\" | [[NTPC Limited|NTPC]] || align=\"center\" | [[File:National Thermal Power logo.svg|50px]] || align=\"left\" |  Utilities || 12.9 || 1.9 || 35.4 || 20.2\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|463|| align=\"left\" | [[Tata Steel]] || align=\"center\" | [[File:Tata Steel Logo.svg|54px]] || align=\"left\" | Materials || 32.77 || 3.08   || 31.16 || 2.46\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|349 || align=\"left\" | [[Indian Oil Corporation]] || align=\"center\" |  || align=\"left\" | Oil & Gas Operations ||  74.3 || 1.2 ||44.7 || 14.6\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|485 || align=\"left\" | [[HDFC Bank|HDFC]] || align=\"center\" |  || align=\"left\" | Banking || 8.4 || 1.4 ||  84.3  || 41.6\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|485 || align=\"left\" | [[Tata consultancy services|TCS]] || align=\"center\" | || align=\"left\" | Information Technology ||  15.1  || 3.5 ||  11   || 80.3\n|}\n\n==India's resource consumption==\n{{see|resource consumption}}\n\n===Oil===\nIndia [[oil consumption|consumes the second-largest amount of oil]] in the Asia-Pacific region behind China. The combination of rising oil consumption and fairly unwavering production levels leaves India highly dependent on imports to meet the consumption needs.\n\n===Natural gas===\nAs per the Oil and Gas Journal, India had {{convert|38|e12cuft|m3}} of confirmed natural gas reserves in 2004.<ref name=\"eia3\">\n{{cite web|url=http://www.eia.doe.gov/emeu/cabs/India/NaturalGas.html|title=Energy Information Administration (EIA)|publisher=Statistical agency of the U.S. Department of Energy|accessdate=27 October 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018085858/http://eia.doe.gov/emeu/cabs/India/NaturalGas.html|archivedate=18 October 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIndia imports small amounts of natural gas. In 2004, India consumed about {{convert|1089|Gcuft|m3|abbr=on}} of natural gas, the first year in which the country showed net natural gas imports. During 2004, India imported {{convert|93|Gcuft|m3|abbr=on}} of [[liquefied natural gas]] (LNG) from Qatar.<ref name=\"eia3\"/>\n\nAs in the oil sector, India's state-owned companies account for the bulk of natural gas production. [[ONGC]] and [[Oil India Ltd]]. (OIL) are the leading companies with respect to production volume, whilst some foreign companies take part in upstream developments in joint-ventures and production sharing contracts ('''PSC'''s). [[Reliance Industries]], a privately owned Indian company, will also have a bigger role in the natural gas sector as a result of a large natural gas find in 2002 in the [[Krishna Godavari basin]].<ref name=\"eia3\"/>\n\nThe [[Gas Authority of India Ltd.]] (GAIL) holds an effective control on natural gas transmission and allocation activities. In December 2006, the Minister of Petroleum and Natural Gas issued a new policy that allows foreign investors, private domestic companies, and [[national oil company|national oil companies]] to hold up to 100% equity stakes in pipeline projects. Whilst GAIL's domination in natural gas transmission and allocation is not ensured by statute, it will continue to be the leading player in the sector because of its existing natural gas infrastructure.<ref name=\"eia3\"/>\n\n==Issues==\n{{see also|Economy of India}}\n\n===Regulation, public sector, corruption,===\n{{main|Corruption in India}}\nIndia ranked 63 on the [[Ease of Doing Business Index]] in 2020, compared with 108 for Pakistan, 31 for People's Republic of China, 131 for Nigeria, 124 for Brazil, and 73 for Indonesia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doingbusiness.org/en/rankings |title=Rankings & Ease of Doing Business Score |accessdate=14 January 2019 |publisher=The World Bank }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Index of Corruption by Indian states in 2005.png|thumb|Extent of corruption in Indian states, as [[Index of perception of corruption|measured]] in a 2005 study by [[Transparency International]] India. (Darker regions are more corrupt)<ref name=\"2005-TI-study\">{{cite journal|author=Centre for Media Studies |title=India Corruption Study 2005: To Improve Governance Volume&nbsp;\u2013 I: Key Highlights |publisher=Transparency International India |year=2005 |url=http://www.prajanet.org/newsroom/internal/tii/ICS2k5_Vol1.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326211644/http://www.prajanet.org/newsroom/internal/tii/ICS2k5_Vol1.pdf |archivedate=26 March 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>]]\n\n[[Corruption]] in many forms has been one of the pervasive problems affecting India. For decades, the [[red tape]], [[bureaucracy]] and the ''[[Licence Raj]]'' that had strangled private enterprise.<ref name=\"bradford\">{{cite journal|author=DeLong, J. Bradford |title=India Since Independence: An Analytic Growth Narrative |year=2001 |url=http://ksghome.harvard.edu/~drodrik/Growth%20volume/DeLong-India.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071202122432/http://ksghome.harvard.edu/~drodrik/Growth%20volume/DeLong-India.pdf |archivedate= 2 December 2007 |author-link=J. Bradford DeLong }}</ref> The economic reforms of 1991 cut some of the worst regulations that had been used in corruption.\n\nCorruption is still large. A 2005 study by [[Transparency International]] (TI) India found that more than half of those surveyed had firsthand experience of paying a bribe or peddling influence to get a job done in a public office.<ref name=\"2005-TI-study\"/> The chief economic consequences of corruption are the loss to the [[exchequer]], an unhealthy climate for investment and an increase in the cost of government-subsidised services. The TI India study estimates the monetary value of petty corruption in 11 basic services provided by the government, like [[education]], [[healthcare]], [[judiciary]], [[police]], etc., to be around {{INRConvert|211|b|1}}.<ref name=\"2005-TI-study\"/> India still ranks in the bottom quartile of developing nations in terms of the ease of doing business, and compared with China, the average time taken to secure the clearances for a [[startup company|startup]] or to invoke [[bankruptcy]] is much greater.\n\nThe [[Right to Information Act]] (2005) and equivalent acts in the states, that require government officials to furnish information requested by citizens or face punitive action, computerisation of services and various central and state government acts that established vigilance commissions have considerably reduced corruption or at least have opened up avenues to redress grievances.<ref name=\"2005-TI-study\"/><ref name=\"rightto\">[http://www.mit.gov.in/rti.asp Example] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051027095556/http://www.mit.gov.in/rti.asp |date=27 October 2005 }} of a central government department's implementation of the Right to Information Act.</ref> The 2006 report by Transparency International puts India at 70th place and states that significant improvements were made by India in reducing corruption.<ref name=\"transparency1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.transparency.org/news_room/latest_news/press_releases/2006/en_2006_11_06_cpi_2006 |title=Transparency International Press release |publisher=Transparency.org |accessdate=12 July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625122546/http://www.transparency.org/news_room/latest_news/press_releases/2006/en_2006_11_06_cpi_2006 |archivedate=25 June 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"transparency2\">[http://www.transparency.org/news_room/in_focus/cpi_2006/cpi_table Transparency International Press release] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070219124000/http://www.transparency.org/news_room/in_focus/cpi_2006/cpi_table |date=19 February 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===Employment===\nIndia's labour force is growing by 2.5% every year, but employment is growing only at 2.3% a year.<ref name=\"unemployment\">{{cite web|url=http://newsgroups.derkeiler.com/pdf/Archive/Soc/soc.culture.pakistan/2008-09/msg00054.pdf |title=Growing Unemployment Problem in India |accessdate=12 July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090521093147/http://newsgroups.derkeiler.com/pdf/Archive/Soc/soc.culture.pakistan/2008-09/msg00054.pdf |archivedate=21 May 2009 }}</ref> Official unemployment exceeds 9%. Regulation and other obstacles have discouraged the emergence of formal businesses and jobs. Almost 30% of workers are casual workers who work only when they are able to get jobs and remain unpaid for the rest of the time.<ref name=\"unemployment\"/> Only 10% of the workforce is in regular employment.<ref name=\"unemployment\"/> India's labour regulations are heavy even by developing country standards and analysts have urged the government to abolish them.<ref name=\"oecd\">[http://www.oecd.org/dataoecd/17/52/39452196.pdf Economic survey of India 2007: Policy Brief] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606000000/http://www.oecd.org/dataoecd/17/52/39452196.pdf |date=6 June 2011 }}. [[OECD]].</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4103554.stm|title=Why India needs labour law reform|work=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110119051601/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4103554.stm|archivedate=19 January 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFrom the overall stock of an estimated 458 million workers, 394&nbsp;million (86%) operate in the unorganised sector (of which 63% are self-employed) mostly as informal workers. There is a strong relationship between the quality of employment and social and poverty characteristics.<ref name=\"Sengupta et al. 2008\">SENGUPTA, A., KANNAN, K. P., RAVEENDRAN, G. (2008): India's common people: who are they, how many are they and how do they live? Economic and Political Weekly, 43, No. 11, pp. 49\u201363.{{cite web|url=http://www.sum.uio.no/pdf/2008_EPW_Indias%20Com%20People.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-10-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614132413/http://www.sum.uio.no/pdf/2008_EPW_Indias%20Com%20People.pdf |archivedate=14 June 2011 }}.</ref> The relative growth of informal employment was more rapid within the organised rather than the unorganised sector. This informalisation is also related to the flexibilisation of employment in the organised sector that is suggested by the increasing use of contract labour by employers in order to benefit from more flexible labour practices.<ref name=\"for example Novotny and Ramachandran 2010\" />\n\nChildren under 14 constitute 3.6% of the total [[Workforce|labour]] force in the country. Of these children, 9 out of every 10 work in their own rural family settings. Around 85% of them are engaged in traditional agricultural activities. Less than 9% work in manufacturing, [[Service (economics)|service]]s and [[repair]]s.<ref name=\"chilab\">\n{{cite web | url=http://www.indianembassy.org/policy/Child_Labor/childlabor.htm|title=Child Labour and India|publisher=Embassy of India, Washington, DC|accessdate=28 November 2007}}</ref>\n[[Child labour]] is a complex problem that is basically rooted in poverty. The Indian government is implementing the world's largest child labour elimination program, with primary education targeted for ~250&nbsp;million. Numerous non-governmental and voluntary organisations are also involved. Special investigation cells have been set up in states to enforce existing laws banning employment of children (under 14) in hazardous industries. The allocation of the Government of India for the eradication of [[child labour]] was {{USD}}10&nbsp;million in 1995\u201396 and {{USD}}16&nbsp;million in 1996\u201397. The allocation for 2007 is {{USD}}21&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"chilab\"/>\n\n===Environmental degradation===\n{{main|Environmental issues in India}}\nAbout 1.2&nbsp;billion people in developing nations lack clean, safe water because most household and industrial wastes are dumped directly into rivers and lakes without treatment. This contributes to the rapid increase in [[waterborne diseases]] in humans.<ref>Gleick PH. 1993. Water in Crisis. New York: Oxford University Press.</ref> Out of India's 3119 towns and cities, just 209 have partial treatment facilities, and only 8 have full wastewater treatment facilities (WHO 1992).<ref>Russell Hopfenberg and David Pimentel [http://www.oilcrash.com/articles/populatn.htm HUMAN POPULATION NUMBERS AS A FUNCTION OF FOOD SUPPLY] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080313172624/http://www.oilcrash.com/articles/populatn.htm |date=13 March 2008 }} oilcrash.com Retrieved on- February 2008</ref> 114 cities dump untreated [[sewage]] and partially cremated bodies directly into the [[Ganges River]].<ref>National Geographic Society. 1995. Water: A Story of Hope. Washington (DC): National Geographic Society</ref> Downstream, the untreated water is used for drinking, bathing, and washing. This situation is typical of many rivers in India as well as other developing countries.\nGlobally, but especially in developing nations like India where people cook with [[fuelwood]] and coal over open fires, about 4&nbsp;billion humans suffer continuous exposure to [[smoke]]. In India, particulate concentrations in houses are reported to range from 8,300 to 15,000 \u03bcg/m<sup>3</sup>, greatly exceeding the 75 \u03bcg/m<sup>3</sup> maximum standard for indoor particulate matter in the United States.<ref>Christiani DC. 1993. Urban and trans-boundary [[air pollution]]: Human health consequences. Pages 13\u201330 in Chivian E, McCally M, Hu H, Haines A, eds. Critical Condition: Human Health and the Environment. Cambridge (MA): MIT Press.</ref>\nChanges in ecosystem biological diversity, evolution of parasites, and invasion by exotic species all frequently result in disease outbreaks such as [[cholera]] which emerged in 1992 in India. The frequency of AIDS/HIV is increasing. In 1996, about 46,000 Indians out of 2.8&nbsp;million (1.6% of the population) tested were found to be infected with HIV.<ref name=\"hivaids\">Burns JF. 1996. Denial and taboo blind India to the horror of its [[AIDS]] scourge. New York Times, 22 September: A1.</ref>\n\n=== Effect on women ===\nEconomic development in India has had a varying effect on women depending on their age, education, and location. Traditionally in India women's role is in the household. As girls they are raised to work for and better their family. Their work, therefore, mostly consists of household duties and is not a part of the formal economy. Because of this India consistently compares poorly to other countries as far as female employment rates. Currently India ranks 11th from the bottom in female labor participation out of the 131 countries with data available.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Batra. Reio|first=Renu.Thomas|date=2016|title=Gender Inequality Issues in India|url=|journal=Advances in Developing Human Resources|volume=|pages=|via=SAGE}}</ref> In addition, women who do work experience discrimination; on average they make 62% of what their male counterparts make for the same position<ref name=\":0\" />.\n\nSince the 1990s there has been significant economic growth and expansion in India,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chakraborty|first=Indrani|date=2010|title=Financial Development and Economic Growth in India: An Analysis of the Post-reform Period|url=|journal=South Asia Economic Journal|volume=|pages=|via=SAGE}}</ref> this has had an effect on how women operate in the workforce there.Women's labor force participation has actually fallen from 37% in 2004\u20132005 to 27% in 2009\u20132019.<ref name=\":0\" /> So with the recent economic growth and development in India, the country has not seen an equal overall growth in jobs for women. This can be broken down further, however, because certain demographics of women in India have seen job rates decline while some have seen them rise. Informal work, which is not included in job rate percentages, has risen for poor, rural, uneducated women while their formal job rate has declined; Microcredit and social help groups have helped poor women connect and work together in the informal job sector.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Davidson, Sanyal|first=Thomas, Paromita|date=June 2017|title=Associational Participation and Network Expansion: Microcredit Self-Help Groups and Poor Women's Social Ties in Rural India|url=|journal=Project Muse|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Women with higher education who mostly live in urban areas have seen a rise in job rates.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAn example of a booming industry for educated women in India is call centers.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Forey|first=Gail|date=2013|title=The impact of call centre employment on women in India|url=|journal=World Englishes|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Many Western countries outsource their call center jobs to India, and these call centers have found that women often have more success at these positions than their male counterparts. These positions give young women in India a chance at independence from their family and the traditional role which women play.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Indian Women Working in Call Centers: Sites of Resistance?|last=Mattingly|first=Doreen|publisher=IGI Clobal|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=156\u2013167}}</ref> There are organizations in India that were created to support women's education and women in the workforce. In 1985 the Ministry of Human Resource Development was founded to improve female literacy rates, and to support women looking to join the work force. Similarly, in 1972 SEWA, the Self Employed Women's Association, was formed by self-employed and low wage women workers to support each other and organize to advocate for their rights.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India|Economics|Business and economics}}\n* [[List of megaprojects in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://web.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/WBI/WBIPROGRAMS/KFDLP/0,,contentMDK:21002801~menuPK:2792475~pagePK:64156158~piPK:64152884~theSitePK:461198,00.html India and the Knowledge Economy]&nbsp;\u2013 a [[World Bank Institute]] report.\n* [http://finmin.nic.in/ Finance Ministry of India]\n* [http://www.indiainbusiness.nic.in/ India in Business] \u2013 Official website for Investment and Trade in India\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071019022045/http://www.rbi.org.in/scripts/Statistics.aspx Reserve Bank of India's database on the Indian economy]\n* [http://www.ibef.org/ India Brand Equity Foundation]\n* [http://dpe.nic.in/ Department of Public Enterprises]\n* [https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/in.html CIA&nbsp;\u2013 The World Factbook&nbsp;\u2013 India]\n* [http://www.cerium.ca/article1684.html Chindia: The next Decade] \u2013 [[Business Week]] writer Pete Engardio compares the rise of both China and India in this online video conference. (video)\n{{Good article}}\n{{Economy of India topics}}\n\n[[Category:Economy of India]]\n[[Category:Development in Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2016}}\n\n{{main|Economy of India}}\n\nThe '''economic development in India''' followed [[socialist]]-inspired politicians for most of its independent history, including state-ownership of many sectors; [[India]]'s per capita income increased at only around [[Hindu rate of growth|1% annualised rate]] in the three decades after its independence.<ref name=\"oecd\"/> Since the mid-1980s, India has slowly opened up its markets through [[Economic reforms in India|economic liberalisation]]. After more fundamental reforms since 1991 and their renewal in the 2000s, India has progressed towards a [[free market economy]].<ref name=\"oecd\"/>\n \nIn the late 2000s, India's growth reached 7.5%, which will double the average income in a decade.<ref name=\"oecd\"/> IMF says that if India pushed more fundamental market reforms, it could sustain the rate and even reach the government's 2011 target of 10%.<ref name=\"oecd\"/> States have large responsibilities over their economies. The average annual [[Compound annual growth rate|growth rate]]s (2007\u201312) for [[Gujarat]] (13.86%), [[Uttarakhand]] (13.66%), [[Bihar]] (10.15%) or [[Jharkhand]] (9.85%) were higher than for [[West Bengal]] (6.24%), [[Maharashtra]] (7.84%), [[Odisha]] (7.05%), [[Punjab]] (11.78%) or [[Assam]] (5.88%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esopb.gov.in/static/PDF/GSDP/Statewise-Data/state%2520wise%2520data.pdf|work=[[Government of India]]|title=State Wise Data|accessdate=11 December 2016|date=29 February 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110192818/http://www.esopb.gov.in/static/PDF/GSDP/Statewise-Data/state%20wise%20data.pdf|archivedate=10 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> India is the [[List of countries by GDP (nominal)|sixth-largest]] economy in the world and the [[List of countries by GDP (PPP)|third largest]] by purchasing power parity adjusted exchange rates (PPP). On per capita basis, it ranks [[List of countries by GDP (nominal) per capita|140th]] in the world or [[List of countries by GDP (PPP) per capita|129th]] by PPP.\n\nThe economic growth has been driven by the expansion of the services that have been growing consistently faster than other sectors. It is argued that the pattern of Indian development has been a specific one and that the country may be able to skip the intermediate [[industrialisation]]-led phase in the transformation of its economic structure. Serious concerns have been raised about the jobless nature of the economic growth.<ref name=\"for example Novotny and Ramachandran 2010\">NOVOTN\u00dd, J., RAMACHANDRAN, N. (2010): Alternative to jobless growth? All-India context and a case of participatory development scheme from rural Tamil Nadu . Geografie, 115, 3, 330\u2013346. {{cite web |url=http://web.natur.cuni.cz/~pepino/Novotny_Ramachandran_2010_Alternative_to_jobless_growth.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-10-23 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721002035/http://web.natur.cuni.cz/~pepino/Novotny_Ramachandran_2010_Alternative_to_jobless_growth.pdf |archivedate=21 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orfonline.org/programme/economy-and-growth/|title=Economy and Growth|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007021132/http://www.orfonline.org/programme/economy-and-growth/|archivedate=7 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFavourable macroeconomic performance has been a necessary but not sufficient condition for the significant reduction of poverty amongst the Indian population. The rate of poverty decline has not been higher in the post-reform period (since 1991){{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}. The improvements in some other non-economic dimensions of social development have been even less favourable. The most pronounced example is an exceptionally high and persistent level of child malnutrition (46% in 2005\u20136).<ref name=\"Chatterjee 2007\">CHATTERJEE, P. (2007): Child malnutrition rises in India despite economic boom. The\nLancet, 369, No. 9571, pp. 1417\u20131418.</ref>\n\nThe progress of economic reforms in India is followed closely. The [[World Bank]] suggests that the most important priorities are public sector reform, infrastructure, agricultural and rural development, removal of labour regulations, reforms in lagging states, and HIV/AIDS.<ref>[http://www.worldbank.org.in/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/COUNTRIES/SOUTHASIAEXT/INDIAEXTN/0,,contentMDK:20195738~menuPK:295591~pagePK:141137~piPK:141127~theSitePK:295584,00.html India Country Overview 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522115104/http://www.worldbank.org.in/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/COUNTRIES/SOUTHASIAEXT/INDIAEXTN/0%2C%2CcontentMDK%3A20195738~menuPK%3A295591~pagePK%3A141137~piPK%3A141127~theSitePK%3A295584%2C00.html |date=22 May 2011 }}. [[World Bank]]</ref> For 2018, India ranked 77th in [[Ease of Doing Business Index]]. According to [[Index of Economic Freedom]] World Ranking an annual survey on economic freedom of the nations, India ranks 123rd as compared with China and Russia which ranks 138th and 144th respectively in 2014.\n\nAt the turn of the century India's GDP was at around US$480 billion. As economic reforms picked up pace, India's GDP grew five-fold to reach US$2.2 trillion in 2015 (as per IMF estimates).\n\nIndia's GDP growth during January\u2013March period of 2015 was at 7.5% compared to China's 7%, making it the fastest growing economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rt.com/business/230915-india-china-world-economy/|title=New GDP calculation puts India growing faster than China|work=RT International|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150211164749/http://rt.com/business/230915-india-china-world-economy/|archivedate=11 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2015/02/11/its-official-india-has-passed-china-to-become-the-worlds-fastest-growing-economy/|title=India Passes China to Become Fastest-Growing Economy|author=Eric Bellman|work=WSJ|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813003622/https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2015/02/11/its-official-india-has-passed-china-to-become-the-worlds-fastest-growing-economy/|archivedate=13 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/Economy/india-pegs-201415-gdp-growth-at-74-per-cent/article6874926.ece|title=India fastest growing economy|author=Puja Mehra|work=The Hindu|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205011840/http://www.thehindu.com/business/Economy/india-pegs-201415-gdp-growth-at-74-per-cent/article6874926.ece|archivedate=5 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> During 2014\u201315, India's GDP growth recovered marginally to 7.3% from 6.9% in the previous fiscal. During 2014\u201315, India's services sector grew by 10.1%, manufacturing sector by 7.1% & agriculture by 0.2%. Indian Economy grew at 7.6 & 7.1 in FY 2015\u201316 and FY 2016\u201317 respectively as major reforms had  taken place like Demonitisation and implementation of GST in FY 2016\u201317.The Economic Growth has Been Slow Down in 2017\u201318 and it is expected to grow at 6.7 and forecasted to Rebound by 8.2% in 2018\u201319{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}.\n\n== History ==\nPrior to [[Independence Day (India)|India's Independence,]] from the period of 1900 to 1947, per capita income in India had either declined or stagnated. Post-Independence, [[Jawaharlal Nehru|Jawaharal Nehru]] enacted an economic policy based on [[import substitution industrialization]]. The Nehru-Mahalanobis approach, often referred to as the [[Five-Year Plans of India|Second Five Year Plan]], emphasized the development of basic and heavy industries as a means of accelerating economic growth. These included steel, copper, petrochemicals, paper, coal, and oil.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Nehru Mahalanobis Model|last=Bhatia|first=V.G.|date=1990|work=Economic and Political Weekly|jstor = 4396620}}</ref> [[Prasanta Chandra Mahalanobis|Mahalanobis]] strived for India to reach autonomy, ridding any outstanding debts. Critics disagreed with this approach, stating that [[World Bank|World Bank's]] claim of Indian export prospects being low were falsified and due to India's inward-looking strategy, the growth opportunity of the world economy was missed.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2015|title=Editorial Note|journal=Social Scientist|volume=43|issue=3/4|pages=1\u20132|issn=0970-0293|jstor=24372931}}</ref> Nonetheless, over 1950-1965, India's acceleration of per capita income growth had increased an average of 1.7%, a value not exceeded since.\n\nThe discourse on the efficacy of the Nehru-Mahalanobis Strategy is commonly contested by economists. A criticism of the approach emphasizes the lack of resource allocation in the agriculture sector. It is argued that the misbalanced weightage towards the machine-making sector contributed to the increase in food-grain prices and thus, perpetuated poverty and malnutrition.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Patnaik|first=Prabhat|date=March 2015|title=The Nehru\u2013Mahalanobis Strategy|journal=Social Scientist|volume=43|issue=3/4|pages=3\u201310|jstor=24372932}}</ref> Defenders of the strategy claim that it sought to increase agricultural output by increasing the [[Incremental capital-output ratio|output-capital ratio]]. This agreeably would have been accomplished through [[Land reform|land-reforms]], something the strategy did not address, not indicating a problem with the strategy itself.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Agriculture==\n{{main|Agriculture in India}}\n[[File:Composition of indias agricultural output in 2003-04.png|thumb|300px|Composition of India's total production of foodgrains and commercial crops, in 2003\u201304, by weight]]\nIndia [[List of countries by GDP sector composition|ranks second]] worldwide in farm output. Agriculture and allied sectors like [[forestry]], logging and fishing accounted for 18.6% of the GDP in 2005, employed 60% of the total workforce<ref name=\"CIA\">{{cite web\n |title       = CIA&nbsp;\u2014 The World Factbook&nbsp;\u2014 India\n |publisher   = CIA\n |date        = 20 September 2007\n |url         = https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/in.html#Econ\n |accessdate  = 2 October 2007\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080611033144/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/in.html#Econ\n |archivedate = 11 June 2008\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> and despite a steady decline of its share in the GDP, is still the largest economic sector and plays a significant role in the overall socio-economic development of India. [[Crop yield|Yields]] per unit area of all crops have grown since 1950, due to the special emphasis placed on agriculture in the [[Five-year plans of India#First Plan .281951-1956.29|five-year plan]]s and steady improvements in [[irrigation]], technology, application of modern agricultural practices and provision of agricultural credit and subsidies since the [[Green revolution in India|green revolution]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}}\n\nIndia is the largest producer in the world of milk, cashew nuts, coconuts, tea, ginger, turmeric and black pepper.<ref>[http://www.ibpn.co.uk/agriculture.asp Agriculture sector] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071226040933/http://www.ibpn.co.uk/agriculture.asp |date=26 December 2007 }} Indo British Partnership network, Retrieved on December 2007</ref> It also has the world's largest cattle population (193&nbsp;million).<ref>Lester R. Brown [http://www.earth-policy.org/Updates/Update6.htm World's Rangelands Deteriorating Under Mounting Pressure] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080311003923/http://www.earth-policy.org/Updates/Update6.htm |date=11 March 2008 }} Earth Policy Institute, Retrieved on- February 2008</ref> It is the second largest producer of wheat, rice, sugar, groundnut and inland fish.<ref name=\"agrind\">[http://www.ficciagroindia.com/indian-agriculture/indian-agriculture.htm Indian agriculture] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080225074057/http://www.ficciagroindia.com/indian-agriculture/indian-agriculture.htm |date=25 February 2008 }} Agribusiness Information Centre, Retrieved on- February 2008</ref> It is the third largest producer of tobacco.<ref name=\"agrind\"/> India accounts for 10% of the world fruit production with first rank in the production of banana and [[sapota]], also known as chiku.<ref name=\"agrind\"/>\n\nThe required level of investment for the development of marketing, storage and cold storage infrastructure is estimated to be huge. The government has implemented various schemes to raise investment in marketing infrastructure. Amongst these schemes are ''Construction of Rural Go downs'', ''Market Research and Information Network'', and ''Development / Strengthening of [[Agricultural Marketing]] Infrastructure, Grading and Standardisation''.<ref>[http://india.gov.in/sectors/agriculture/agri_marketing.php Agriculture marketing] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080205003341/http://india.gov.in/sectors/agriculture/agri_marketing.php |date=5 February 2008 }} india.gov Retrieved on- February 2008</ref>\n\nMain problems in the agricultural sector, as listed by the World Bank, are:<ref name=\"agriculturepriorities\">[http://web.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/COUNTRIES/SOUTHASIAEXT/EXTSAREGTOPAGRI/0,,contentMDK:20273764~menuPK:548214~pagePK:34004173~piPK:34003707~theSitePK:452766,00.html India: Priorities for Agriculture and Rural Development] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090121122011/http://web.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/COUNTRIES/SOUTHASIAEXT/EXTSAREGTOPAGRI/0,,contentMDK:20273764~menuPK:548214~pagePK:34004173~piPK:34003707~theSitePK:452766,00.html |date=21 January 2009 }}. [[World Bank]]</ref>\n* India's large [[agricultural subsidies]] are hampering productivity-enhancing investment.\n* Overregulation of agriculture has increased costs, price risks and uncertainty.\n* Government interventions in labour, land, and credit markets.\n* Inadequate infrastructure and services.\n\n===Research and  development===\nThe [[Indian Agricultural Research Institute]] (IARI), established in 1905, was responsible for the research leading to the \"[[Indian Green Revolution]]\" of the 1970s. The [[Indian Council of Agricultural Research]] (ICAR) is the apex body in kundiure and related allied fields, including research and education.<ref>[http://www.iari.res.in/objectives.php Objectives] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071024132458/http://www.iari.res.in/objectives.php |date=24 October 2007 }} Indian agricultural research institute, Retrieved on December 2007</ref> The Union Minister of Agriculture is the President of the ICAR. The [[Indian Agricultural Statistics Research Institute]] develops new techniques for the design of agricultural experiments, analyses data in agriculture, and specialises in statistical techniques for animal and plant breeding.\nProf. [[M.S. Swaminathan]] is known as \"Father of the Green Revolution\" and heads the MS Swaminathan Research Foundation.<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/asia/asia/magazine/1999/990823/swaminathan1.html MS Swaminathan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080114015753/http://www.time.com/time/asia/asia/magazine/1999/990823/swaminathan1.html |date=14 January 2008 }} Times Inc. Retrieved on- 21 February 2008</ref> He is known for his advocacy of environmentally [[sustainable agriculture]] and sustainable [[food security]].\n\n==Industrial output==\n[[File:India industry.jpg|thumb|An industrial zone near [[Mumbai]]]]\nIndia is [[List of countries by GDP sector composition|tenth]] in the world in factory output. Manufacturing sector in addition to mining, [[quarrying]], electricity and gas together account for 27.6% of the GDP and employ 17% of the total workforce. Economic reforms introduced after 1991 brought foreign competition, led to privatisation of certain public sector industries, opened up sectors hitherto reserved for the public sector and led to an expansion in the production of fast-moving [[Final goods|consumer goods]]. In recent years, Indian cities have continued to liberalise, but excessive and burdensome business regulations remain a problem in some cities, like Kochi and Kolkata.<ref name=\"World Bank and International Financial Corporation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.doingbusiness.org/subnational/exploreeconomies/India2009.aspx|title=Doing Business in India 2009|publisher=[[World Bank]]|accessdate=8 June 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101007005506/http://doingbusiness.org/subnational/exploreeconomies/India2009.aspx|archivedate=7 October 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nPost-liberalisation, the Indian private sector, which was usually run by oligopolies of old family firms and required political connections to prosper was faced with foreign competition, including the threat of cheaper Chinese imports. It has since handled the change by squeezing costs, revamping management, focusing on designing new products and relying on low labour costs and [[technology]].<ref name=\"compete\">{{cite news|title=Indian manufacturers learn to compete |date=12 February 2004 |work=The Economist |url=http://economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=S%27%298%3C%2FPQ%3B%21%21P%214%0A |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://wayback.vefsafn.is/wayback/20071213195957/http://economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=S%27%298%3C%2FPQ%3B%21%21P%214%0A |archivedate=13 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nIndia [[List of countries by GDP sector composition|is fifteenth]] in services output. [[Tertiary sector of economic activity|Service industry]] employ [[Indian English|English-speaking Indian]] workers on the [[Supply and demand|supply side]] and on the demand side, has increased demand from foreign consumers interested in India's service exports or those looking to outsource their operations. [[Indian IT industry|India's IT industry]], despite contributing significantly to its [[balance of payments]], accounts for only about 1% of the total GDP or 1/50th of the total services.<ref name=\"Revolution\">{{cite journal|author1=Gordon, Jim|author2=Gupta, Poonam|title=Understanding India's Services Revolution|year=2003|version=12 November 2003|url=http://www.imf.org/external/np/apd/seminars/2003/newdelhi/gordon.pdf|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326211643/http://www.imf.org/external/np/apd/seminars/2003/newdelhi/gordon.pdf|archivedate=26 March 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring the Internet bubble that led up to 2000, heavy investments in undersea fibre-optic cables linked Asia with the rest of the world. The fall that followed the economic boom resulted in the auction of cheap fiber optic cables at one-tenth of their original price. This development resulted in widely available low-cost communications [[infrastructure]]. All of these investments and events, not to mention a swell of available talent, resulted in India becoming almost overnight the centre for outsourcing of Business process.<ref>What's Next for the Startup nation {{cite web|url=http://www.startup-nation.com/the-book/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-08-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120819031009/http://startup-nation.com/the-book/ |archivedate=19 August 2012 }}</ref> Within this sector and events, the [[ITES]]-[[Business process outsourcing|BPO]] sector has become a big employment generator especially amongst young college graduates. The number of professionals employed by IT and ITES sectors is estimated at around 1.3&nbsp;million as of March 2006. Also, Indian IT-ITES is estimated to have helped create an additional 3 million job opportunities through indirect, induced and in helpful manner have created employment.<ref>[http://india.gov.in/sectors/communication/ites_bpo.php ITES and BPO Services] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213174333/http://india.gov.in/sectors/communication/ites_bpo.php |date=13 February 2008 }} india.gov Retrieved on- February 2008</ref>\n\n==GDP growth rate==\nSince the economic liberalisation of 1991, India's GDP has been growing at a higher rate.<ref name=\"GDP growth\">[http://www.indexmundi.com/g/g.aspx?v=66&c=in&l=en India&nbsp;\u2013 GDP&nbsp;\u2013 real growth rate (%)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305185731/http://www.indexmundi.com/g/g.aspx?v=66&c=in&l=en |date=5 March 2012 }}.</ref> The following table has been collected from public data archives<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG?end=2017&locations=IN&start=2000|title=GDP growth (annual %) {{!}} Data|website=data.worldbank.org|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref> with data from the [[World Bank]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Growth (real) (%)\n|-\n| 2000 || 3.841\n|-\n| 2001 || 4.824\n|-\n| 2002 || 3.804\n|-\n| 2003 || 7.86\n|-\n| 2004 || 7.923\n|-\n| 2005 || 7.923\n|-\n| 2006 || 8.061\n|-\n| 2007 || 7.661\n|-\n| 2008 || 3.087\n|-\n| 2009 || 7.862\n|-\n| 2010 || 8.498\n|-\n| 2011 || 5.241\n|-\n| 2012 || 5.456\n|-\n| 2013 || 6.386\n|-\n| 2014 || 7.41\n|-\n| 2015 || 7.996\n|-\n| 2016 || 8.17\n|-\n| 2017\n|7.168\n|-\n| 2018\n|6.982\n|}\n\nGDP growth rate is unequal within India. For the year 2015\u201316, GDP growth rates of [[Andhra Pradesh]] (10.99%), [[Bihar]] (10.27%) and [[Madhya Pradesh]] (10.16%) were higher than [[Maharashtra]] (8%), [[Odisha]] (6.16%) and [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] (5.96%).<ref>{{cite news |title=AP stands 1st in India in GSDP growth rate |url=http://m.timesofindia.com/city/hyderabad/AP-stands-1st-in-India-in-GSDP-growth-rate/articleshow/52709609.cms |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |accessdate=5 April 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170604195054/http://m.timesofindia.com/city/hyderabad/AP-stands-1st-in-India-in-GSDP-growth-rate/articleshow/52709609.cms |archivedate=4 June 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Companies==\n47 Indian companies were listed in the [[Forbes Global 2000]] ranking for 2015.<ref name=\"fg2-2007\">{{cite news|title = Forbes Global 2000 (Ger-Ind)|url = https://www.forbes.com/global2000/list/|accessdate = 22 July 2015|url-status = live|archiveurl = http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20150408120044/https://www.forbes.com/global2000/list/|archivedate = 8 April 2015|df = dmy-all}}</ref> The 10 leading companies were:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n!World Rank !! Company !! class=\"unsortable\"|Logo !! Industry !! Revenue <br /> (billion $) !! Profits  <br /> (billion $) !! Assets  <br /> (billion $) !! Market Value  <br /> (billion $)\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|142 || align=\"left\" | [[Reliance Industries]] || align=\"center\" |   || align=\"left\" | Oil & Gas Operations || 71.7 ||  3.7    ||  76.6    || 42.9\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|152 || align=\"left\" | [[State Bank of India]] || align=\"center\" | [[File:SBI-logo.svg|40px|State Bank of India logo]] || align=\"left\"|Banking || 40.8 ||  2.3    ||  400.